<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HotelFire     07-29 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out At Retirement Hotel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out at a downtown retirement hotel
Friday, forcing the evacuation of about 150 residents as flames
shot out of the top floor and roof of the six-story building,
authorities said.
   Nine of the elderly occupants of the Maryland Hotel were taken
to hospitals for treatment of minor symptoms ranging from smoke
inhalation to chest pains, said fire Capt. Richard McDowell.
   Hotel resident Wayne Huffman, 60, said he was standing in the
lobby shortly before 5 p.m. when he heard a hotel employee shout a
warning.
   ``The desk clerk came running up, yelling `The building's on
fire! The building's on fire!'''
   ``It was such a small fire,'' said Huffman. ``No one took it
seriously until we saw the smoke. Now here we are, out on the
street.''
   The blaze broke out during the commuter rush hour, drawing a
large crowd of spectators and snarling traffic. Hotel residents
were among the onlookers, some sitting in wooden chairs across the
street from the burning building.
   More than 75 firefighters were called to the scene and several
city blocks were cordoned off. They remained closed at 7 p.m. as
firefighters mopped up the blaze, which was confined to the sixth
floor.
   ``We don't have anything on cause or point of origin yet,''
McDowell said. He estimated 150 people were evacuated, including
two people who were rescued from the top floor by an
aerial-platform atop a firetruck ladder.
   ``Structurally, the building is sound,'' McDowell said. ``A wing
of the sixth floor was gutted,'' McDowell said, but firefighters
hoped residents of unaffected floors might return home later Friday
night, he said.
   Salvation Army officials were arranging hotel rooms for those
who needed them.
</TEXT>
