<1ST_LINE>u a AM-People-Cher     07-29 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Cher,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographer Sues Actress, Her Boyfriend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Cher and her 24-year-old
boyfriend, Robert Camilletti, were sued Friday by a free-lance
photographer who alleges Camilletti tried to run him down with
Cher's sports car.
   The lawsuit, filed in Los Angeles County Superior Court, alleges
Cher was negligent by entrusting her Ferrari to Camilletti, and
accuses him of assault and battery on photographer Peter Brandt.
   In addition, Brandt is suing for emotional distress from the
accident Wednesday in front of Cher's Benedict Canyon home. The
sports car driven by Camilletti hit Brandt's Honda Accord, damaging
both vehicles.
   ``He chased him and said he was going to kill him,'' said
Brandt's attorney, Ron Carpol.
   Cher and Camilletti have blamed the accident on the tabloid
press and the frustration of dealing with paparazzi who incessantly
stake out their home.
   Camilletti was arrested Wednesday and booked for investigation
of felony assault with a deadly weapon. He has denied allegations
that he was trying to run down Brandt.
   Camilletti said in a statement prepared by his lawyer that he
had hoped to avoid the photographer's stakeout by swerving the car
into the Cher's driveway.
   The Oscar-winning actress, 42, and Camilletti have been
companions since meeting at a New York nightclub on her 40th
birthday. Marriage plans have been denied repeatedly by Cher's
publicist Lois Smith.
   A former bagel maker, pizza chef and bartender, Camilletti is
now pursuing an acting career and he recently completed shooting of
``Loverboy'' with Kate Jackson and Kirstie Alley.
</TEXT>
