<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0773 07-29 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0773 ,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Stocks Rise for Fifth Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with closing stocks</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices surged Saturday on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange for the fifth straight day of gains and a closing level
that topped 28,000 points for the first time since mid-July.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 115.54-point
winner Friday, advanced 288.31 points, or 1.02 percent, to close
Saturday's half-day session at 28,199.94.
   The Nikkei index, the most widely followed market barometer,
briefly hovered above 28,000 points in early trading Friday. But
Saturday's closing represented the first time the index has
finished above the 28,000 level since July 15.
   Volume on the first section was a heavy 700 million shares.
   Shinji Shihara of Okasan Securities said the Tokyo market was
taking a cue from sharp advances on Wall Street overnight.
   ``It's the fifth straight day of gains, but the market is really
moving up in reaction to New York trading.''
   The upsurge in shares prices has also been attributed to a
strong U.S. currency and reduced concern over growing inflation.
   ``It's not just the bullish London and New York market, but
we've got positive economic factors here (in Japan) along with a
strong dollar and less concern about inflation,'' said an analyst
with Nikko Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shihara said light electricals like Sony were being sought along
with heavy electricals, financials and automakers on the first
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The Tokyo foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
