<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eastern-Machinists     07-29 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Machinists,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Files Suit to Block Eastern Cutbacks in Service, Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union representing 12,000 Eastern Airlines
employees seeks to block the carrier from eliminating service in 14
cities in a lawsuit that contends the cutbacks will eventually
destroy the company.
   The suit requests a preliminary injunction or temporary
restraining order against the cutbacks in service, scheduled to
take effect Aug. 31. Eastern announced the changes, along with a
work force reduction of 4,000, last Friday.
   Unless the cutbacks are blocked, the suit says, Eastern will
``embark on a program that will significantly increase its
recurring losses and lead to the ultimate destruction of the
carrier.''
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers filed the suit Thursday in U.S. District Court for the
District of Columbia. The union represents Eastern mechanics and
ground workers.
   Charles Bryan, president of the Machinists local in Miami, said
the union will argue that Eastern's reduction in service benefits
Continental Airlines. Both companies are subsidiaries of Texas Air
Corp. of Houston.
   ``This is an act of self-help,'' Bryan said at a news
conference. ``It's not too different from a lockout, quite
frankly.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the airline has ``taken
these actions because they're in the best interests of the company,
and we expect that the court will agree with us.''
   Eastern's cutbacks mean an 11.4 percent reduction in daily
flights. The financially struggling company said the move would
permit it to concentrate on serving cities where it is strongest.
</TEXT>
