<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Clinton 2ndLd-Writethru a0416 07-29 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clinton, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0416,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Getting Mileage out of Publicity Over Bad Speech</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 7th graf `The governor' to add that
Clinton played sax with orchestra.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As sand trickled through an hourglass on
Johnny Carson's desk, Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton admitted to
``Tonight Show'' viewers that his comically savaged speech at the
Democratic convention did not go as planned.
   ``My sole goal was achieved, however. I wanted so badly to make
Dukakis look great, and I succeeded beyond my wildest dreams,''
said Clinton, to the laughter and applause of the show's studio
audience.
   Clinton delivered the nominating speech for Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis at last week's Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta. Allotted 15 minutes, Clinton spoke for 32 minutes,
ignoring flashing red lights and other attempts to cut him off.
Finally, Clinton's line ``I want to say, in closing'' drew applause.
   Carson told the audience in his monologue that Clinton was to be
a guest, and added: ``Not to worry we have plenty of black coffee
and extra cots in the lobby.''
   Carson introduced Clinton with a satirical, long-winded speech
of his own that included details ranging from the governor's
educational background.
   After Clinton sat on the couch, Carson said, ``My first question
is, how are you?'' then turned over the hourglass.
   The governor said that while his speech was ridiculed, his
constituents continued to support him. He said the speech was a
``good idea that didn't work.''
   Clinton tried a different approach to win over Carson's
audience, playing a tenor saxophone with the show's orchestra.
   Clinton's appearance on the Carson show was his latest attempt
to use humor to keep the disastrous speech from ruining his image
as a rising star in the Democratic Party. The governor, who
previously had a reputation as a good orator, began polishing his
quips in Little Rock shortly after the convention speech was over:
   ``It wasn't my finest hour,'' went one line. ``It wasn't even my
finest hour and one-half.''
   During a speech this week to about 150 educators, Clinton had
trouble with his microphone. Without skipping a beat, he said,
``Have the networks taken control of the mikes?''
   On Wednesday at the Capitol, Little Rock activist and
restaurateur Robert ``Say'' McIntosh dished up food for anyone
willing to dish out criticism for the Clinton bashers.
   Diners earned a free meal with lines such as:
   ``Bill Clinton may be a blabbermouth, but he's the best thing to
happen to Arkansas.''
   ``I appreciate my governor even if he is boring.''
   On Thursday, the Arkansas Democrat carried Clinton and Carson in
its editorial page comic strip ``Spanks.''
   The first frame shows Carson introducing Clinton with, ``Now
here's a man who was a miniseries unto himself _ ``Gone with the
windbag''_ Arkansas' TALK of the town _ Governor Clinton.''
   Clinton appears in the second frame in the image of comedian
Rodney Dangerfield saying, ``Hey, Johnny, I tell yuh, I don't get
no respect.''
   The last frame shows Clinton finishing his monologue, ``When I
was speaking at the convention, one delegate accidentally hit
another delegate with his sign.
   ``Oh excuse me!'' said the first delegate. ``I hit you with my
sign.''
   ``Hit me again,'' said the second delegate. ``I can still hear
him.''
   The Arkansas Gazette, on its op-ed page, carried a 13-paragraph
story by a retired newspaper editor who urged Clinton not to let TV
people get under his skin.
   ``If they were all as smart as they sometimes pretend to be,
surely some of them would be out there where the really big money
is _ selling red neckties to the people who are on television,''
wrote John E. Pruniski.
   Clinton, first elected governor in 1978 at the age of 32, met
Dukakis while serving as president of the National Governor's
Association last year and eventually landed a major role in
Dukakis' campaign as an adviser and sometime stand-in. Clinton, who
at one time flirted with the idea of running for president, was
among those talked of as a possible Dukakis running mate.
</TEXT>
