<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Israel     07-29 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Israel,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Delegation Makes First Trip Since Relations Broken In 1967</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Reforms, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Israelis on the first diplomatic mission to
Moscow since the Kremlin broke diplomatic relations with the Jewish
state in 1967 say they want to review procedures for Soviet Jews
who want to leave.
   The Israeli diplomats planned to pray in Moscow's central
synagogue on the Jewish Sabbath, which begins this evening.
   Officially, the Israelis came Thursday to inspect the embassy
building on Bolshaya Ordynka Street. Israel has been paying the
Soviets $100,000 a year to rent the building and diplomats from the
Netherlands have been taking care of it.
   But the focus of the Israelis' visit is another role the Dutch
have been performing for the Israeli government _ the processing of
requests by Soviet Jews for Israeli visas.
   Meron Gordon, head of the delegation and a counselor at his
country's embassy in Rome, said his group might meet with prominent
Jewish refuseniks who have been denied permission by Soviet
authorities to leave the country.
   From January to June, 6,017 Soviet Jews emigrated, but only a
small fraction went to Israel. Last year, the Soviet Union allowed
8,011 Jews to emigrate.
   Four of the diplomats were born in the Soviet Union. Gordon left
in 1957 at the age of 10.
   ``I think you have an expression _ butterflies in the stomach,''
he said at Sheremetyevo airport after the group arrived from
Amsterdam. ``The ones I have in my stomach are very big.''
   Gordon said he hopes the visit is ``the first step in developing
the process of improving relations between the states of Israel and
the Soviet Union.''
   But Kremlin officials stress that the visit is not a precursor
to the restoration of diplomatic relations, broken off after Israel
seized lands from Egypt, Jordan and Syria during the 1967 Middle
East War.
   The Soviet visas the delegation received in the Netherlands
entitle them to a two-month stay in the Soviet Union.
   The Kremlin says it won't restore relations until Israel
withdraws from the occupied territories and agrees to an
international Middle East peace conference.
   Israel insisted the Kremlin allow its representatives to visit
in exchange for permission for a Soviet consular delegation to
visit the Jewish state. Eight Soviet diplomats have been in Israel
since last July to survey Russian Orthodox Church property and meet
with Soviet citizens living there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
