<DOCNO> AP880729-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugTesting     07-29 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Air Controllers' Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has upheld a Reagan
administration program of drug testing for air traffic controllers,
saying they ``have the lives of thousands of people in their
hands.''
   U.S. District Judge John Vukasin's ruling was the first in favor
of a drug testing program by a judge in the federal court here,
where labor groups have filed most of their suits attacking the
administration's plans for urine testing of federal employees.
   An appeal of the ruling is expected.
   Another federal judge in San Francisco has struck down a testing
program for all federal prison workers, and the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, which covers California and eight other Western
states, has ruled against mandatory testing of railroad crews after
accidents and rule violations. The latter decision has been
accepted for review by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Vukasin announced his ruling July 19 but has not yet issued it
in written form. A transcript of his comments was made available to
reporters Thursday.
   The lawsuit, like those against other drug programs, contended
random drug testing is unconstitutional because it is not based on
individual suspicion of impairment from current drug use. The suit
also argued that drug testing was unreliable and would be
ineffective in promoting safety.
   The judge said he was unimpressed by statistics showing that
less than 1 percent of air traffic controllers had shown signs of
drug use in testing so far.
   ``We are talking here about air traffic controllers who have the
lives of thousands of people in their hands,'' Vukasin said.
   In response to arguments that drug testing doesn't show whether
an employee is currently impaired or under the influence, Vukasin
said, ``Unfortunately, the state of the art has not reached that
level. But that is not an argument of why what at least is
available to the (Federal Aviation Administration) should not be
exercised and utilized.''
   Apparently referring to the ruling on railroad workers, he said
he ``may be failing to follow precedents, but if so, it is not done
out of disrespect.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     07-29 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Program to Remain Unchanged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No major adjustments because of this year's
drought are in the works for the Agriculture Department's 1989
wheat acreage program.
   Winter wheat producers soon will be planting next year's crop,
and the no-change announcement Thursday by Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng helps clear the way. All they need now is rain.
   As it stands now, wheat farmers will have to idle 10 percent of
their base acreage in 1989 to qualify for federal price supports,
the same as announced last spring.
   The 10 percent acreage reduction for next year was announced on
May 25, under 1985 farm law which requires a determination for the
following year's crop prior to June 1. That was before the drought
became so widespread and severe.
   ``Even though the severe drought has reduced wheat production,
especially that of spring wheat, the prospective supply-demand
balance (for the coming year) does not call for a change in the
previously announced wheat acreage reduction program in 1989,''
Lyng, who was out of town, said in a statement.
   A crop projection issued on July 12 put the 1988 wheat crop at
1.84 billion bushels, down from 2.12 billion bushels forecast in
June. The 1987 harvest was about 2.1 billion bushels.
   But U.S. wheat inventories have been large, despite a heavy
export drain, and totaled around 1.27 billion bushels on June 1,
the beginning of the 1988-89 wheat marketing year. The smaller
harvest will result in a further reduction in the stockpile to
around 666 million bushels by June 1, 1989, according to the
projections.
   Earlier, the June 1, 1989, wheat carryover was forecast at 781
million bushels.
   Winter wheat, which comprises about three-fourths of the U.S.
total, will be planted this fall for harvest next year. Spring
wheat, including durum used for pasta, is produced farther north
and bore the brunt of this summer's drought damage to the wheat
crop.
   In a related development, officials served notice that wheat
export subsidies are continuing, despite the drought and reduction
in wheat supplies.
   Melvin E. Sims, general manager for the department's Foreign
Agricultural Service, said China has bought an additional 400,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   The sales, equal to about 14.7 million bushels, were handled by
two companies: Cargill Inc., 200,000 tons, and Ferruzzi USA Inc.,
200,000 tons.
   Sims said the sales were part of an authorized 2 million tons of
wheat announced April 5 under the Export Enhancement Program, or
EEP, and some left over from an earlier authorization.
   Although no selling prices or other details were announced,
recent wheat prices at farm points have averaged around $3.46 per
bushel, indicating a U.S. farm value of about $50 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Prior to the new authorization on April 5, China had bought 4.9
million tons of wheat under EEP subsidy arrangements. Sims said
China has 610,000 tons still available for use.
   Under the program, exporters can sell U.S. commodities at
reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sims said the bonuses due the four companies averaged $9.84 per
ton of wheat, or about 27 cents a bushel. The bonuses will be paid
in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's
Commodity Credit Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought may be gnawing at the bank accounts of
many farmers, but the hot, dry weather isn't expected to cut back
on their spending for many production items this year, according to
an Agriculture Department report.
   ``The drought is expected to have little impact on 1988
expenditures for seed, fertilizer and pesticides because most of
these ... were applied at or before planting,'' the report by the
department's Economic Research Service said Thursday. ``Farm
machinery expenditures are projected to increase again in 1988 but
could be slowed by the drought.''
   Spending on the fuel and electricity needed to run farms will be
affected significantly by the drought, however.
   ``Energy expenditures for irrigation will be up, but likely will
be more than offset by decreased outlays for harvesting and
drying,'' the report said, a grim reminder that reduced yields _ or
none at all _ mean it will cost less to run grain combines and
dryers.
   Spending on farm machinery increased $1.2 billion to $5.8
billion in 1987, ending seven years of decline, the report said.
   Net cash income of farmers _ the difference between gross cash
receipts and cash expenses _ rose to a record $56 billion in
calendar 1987. Current USDA forecasts put 1988 net cash income at
$53 billion to $59 billion.
</TEXT>
