<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish Stowaway, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0803,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Stowaway Tells Judge She Yearns for Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to UPDATE with departure for Ireland. Picks up
4th graf pvs `The girl...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos RA1, NY53</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish girl who crossed the Atlantic as a
stowaway on a Navy destroyer told a judge Thursday she yearns for
her homeland, and her mother said the family might seek legal
action against the U.S. government.
   ``I just want to go home,'' 16-year-old Suzanne Twomey of Cork
told Wake County District Court Judge Fred Morelock. The judge put
her in custody of two Naval Investigative Service agents who were
escorting her.
   Miss Twomey was put on a flight to New York's John F. Kennedy
International Airport, and left from there at 10:45 p.m. on a
flight to Shannon, Ireland.
   The girl apparently slipped aboard the USS Conyngham while it
was on a courtesy call in Cork Harbor. She was discovered aboard
the guided missile destroyer Saturday when it returned to its
Norfolk, Va., base.
   Three officers searched the ship after hearing a girl was aboard
and found her in a 2{-foot-wide, 15-foot-long, 3-foot-high
compartment above a refrigeration unit.
   Five sailors accused of helping the girl were being held at the
Norfolk Naval base, authorities said. If charged and convicted,
they face a maximum five years in prison and a fine of $2,000 for
aiding an illegal entry into the United States.
   Meanwhile, Miss Twomey's parents said they are considering suing
the U.S. government.
   ``There is a lot more to this than meets the eye,'' said
Christine Twomey. Mrs. Twomey said U.S. officials had telephoned
her in Ireland to apologize.
   They said her daughter could not have boarded the ship
undetected without help from crew members, Mrs. Twomey said.
   In court Thursday, Miss Twomey listened intently as Assistant
District Attorney J. Franklin Jackson told the judge she was a
runaway and would be considered an undisciplined child under the
American court system.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Rocco J. de Grasse said no charges would
be filed against Miss Twomey.
   After the hearing, deGrasse approached Miss Twomey and gave her
a stern lecture. He said her status as a juvenile had protected
her, but that she had committed a serious offense.
   A Delta Airlines flight carrying the girl to Atlanta for a
connecting flight home was diverted to Raleigh on Tuesday when she
became sick. She was released Wednesday night from Rex Hospital,
said Mary West, a nursing supervisor who did not know what the girl
was treated for.
   Bill Berry, a Delta spokesman in Atlanta, said the Navy had
asked Wednesday night about booking the girl on another Delta
flight to Ireland, but the airline refused her passage because of
possible medical problems.
</TEXT>
