<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Afghanistan     07-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Afghanistan,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pressing Soviets for Afghan Mine Maps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. interagency team is meeting daily in
Washington to plan for what is expected to be one of the largest
refugee migrations in this century, the return of exiled Afghans to
their homeland.
   The refugees are expected to include some 3 million in Pakistan
and another 2.2 million exiled in Iran. There are also between 1
million and 3 million Afghans still inside their country but who
have been displaced by the anti-Soviet guerrilla war.
   As part of the repatriation planning, the United States is
pressing the Soviet Union for maps showing the locations of land
mines scattered by Soviet troops throughout Afghanistan, a top
State Department official said Thursday.
   At the same time, Pakistan's foreign minister, in a meeting with
Secretary of State George Shultz, allayed concerns that the Soviet
Union was reneging on its timetable for withdrawing troops from
Afghanistan. ``This impression has just been dispelled,'' Sahabzada
Yaqub Khan said.
   Shultz, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and Yaqub Khan are
comparing notes on how to monitor the Soviet withdrawal _ and on
Afghanistan's future after the troops are gone.
   One of the immediate problems is the land mines. A team of
Defense Department experts recently visited Pakistan to assess the
extent of the mine problem across the border in Afghanistan, said a
senior official involved in the refugee repatriation effort. The
official asked not to be identified.
   The official said the Pentagon team recommended that Afghan
refugees be taught how to recognize mines so they do not
inadvertently step on them, and that some of them be trained to
deactivate the explosive devices.
   ``They have to be trained in mine awareness. They'll have to
live with it for decades,'' he said.
   Some refugees returning to the town of Barikot stepped on mines
in recent weeks, and word of the danger spread among the refugee
camps in Pakistan.
   U.S. officials say it is difficult to determine just how many
mines are strewn around the rugged Afghan countryside because many
of the devices were dropped out of helicopters rather than
methodically sown. Estimates vary from 5 million to 30 million.
   ``We're telling them (the Soviets) that they're responsible for
the devastation, and the least they can do is help with maps,''
said the State Department official. The Soviets have said they
removed most of the mines and that the remaining ones were planted
by the U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting the Soviets.
   ``That's just false,'' the U.S. official said.
</TEXT>
