<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andy Mill says he used to enjoy watching
television broadcasts of Chris Evert's tennis matches and wanted to
meet her even though ``celebrities and athletes are a dime a
dozen.''
   On Saturday, the former Olympic skier plans to marry the tennis
star at a ceremony attended by about 100 family members and
friends, including tennis stars Martina Navratilova and Pam Shriver
and actress Lynda Carter.
   When Mill first saw Evert in person on New Year's Eve in Aspen,
Colo., nearly 19 months ago, he said he fell in love.
   ``I was really curious about who this person was because, well,
celebrities and athletes are a dime a dozen,'' said Mill.
   Both Evert and Mill were ending eight-year marriages when they
met.
   Evert, 33, who was married to British tennis star John Lloyd,
has won three Wimbledon championships, six U.S. Opens and seven
French Opens. Mill, 35, placed sixth in the 1976 Olympic downhill
competition and 18th in the 1980 games.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author James A. Michener,
who has been living in nearby Coral Gables for two years while
researching a book on the Caribbean, has been named grand marshal
of the 1988 Orange Bowl parade.
   ``He will be a great drawing card, besieged for autographs,''
Jim Barker, president of the Orange Bowl Committee, said Thursday.
   Michener, a visiting professor at the University of Miami, has
written 34 books, including the 868-page bestseller ``Alaska.'' His
1947 work ``Tales of the South Pacific'' won a Pulitzer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moody Blues has begun a nationwide tour to
mark the 20th anniversary of the English band's first U.S. tour.
   ``Our major success has been in America. A lot of Americans
think we are American,'' lead singer Justin Hayward said in an
interview Wednesday. ``We came here in 1968 when we had nothing
else going for us anywhere else.''
   Today their fame spans two generations.
   The Moody Blues, whose 1968 album ``Days of Future Passed''
pioneered the orchestrated rock 'n' roll album, get letters from
10-year-olds who are fans of their latest hit, ``I Know You're Out
There Somewhere.''
   Flutist Ray Thomas and drummer Graeme Edge are the only original
members from the group's 1964 start in Birmingham, England. The
current tour began here Wednesday night at the Kings Island
amusement park.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven years ago this month, singer
Tony Orlando stunned his audience and his two partners when he
walked out in the middle of a performance.
   On Tuesday night, Orlando and Dawn reunited on stage at Trump
Plaza Hotel and Casino, where they will continue through tonight.
   Two months ago Orlando took the first step toward an on-stage
reconciliation with the two performers who comprised Dawn _ Telma
Hopkins and Joyce Vincent Wilson. He telephoned Ms. Hopkins and
asked her point-blank if she would consider a limited tour.
   Ms. Hopkins did not hesitate to answer. ``Let's do it,'' she
said.
   When the trio started rehearsing, Wilson said, ``It was like
we'd never stopped singing.''
   Among the group's million-selling hits from 1970 to 1977 were
``Candida,'' ``Knock Three Times'' and ``Tie A Yellow Ribbon
('Round The Old Oak Tree).''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Robert Urich is upset that his fame
is being used to promote the sale of a house he rented briefly.
   ``It's unethical, un-neighborly and dishonest because I was
never told about the ad and I never considered it my house,'' said
Urich, star of the former ``Spenser: For Hire'' TV series.
   Urich, 41, his wife and their two children rented the 11-room
English Tudor house for $4,000 a month between October 1986 and
July 1987 while waiting for their own home to be remodeled.
   Newspaper advertisements by Saperstein Company Auctioneers of
Boston state: ``11-room luxury home in Andover, formerly rented by
actor Robert Urich, star of `Spenser: For Hire.'''
   Douglas Ahern, the real estate developer who owns the house,
said he's surprised Urich is upset and that no offense was meant.
   ``Real estate agents in Beverly Hills can sell a house that Rock
Hudson lived in for two months and they call it Rock Hudson's
house,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael G. Gartner, a former newspaper editor
named as the new president of NBC News, gave the network's news
staff and affiliates a good-natured tweak as he introduced himself
to them.
   ``My favorite network is the BBC,'' Gartner said Thursday in a
closed-circuit broadcast to NBC employees and affiliates, ``and I
think if we just had somebody standing there reading the news, and
could get rid of all this film and everything, it would be far more
palatable.''
   Just kidding, he added.
   ``I happen to think that in Tom Brokaw and in all the producers
here, we have the greatest news organization in the world,''
Gartner said.
   Gartner, 49, was appointed Wednesday to replace Lawrence K.
Grossman, who stepped down after four years as head of the news
division. Gartner was formerly editor of the Des Moines (Iowa)
Register and The Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky., and a general
executive of Gannett Co. Inc.
