<DOCNO> AP880729-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Cabinet     07-29 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Cabinet,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Ministers Quit in Constitutional Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cabinet ministers joined a third
colleague and quit in a growing dispute over the nation's proposed
constitution, a presidential aide said.
   Culture Minister Celso Furtado and Science and Technology
Minister Luiz Henrique da Silveira handed in their resignations
Thursday, said a presidential aide who spoke on condition of
anonymity. He said he did not know why they had resigned.
   Renato Archer, the Social Welfare minister, quit Wednesday.
   The resignations came after President Jose Sarney on Tuesday
attacked the constitution, proposed by lawmakers after 18 months of
work, as ``chaotic.'' He said it could make Brazil impossible to
govern.
   Despite Sarney's broadcast, legislators overwhelmingly approved
the rough draft of the new constitution late Wednesday.
   The document includes proposals to limit annual interest rates
to 12 percent, to give Brazilians control of all mining operations,
to cut the voting age from 18 to 16, and to grant the unrestricted
right to strike and a six-hour work day.
   
   The three ministers' resignations deepened a split between the
president and Ulysses Guimaraes, the powerful speaker of the House
of Representatives and president of the 559-member Constitutional
Assembly.
   All three ministers are close personal friends of Guimaraes, who
responded to Sarney's criticisms with a sharply-worded defense of
the assembly's work.
   Tuesday's broadcast was Sarney's last-ditch attempt to remove
several proposals from the new document that will replace a 1969
constitution handed down by military generals. The military has
raised objections to the constitution.
   Lawmakers now can amend the document in a second round of voting
expected to end in September.
   Agrarian Reform Minister Jader Barbalho will be the new Social
Welfare minister, the presidential spokesman said. Education
Minister Hugo Napoleao will head the Culture Ministry, and the
Technology Ministry will be headed by Luiz Rico Vicente.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
