<DOCNO> AP880729-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Mandela     07-29 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Mandela,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Guts Mandela Home; Teen Rivalry Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire that destroyed the
home of imprisoned black leader Nelson Mandela was prompted by a
dispute between black teen-age groups and was not aimed at Mandela
himself, sources said.
   Police said as many as 50 black high school students stoned the
house, doused it with gasoline and set it ablaze Thursday. No one
was hurt and no arrests were made, they said.
   Neighbors and black journalists, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said some attackers wore jackets of Daliwonga high
school in Soweto and were involved in a dispute Wednesday with
young blacks who guard the home.
   Mandela's wife, Winnie, a prominent anti-apartheid activist, was
bound for a news conference concerning detainees when she learned
of the fire. Her daughter, Zindzi, 27, and her two grandchildren,
who also live at the four-room home, were away at the time.
   State of emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest and a range of statements classified as subversive.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, said leaders in Soweto and other black
townships had been asked ``to call upon the community not to act
emotionally so they do not create a situation where there is a
spiral of violence.''
   He leaders would try to talk to the principal and the students
of the school involved to ease the situation. He said young men who
congregate around the Mandela home were told ``not to act without
thinking or with revenge.''
   Mrs. Mandela arrived by car about an hour later and viewed the
blackened windows and burned furniture in the yard from inside the
car. She then was driven to her nearby offices where she conducts
social welfare projects.
   Youths who guarded the house, some wearing jackets of the
Mandela United soccer club sponsored by the family, pushed
journalists away from the office. One threatened to burn a
photographer's car.
   Later, attorney Amrichand Soma told reporters Mandela was
reached at Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town, where he is serving a
life term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the
white-dominated government, and said no statement should be made.
   For Mrs. Mandela, the fire was one of many hardships since her
husband, a leader of the outlawed African National Congress, was
jailed in 1962. Mandela, 70, received a life sentence in 1964 after
being convicted of plotting a sabotage campaign to overthrow the
white-led government.
   Mrs. Mandela, 54, has spent 17 months in solitary confinement,
lived in isolation, been arrested several times and passed
virtually her entire adult life under stringent police restrictions
and public scrutiny.
   She was trained as a social worker. She has become a leading
campaigner against apartheid and black activists often call her
``Mother of the Nation.''
   Another result of her prominence is that some of her personal
hardships become public events.
   When she visits her husband in prison, journalists are present.
   By the time she reached her burned-out home Thursday it was
surrounded by firefighters, police and journalists who already had
wandered through the smoldering remains.
   Mrs. Mandela moved into the modest four-room bungalow in Soweto,
Johannesburg's huge black township, after she married Mandela in
1958. Mandela had owned the house and lived in it since the 1940s.
   It has been shot at and stoned by attackers who have not been
identified. Police visit it regularly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
