<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     07-29 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Arrest Alleged Marcos Supporters, Seize Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided an apartment before
dawn today and arrested eight people, including renegade soldiers,
believed linked to ousted President Ferdinand Marcos, officials
said.
   Col. Manuel Oxales, deputy commander of the National Capital
Regional Defense Command, said police seized one claymore mine,
plastic explosives and improvised bombs that may have been intended
for terror attacks in the capital.
   Oxales said the raid at about 4:30 a.m. was in a crowded
neighborhood of suburban Caloocan City. He said the eight included
two women and at least two army enlisted men.
   Two or three others escaped, and ``some tried to escape by
climbing the walls and climbing to the rooftop,'' he said.
   Oxales said the eight were being interrogated and could face
charges of illegal possession of weapons and explosives.
   Marcos, who ruled the Philippines for 20 years, was deposed in
February 1986 in a civilian-military uprising that swept President
Corozon Aquino to power.
   Oxales said one of those arrested was linked to an abortive
April 1987 raid on Fort Bonifacio, which the military said was an
attempt to free rebel troops jailed in a coup attempt three months
before.
   The government said the January 1987 coup attempt was aimed at
restoring Marcos to power. The attempt included attacks on media
and military facilities in the Manila area.
   Oxales said some of those arrested were also suspected of
involvement in a similar raid last June on Camp Crame, where
mutineers failed to free jailed coup plotters but made off with two
dozen rifles.
   He said raiders also found street maps and other diagrams that
they suspected may have been used in planning bombings within the
capital.
   On Thursday, Mrs. Aquino's chief aide accused Marcos of trying
to evade U.S. prosecution by offering $5 billion to come home.
   ``We saw it for what it was. It was just a ploy to get his U.S.
indictment against him suspended,'' Executive Secretary Catalino
Macaraig said.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow the former president to return
from exile in Hawaii.
   In New York, The Village Voice reported this month that U.S.
attorney Rudolph Giuliani recommended that Marcos and his wife
Imelda be indicted on fraud and conspiracy charges in connection
with real estate acquisitions in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Messer     07-29 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Messer,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Messer Executed For 1979 Murder Of Niece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted in the stabbing death of his
8-year-old niece was put to death in Georgia's electric chair,
prompting the victim's mother to remark, ``We can finally put our
baby to rest.''
   James Messer Jr. died a little more than an hour after the U.S.
Supreme Court, in a 7-2 vote, refused to stop the execution.
Justices Thurgood Marshall and William J. Brennan dissented, but
there was no immediate elaboration from the court.
   Prosecutors said Messer abducted Rhonda Joan Tanner from her
school in 1979 and tried to molest her. She bled to death after
being beaten and stabbed.
   The victim's father, Wayne Tanner, 47, said Messer's execution
was a ``big relief. He finally paid.''
   Messer, 34, was pronounced dead at 7:23 p.m., said Department of
Corrections spokesman John Siler. He was the 13th person to die in
the state's electric chair since Georgia resumed executions in 1983
and the 101st person put to death since the Supreme Court allowed
states to restore capital punishment in 1976.
   ``We feel we can finally put our baby to rest,'' said the
victim's mother, Joyce Tanner, 45, of Cedartown, one of about 20
death penalty advocates who carried placards and demonstrated in
front of the prison Thursday.
   Messer declined to make a final statement, but requested a
prayer. Prison Chaplain Nolan LaVell placed his hands on Messer's
left forearm and delivered a one-minute prayer while the condemned
man held his eyes tightly shut.
   At the conclusion of the prayer, Messer said, ``Amen'' and that
was his last word.
   Fourteen people witnessed the execution, including seven state
witnesses, one of Messer's attorneys, Howard Manchell, and six
media representatives.
   Outside the prison, 12 anti-death penalty protesters sang.
Nearly twice as many pro-death penalty demonstrators, including one
man wearing a white Ku Klu Klan robe, cheered and clapped when
Messer's body was driven out of the prison in a hearse.
   Messer did not ask for any witnesses to the execution, Siler
said. His mother, Mary Messer of LaGrange, and an aunt visited him
at the prison Wednesday.
   Earlier Thursday, the Georgia Board of Pardons and Paroles
refused to commute Messer's sentence to life in prison. Chairman
Wayne Snow said the panel concluded ``there are insufficient
grounds for further consideration'' of the commutation rquest.
   Snow said the board rejected a psychiatrist's testimony that
Messer's ``explosive'' behavior may have been caused by brain
damage. Messer exhibited no such behavior in prison, he said, and
the testimony was ``not a matter that we can base a decision on a
crime that occurred nine years ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Emmys     07-29 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emmys,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`L.A. Law,' `Golden Girls' and New Shows Dominate Emmy List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legal power plays portrayed in
the pin-striped world of ``L.A. Law'' and the shenanigans of ``The
Golden Girls'' led Emmy contenders in nominations for television
excellence.
   Cable shows won 15 nominations in their first outing against the
networks, and a surprising 22 were garnered by two new shows _ the
forbidden life of ``Beauty and the Beast'' beneath New York and
``thirtysomething,'' which focuses on the ups and downs of the baby
boomer generation.
   It was the gripping courtroom and corridor intrigue of ``L.A.
Law'' and its polished cast that earned 19 nominations for the 40th
annual Emmy Awards.
   ``We have good stories and that great ensemble group,'' producer
Steven Bochco said. ``We draw inspiration from their ability.''
   Noteworthy, too, were two NBC shows overlooked by the Academy of
Television Arts and Sciences: Only one nomination was given TV's
most-watched series ``The Cosby Show'' and its spin-off ``A
Different World'' got none.
   Last year's trendy ``Moonlighting,'' a nominations leader last
year, was also fading, capturing six nominations and none in major
categories.
   NBC led the networks with 114 nominations, followed by CBS with
87 and ABC with 75. The Fox Broadcasting Co., the so-called
``fourth network,'' collected six Emmy nominations. Syndicated
shows were nominated 13 times.
   Among cable companies, Home Box Office and Showtime each claimed
six nominations. The Disney Channel drew two nominations and Turner
Broadcasting System had one. Shows on the Public Broadcasting
Service were nominated 27 times.
   Fox will broadcast the Emmy ceremony Aug. 28 from the Pasadena
Civic Auditorium.
   ``L.A. Law'' was selected in the categories of best drama
series, best actor in a drama series for Michael Tucker and Corbin
Bernsen and best actress in a drama series for Jill Eikenberry and
Susan Dey.
   The on-screen and real life husband-wife duo Michael Tucker and
Jill Eikenberry, called the ``Tucker-Berrys'' by the ``L.A. Law''
crew, were out of town. Tucker was doing a film in Montreal and his
wife was in North Carolina.
   Betty White, who won three years ago for her ``Golden Girls''
role, said of her third nomination for best actress in a comedy
series: ``I don't take it lightly. It's your peer group saying they
like you.''
   NBC's comedy ``Cheers'' received 11 nominations, including one
for new cast member Kirstie Alley for best actress in a comedy
series. The 10 for ABC's ``thirtysomething'' was a surprise for its
producers.
   ``We're thrilled and surprised that a new show has generated
this kind of recognition,'' said co-producer Marshall Herskovitz.
   Actor Tim Busfield, nominated for supporting actor in
``thirtysomething,'' was named for an episode involving marriage
counseling.
   ``I owe this to all the women I've ever had fights with,'' he
said.
   The ``L.A. Law'' sweep came despite a divisive flap that began
last year between series co-creators Bochco and Terry Louise
Fisher. At one point, Fisher was barred from the ``L.A. Law''
offices. She subsequently was forced to quit the show. But Fisher
received two nominations for ``L.A. Law'' scripts while Bochco had
just one.
   Joining ``L.A. Law'' in the best drama series competition will
be ``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``St. Elsewhere'' and
``thirtysomething.'' ``L.A. Law'' won last year.
   Nominated for best comedy program were ``Cheers,'' ``Frank's
Place,'' NBC's ``Night Court,'' ABC's ``The Wonder Years'' and last
year's winner, ``The Golden Girls.''
   ``We're jumping up and down here. I was watching the `Today
Show' and during the break the local news announced the
nominations. We started jumping, said producer Tony Thomas of ``The
Golden Girls'' and ``Beauty and the Beast.
   Ann Jillian was overwhelmed by two nominations won by the NBC
movie ``The Ann Jillian Story,'' including leading actress in a
miniseries or special and best drama-comedy special. It dealt with
her battle with breast cancer.
   ``I'm very honored and very thrilled, but the nomination isn't
for me. It goes for all those ladies who had to go through this. I
tried to do this with dignity and above all hope. I'm so grateful.''
   Named for best miniseries were ``Baby M,'' ``Gore Vidal's
Lincoln,'' ``Billionaire Boys Club'' and ``The Murder of Mary
Phagan.''
   For best variety music or comedy program, the nominees were CBS'
``Irving Berlin's 100th Birthday Celebration,'' CBS' ``The Smothers
Brothers Comedy Hour,'' Fox's ``The Tracey Ullman Show'' and two
episodes of NBC's ``Late Night With David Letterman.''
   The Board of Governors award this year goes to cartoon masters
William Hannah and Joseph Barbera.
   Cable shows were eligible for Emmys this year because national
cable networks are now available to more than 50 percent of the
country.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
