<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Exports     07-29 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Exports,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Shouldn't Hurt US Role As Food Exporter, Agriculture
Secretary Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Drought Relief, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the drought, U.S. food exporters this
year can remain reliable sources for foreign nations that depend on
them and should make it their top priority to do so, says
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng.
   ``This year, even though our crops are way down, combining our
crops with our carryover, we'll have an ample supply for both our
domestic and our export needs,'' Lyng said Thursday at an
Illinois-Japan agricultural trade conference.
   Japan, which depends on imports for 50 percent of its food, is
the ``best customer of U.S. agriculture,'' Lyng said.
   The Japanese are expected to buy $6.5 billion in U.S.
agricultural products this year, said Mark Randal, spokesman for
the Illinois Department of Agriculture, co-sponsor of the
conference.
   ``If you think about Japan's huge purchases from the United
States and their dependence upon us, we must make it clear that ...
even in a year when we have a drought ... we will not restrict
exports to protect purchases within our own country,'' Lyng said.
   ``It's absolutely essential that we assure Japan that we will
have enough, that we will be responsible,'' he added in his
15-minute talk to about 200 people at the conference, co-sponsored
by the Japan Economic Institute of America Inc.
   Lyng said the United States owes a ``debt of gratitude'' to the
Japanese for their recent agreement to dismantle many of the trade
barriers to U.S. products such as beef, citrus fruits, juices, ice
cream, processed cheeses and sugar-based goods.
   ``I compliment the Japanese for their effort to modernize and
update and improve their access,'' he said at a news conference
after his talk. ``It's not easy for them to do that.''
   Nobuo Matsunaga, Japanese ambassador to the United States, said
Americans need to be aggressive in their marketing efforts to his
country, because there are many foreign competitors.
   He reiterated Lyng's call for reliability among U.S. suppliers,
noting that past U.S. export restrictions still evoke ``bitter''
memories.
   In the early 1970s, a feared shortage of soybeans in the United
States prompted an embargo that forced Japan unexpectedly to seek
other markets to fulfill its high demand for soybean products,
Randal said.
   Lyng said U.S. law as well as Reagan administration policy now
supports unrestricted international trade regardless of conditions
at home.
   On the topic of drought relief for American farmers, Lyng said
the $6 billion measure approved in Congress is ``a pretty good
bill,'' despite some provisions the Reagan administration opposes
and some efforts by lobbyists to use the legislation for special
interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Convoy     07-29 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Convoy,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Peace Convoy Heads For Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Sandinista party's
newspaper saluted a convoy of U.S. veterans that brought food,
medicine and clothing with a banner headline reading, ``Veterans
Break Boycott.''
   The newspaper Barricada said in its Thursday edition that
thousands of people greeted the convoy of 20 vehicles and 44
activists when it crossed the Honduran-Nicaraguan border the day
before, after months of opposition from the U.S. government.
   The Veterans' Peace Convoy was scheduled to arrive in Managua's
downtown Revolution Plaza today, where it will turn over its
shipment to the leftist government.
   The veterans oppose U.S. support of Nicaraguan Contra rebels,
who have waged a 7-year-old war to topple the Sandinista government.
   The U.S. Customs Service opposed letting the convoy cross the
U.S.-Mexico border, saying taking the vehicles to Nicaragua would
violate a 1985 trade embargo. Humanitarian aid is permitted under
the embargo, but the Customs Service says the vehicles must return
to the United States.
   The newspaper said U.S. police ``brutally repressed'' the group
in its attempt to bring ``medicine, food and clothes for Nicaraguan
children butchered by the war action of the Reagan administration.''
   Eight members of the group were arrested July 9 when they
refused to leave the road leading to a toll booth at a Rio Grande
bridge crossing in Laredo, Texas. The convoy finally crossed the
Mexican border at Nuevo Laredo on July 14.
   The Customs Service said the trucks must return to the United
States within 30 days or convoy members will face fines of up to
$50,000 and 10 years in prison. The veterans refused to sign forms
promising they would return the trucks.
   In June, U.S. Customs officials stopped the original convoy of
38 vehicles from crossing into Mexico. About 100 convoy
participants drove to Washington to rally against Customs'
decision, circling around the White House and in front of the State
Department in three days of protest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
