<DOCNO> AP880729-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Abortion     07-29 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Abortion,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Remains Divided On New Abortion Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament rejected proposals for a new abortion
law ranging from freedom of choice to a ban except in cases of a
threat to the pregnant woman's life.
   Also Thursday, the British Columbia Court of Appeal ruled that a
fetus is not a person.
   The national government began searching for a new abortion law
after the Supreme Court in January struck down Canada's restrictive
abortion law. The lack of a new law has brought abortion-on-demand
to many cities and led to angry protests from anti-abortion groups.
   Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's government, itself
split on the issue, proposed a compromise in which abortion would
be easy to obtain early in pregnancy but restricted later on.
   That proposal was defeated 147 to 76, and other proposed
measures also fell. The voting followed a two-day debate, and the
issue now goes back to the drawing board.
   Opposition parties criticized Mulroney for staying out of the
debate or revealing his own views. But with a general election
expected this fall, Mulroney can go to voters saying that he tried
to propose a compromise.
   The British Columbia Court of Appeal ruled Thursday that a
newborn becomes a person only after it leaves the mother's body
alive.
   The decision overturned the conviction of two midwives charged
with criminal negligence in the death of a fetus in 1985.
   But the court upheld their conviction on charges of causing
bodily harm to the pregnant woman.
   The Canadian Supreme Court is expected to deliver its view this
fall on whether a fetus has any rights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
