<DOCNO> AP880729-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Ambassador-Cocaine     07-29 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ambassador-Cocaine,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambassador Switches Plea to Guilty in Cocaine Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Honduran ambassador to Panama faces a
possible life sentence after pleading guilty to charges of
attempting to smuggle 26 pounds of cocaine hidden in coffee bags in
his luggage.
   Rigoberto Regalado Lara, 49, was arrested May 15 at Miami
International Airport and immediately stripped of his diplomatic
immunity by Honduran officials.
   Regalado had initially pleaded innocent, but on Thursday he told
U.S. District Court Judge Edward B. Davis he wanted to change his
plea to guilty of importing cocaine.
   In return, Assistant U.S. Attorney Toby Vick said the government
was dropping a second charge of possession with intent to
distribute.
   Davis warned Regalado that he faces at least 10 years in prison
and could be sentenced to life, as well as fined $4 million on the
importation charge. He asked the former ambassador if he understood.
   ``Yes, your honor, I do,'' Regalado responded through an
interpreter. Davis set sentencing for Sept. 14.
   Vick refused to comment on the case or the plea bargain, but
federal sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
investigation was continuing.
   Regalado has been held at the federal Metropolitan Correctional
Center south of Miami since his arrest.
   Honduran authorities cooperated with U.S. drug investigators in
the case, and even threatened to try Regalado in his homeland if he
tried to return there.
   Prosecutors had asked he be held without bond prior to his plea
because Honduras has no extradition treaty with the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
