<DOCNO> AP880729-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NamelessProtesters Bjt   07-29 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nameless Protesters, Bjt,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Days After Arrests, Protesters Still Refuse To Give Names</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten days after their arrests during the
Democratic National Convention, 96 anti-abortion protesters who
refuse to give their names remain jailed, most vowing to stay until
their next court date or the city frees them.
   Lawyers said Thursday that the jailed protesters, charged with
criminal trespass, cannot be freed on bond until they give
verifiable proof of their identities.
   ``If we can identify them ... we can try them,'' explained Lee
O'Brien, Fulton County's chief assistant solicitor. He said the
offense carries a maximum penalty of a year in jail and a fine of
$1,000.
   ``Demonstrators like this ... do all they can to frustrate the
system,'' O'Brien said. ``If in so doing they are willing to spend
more time in jail than they would have, if any, so be it. It really
depends on how far they want to carry it.''
   The protesters, part of an anti-abortion effort called Operation
Rescue, were among 134 arrested July 19 at a clinic near downtown
Atlanta where abortions are performed. The city began processing
them through the court system this week.
   ``We just hope the city will realize it made a mistake and just
let us go,'' said Lowell Patterson, a spokesman for the protesters
who is not jailed. ``We have served more time even than we would
have if we had been found guilty'' of criminal trespass.
   On Thursday, a man calling himself Baby John Doe 105 and a woman
calling herself Baby Jane Doe 111 clutched Bibles as they stood
silently in Municipal Court. A man calling himself Baby John Doe
132 was dressed as a priest.
   The protesters, who are being held at the Atlanta Corrections
Center, say they have taken the names in solidarity with aborted
fetuses.
   Judge Howard Johnson, however, referred to the prisoners as
``White Male 42,'' or ``White Female 47,'' as he methodically sent
their cases to state court.
   Thirty-two of those arrested last week have given their names
and been released on $500 recognizance bonds, said Tom Pocock,
deputy director of the corrections center. He said six others were
identified through other means.
   The demonstrators have been brought into court in groups of
seven or eight for their brief appearances before being returned to
jail.
   The remaining 23 demonstrators were to appear today.
   ``We have 75 percent of our people committed to stay (in jail)
until their court hearing, assuming it is within the next month or
so,'' said Patterson.
   It normally takes two to three months for such a case to reach
state court.
   ``Most of our local people are in jail,'' Patterson said.
Supporters are coming in from outside the Atlanta area, and there
would be large demonstrations in the coming weeks, he said, but
declined to elaborate.
   Similarly charged demonstrators arrested during an anti-nuclear
protest at U.S. Department of Energy offices during the convention
were sentenced to the five days they had spent awaiting a court
appearance and were freed.
   Robert Fierer, who is representing the demonstrators in court,
said he does not know whether some will reveal their identities to
get out of jail.
   ``These are people of conscience,'' he said this week. ``They
have to make their own decisions about these sorts of things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     07-29 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15 South Korean Delegates Named For Talks With North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly today appointed
15 delegates for parliamentary talks with North Korea on various
tesion-easing measures and the Olympic Games.
   National Assembly officials said a South Korean letter proposing
the talks will be delivered to North Korea through Panmunjon, the
border truce site, on Monday.
   The letter will also ask North Korea to send an equal number of
delegates to the border village for the talks, the officials said.
   The naming of the delegates was endorsed today by the heads of
the nation's four main political parties, who approved plans for
the talks worked out by their aides earlier this week.
   North Korea has proposed that the full legislatures of the two
nations meet in August to discuss a non-aggression pact and
Pyongyang's possible entry into the Olympic Games in Seoul.
   In a letter delivered Thursday last week, North Korea suggested
the two sides skip working contacts to prepare for the joint
parliamentary conference. But Seoul officials say preliminary talks
are needed to set an agenda and other details.
   The delegates picked today _ six governing and nine opposition
lawmakers _would attend preliminary talks at Panmunjon in the
second week of August if North Korea agrees. Seoul officials
suggested a date between Aug. 13 and 15.
   The non-aggression pact and North Korea's demand to co-host the
Olympics would be high on the agenda, but South Korean delegates
also plan to raise other tension-easing measures, including
reuniting separated family members.
   North Korea has said it would boycott the Sept. 17-Oct. 2
Olympics unless its demand to co-host the Games is accepted.
   The International Olympic Committee rejected the demand, saying
the Olympics are awarded to a single city.
   The two Koreas remain as bitter rivals since the division of the
Korean land at the end of World War II in 1945. They fought the
three-year Korean War that ended in standoff in 1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti-Killing     07-29 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti-Killing,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Tonton Macoute Acquitted In Murder Retrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ An ex-militiaman of deposed
dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier was acquitted of charges he fatally
shot a 21-year-old waitress, and her father tried to kill himself
when the case ended, Radio Haiti Inter said.
   Joseph Louis stood on the front steps of the Palace of Justice
and slashed his throat with a razor blade, the independent radio
station said Thursday. He was rushed to State University Hospital
in Port-au-Prince, where he was reported in stable condition.
   The radio said Louis tried to kill himself Wednesday after a
jury acquitted Serge Gaston, 45, a former member of the dreaded
Tonton Mocoutes militia, in the killing of Louis' daughter, Ingrid.
   She was shot and killed by two gunmen firing from a speeding car
in front of the capital's Tiffany restaurant, where she worked, on
Jan. 31, 1986 _ one week before Duvalier was ousted and fled to
France. The motive for the killing was not known.
   Gaston originally was convicted last year and sentenced to death
in the killing, but an Appeals Court overturned the conviction on a
legal technicality and ordered a retrial.
   The Appeals Court retrial was held Wednesday, and the jury
acquitted Gaston after two witnesses failed to show up for
unexplained reasons, Radio Haiti Inter reported.
   The witnesses, Jacques Delmas and Camille Eustache, swore they
saw Gaston and another Macoute in the car from which gunfire was
sprayed at Miss Louis and other restaurant employees. The second
Macoute was not captured.
   Haiti Inter said the jury expressed hostility toward the
victim's father, and the prosecuting attorney did not press the
defense witnesses with questions.
   Several spectators marched out of the courtroom in disgust
before the jury acquitted Gaston, the radio station said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
