<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-29 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0455,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Strike In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with strike, report that</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian killed by army; no pickup
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians in the occupied territories
blocked streets and stayed away from work today to show support for
women jailed for their roles in the Palestinian uprising.
   Also, state-run radio said a Palestinian who died in Gaza City
Thursday was killed by Israeli troops as he prepared to throw a
firebomb. The death touched off demonstrations in which two
Palestinians were wounded by gunfire and two Israeli riot police
were injured by stones.
   Palestinians throughout the occupied lands went on strike today.
Outlawed Palestinian flags waved on utility poles from Bethlehem to
Nablus in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Graffiti appeared on walls overnight reading ``Death to the
Zionists'' and ``Yes for a Palestinian state.''
   Before dawn, Palestinian protesters blocked some streets with
rocks, barrels and burning tires, an apparent effort to prevent
Palestinians from breaking the strike organized by the underground
leadership of the uprising that began Dec. 8.
   The strike, called to protest the jailing of Palestinian women,
halted transportation and shut down shops.
   The Palestinian-run Jerusalem Media and Communication Center
said 30 Palestinian women are being held in Israeli jails, most on
suspicion of inciting violence against Israel.
   An Israeli army spokesman said the army was checking the report
on Israel's state-run radio that troops fatally shot 37-year-old
Hadel Hafez el Toruk in Gaza City.
   He died in Ahali Hospital of wounds sustained on July 22,
hospital officials said. The army confirmed the death and said it
was investigating the circumstances.
   Toruk's family told the army he was shot at the same time
soldiers opened fire at Palestinians who threw a Molotov cocktail
at them. Toruk said before he died that he did not see his
assailants, a hospital official said.
   ``He said he was walking in the street, and then he fell down,
and he didn't know what happened,'' said the hospital official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The fatality brought to 235 the number of Palestinians killed in
the anti-Israeli revolt. Four Israelis also have died.
   Meanwhile, Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said he reacted
positively to reports that U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
Richard Murphy planned to meet with Palestinian representatives.
   Peres said he was against meetings with members of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which is banned in Israel, but did not
necessarily oppose meetings with PLO supporters.
   ``We make a distinction between people who are members of the
PLO, which is an organization that deals in terrorism and has a
charter that calls for the destruction of Israel,'' Peres said on
Israeli television.
   Murphy is to leave next week for a peace mission that will take
him to Israel, Jordan, Syria, and Egypt.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Anita Stockman said
Thursday she was unaware of plans for Murphy to talk to Palestinian
leaders. She also said U.S. policy of refusing to meet PLO leaders
remained in place.
   Peres previously has called for negotiations between Israel and
a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.
   But on Thursday, Jordan said it was changing its policy toward
the 1.5 million Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories to
give the PLO more responsibility there and avoid friction between
Jordan and the PLO.
   Toward this end, Jordan announced it was halting a $1.3 billion,
5-year development project in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. The plan was set up in 1986 by agreement with the PLO.
</TEXT>
