<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BankRobbers     07-29 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Bank Robbers,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Extradited From Burma And Sentenced To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who fled to Burma after killing two
people during a failed bank heist were returned to China and
sentenced to death, an official newspaper reported today.
   The People's Daily saod Burma extradited Li Danian and Wang
Yueping to China in February after they sneaked across the border.
   The paper said Li, Wang and another accomplice were running a
business in Hunan province that went into debt. To pay back the
debt they decided to start robbing banks.
   It said the trio began robbing banks in June 1987, striking
among others the Agricultural Bank and the Industrial and
Commercial Bank in the Hunan city of Yueyang. The paper said they
failed to steal any money.
   On July 7, 1987, the paper said, the trio broke into another
Yueyang bank and killed a bank guard and a clerk. Still, no money
was stolen, it said.
   Li and Wang then fled to Burma. Their accomplice, Yi Maohua,
stayed behind and was captured.
   The paper said the three were sentenced on Monday and would be
executed soon. China executes people with a bullet to the back of
the head.
   Chinese papers have been devoting more space to reports on crime
in recent years. In almost every case, when they report on bank
heists, the papers say the robberies end in failure.
   The apparent reason for this is that the state-run press doesn't
want to encourage copycat crimes.
</TEXT>
