<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AgentSlain     07-29 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Agent Slain,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Alleges Mexican Cover-Up In Death Of DEA Agent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer says the Mexicans charged in
the barbaric killing of a U.S. drug agent are innocent victims, and
he has evidence of a huge coverup designed to protect the highest
Mexican officials.
   The three men charged in the kidnapping and murder of Enrique
Camarena, a Drug Enforcement Administration agent, are victims of
Mexico's corrupt judicial system, defense attorney Barry Tarlow
said in opening arguments Thursday.
   ``People destroyed, altered and failed to preserve evidence,''
Tarlow told the jury. ``When you see the widespread corruption, it
becomes impossible to see who is reliable.''
   The prosecutor in the case said that Camarena died in a torture
chamber at the hands of people trying to elicit information about a
U.S. drug investigation.
   ``Special agent Camarena's skull was fractured in numerous
places, in the front of the head and in the back of the head. It
resembled, basically, a cracked eggshell,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Jimmy Gurule.
   ``At the top of the skull, the skull had actually been
penetrated by a blunt instrument, that an object had been driven
through the skull,'' he said.
   Tarlow, however, contends the people responsible for Camarena's
slaying are in a safe haven in Mexico.
   The sensitivity of the grisly case was evident at the entrance
of U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie's courtroom, where U.S.
marshals had set up a metal detector, in addition to security
checks made at the courthouse entrances.
   The trial is expected to take about 10 weeks.
   The bodies of Camarena and his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar,
were found buried at a remote ranch in Mexico several weeks after
they were abducted separately in Guadalajara on Feb. 7, 1985.
   On trial are Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, and Raul Lopez Alvarez,
28, who are charged with murdering Camarena and Zavala; and Jesus
Felix Gutierrez, 38, who is charged with being an accessory.
   They were among nine people indicted in the case by a federal
grand jury in Los Angeles earlier this year. Four are in custody in
Mexico, one was killed by Mexican police and one is at large.
   Camarena was kidnapped in 1985 as he left the U.S. consulate in
Guadalajara after he and other agents uncovered a drug trafficking
operation said to have been run by reputed Mexican drug lord Rafael
Caro Quintero.
   Caro also is charged in the killings and is in custody in Mexico.
   The prosecution alleges Camarena was tortured in an effort to
make him provide information about the U.S. investigation into
Caro's activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
