<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthKorea-US     07-29 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Korea-US,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korean Parliament Proposes U.S. Talks On '53 Armistice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea today said it proposed a conference
with U.S. lawmakers so the nations can discuss a peace accord that
would replace the 1953 armistice ending the Korean War.
   Pyongyang's official Korean Central News Agency said the
proposal was made by Chairman Yang Hyong Sop of the Supreme
People's Assembly in a letter sent to the leaders of the U.S. House
and Senate.
   It said Yang proposed that the talks be held at the earliest
possible date in Pyongyang, New York or any third country between
the two delegations, each comprising seven to nine legislators.
   ``It would be good to discuss measures for cooperation between
the two parliaments in replacing the Korean armistice agreement
with a peace agreement,'' it quoted Yang's letter as saying.
   The armistice was signed by North Korea and China on one side
and the United Nations Command, led by the United States, on the
other. It ended the bloody Korean War, which began in 1950 when
North Korea invaded the south in an attempt to unify the Korean
peninsula by force.
   Protesters in South Korea have demanded that the United States
sign a peace treaty that would replace the armistice agreement. The
two Koreas are technically still at war, since no treaty has been
signed.
   Last week, North Korea sent a proposal to South Korea calling
for joint sessions between their legislatures to draw up a
non-aggression pact to end the enmity and rivalry that have
prevailed since the peninsula was divided at the end of World War
II.
   The South Korean National Assembly said it was ready to accept
the North Korean call for talks on the non-aggression pact and the
North's possible participation in the Olympic Games in Seoul in
September.
   The latest North Korean peace offer to the United States was the
first in four years. In 1984, Pyongyang proposed a tripartite
conference among the two Koreas and the United States to seek a
permanent peace and an eventual reunification of the Korean
peninsula.
   The 1984 proposal was rejected by both South Korea and the
United States on grounds that peace and unification were matters to
be settled between the two Koreas.
   After the 1984 proposal, President Reagan, at a state dinner
honoring Chinese Premier Zhao Ziyang in Washington, told reporters,
``It would be just wonderful if there would be a four-way
conference with China and both Koreas and the United States.''
   The latest proposal was made in cordial, diplomatic language
free from the North's usual vitriolic hyperbole.
   ``The best way we and the United States can choose at present is
to have peace negotiation to slacken the whetting swords and firing
guns against each other or cease them completely,'' Yang's letter
said.
   Yang said he made the proposal ``recognizing that we and the
United States, directly responsible parties for easing tension and
providing peace in Korea, must sit at the table as soon as
possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
