<HEAD>With PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi-backed Iranian rebels said they
pulled out of two towns in western Iran today after killing or
wounding 40,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards during three days of
fighting.
   But Iran said its forces drove the rebels out of the Iranian
towns of Eslamabad and Karand, killing or wounding at least 1,000
enemy troops in a battle with the ``forces of the Baghdad regime
and their hypocritical mercenaries.''
   At the United Nations on Thursday, representatives for both gulf
war foes accused each other of blocking U.N. efforts to end the
nearly 8-year-old war.
   Tehran radio interrupted its normal programs to play martial
music and announce victory over the rebels, members of the National
Liberation Army of Iran.
   In a later announcement, the radio said Iranian forces were
advancing in a bid to liberate the Iraqi-occupied Iranian towns of
Sar-e Pol-e Zahab and Gilan-e Gharb.
   The National Liberation Army rebels operate a series of bases or
camps along the border, usually just on the Iraqi side of the
frontier.
   The rebel group said in a communique released in Baghdad that
its guerrillas penetrated 95 miles into Iran and controlled Karand
and Eslamabad near the central border for 72 hours.
   It said that during the fighting, two Iranian F-4 jet fighters
and two Cobra helicopter gunships were shot down, and hundreds of
tanks and armored personnel carriers were destroyed.
   The claims by the rebel group could not be independently
confirmed. Reporters are allowed into battle areas only during rare
guided tours.
   Earlier, Iran said its forces broke through the defenses of the
Iraqis and the National Liberation Army at Eslamabad.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus, said Thursday that Iranian forces killed at least
4,000 Iraqis and ``mercenaries'' in the battle.
   A communique issued Thursday by Iraq's military said its
warplanes were bombing Iranian military airfields around Eslamabad.
   Iraq demands a face-to-face meeting with Iran before a
cease-fire, and Iran insists on a truce before it will consider a
direct talks.
   Pressure was increasing on Iraq in the 15-member U.N. Security
Council to drop its direct talks demand and other proposals that
could prolong the fighting, according to U.N. diplomats, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The foreign ministers of both countries have met separately in
New York with U.N. secretary-general Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The talks were made possible on when Iran, which has suffered a
series of battlefield setbacks in recent months, on July 18
accepted a year-old United Nations resolution calling for a
cease-fire in the war. Iraq accepted the resolution shortly after
it was passed.
