<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rumble Across Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled across parts of the nation's midsection
earlier today after storms dropped large hail and heavy rain.
   Thunderstorms were scattered from northern Montana into northern
North Dakota, central and southwest Minnesota and southwest
Nebraska early this morning.
   Golf ball-size hail and 1-2 inches of rain fell near Miller,
S.D., Thursday evening, but many of the thunderstorms that were
rumbling over the southern Atlantic Coast and Gulf Coast regions
earlier in the day weakened by late Thursday. Many of these storms
developed due to very warm and humid air in the afternoon, then
died out as the evening air cooled.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Thursday night over
parts of eastern Colorado and extreme western Kansas. Thunderstorms
also were widely scattered in northeast and central New Mexico.
Nearly 1\ inches of rain fell in 20 minutes in the Four Hills area
of Albuquerque, where street flooding was reported.
   Thunderstorms also were scattered over western Arizona on
Thursday evening. Strong thunderstorm winds damaged several
trailers near Surprise, Ariz.
   Widely scattered thunderstorms developed from south-central and
southeast Kansas into southwest Missouri.
   Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT included
nearly an inch at Kennedy Airport near New York City, a half-inch
at Joplin, Mo., over a third of an inch at Alexandria, Minn., and
Huron, S.D., and over a quarter inch at Albuquerque.
   For today, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for
the southern Atlantic and Gulf Coastal states, the lower Missouri
and middle Mississippi valleys, northeast Minnesota and the High
Plains of Colorado.
   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 90s across much of
the nation; in the 80s along much of the California coast, the
northern parts of the Pacific Northwest and northern Rockies, and
from the upper Ohio Valley into New England; in the lower 80s near
the front range of the Rockies; up to 100 degrees over parts of
north-central Texas and Illinois; and between 100 and 110 degrees
from the valleys of southwest Oregon and California into the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Laramie and Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., and Arcata, Calif.,
to 91 at Phoenix and Nellis Air Force Base near Las Vegas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 76 fair; Boston 66 foggy; Buffalo 71 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 75 fair; Cincinnati 68 fair; Cleveland 72 fair;
Detroit 71 fair; Miami 83 partly cloudy; New York 74 foggy;
Philadelphia 74 foggy; Pittsburgh 73 fair; Portland, Maine, 64
foggy; Washington 75 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 65 fair; Chicago 76 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
80 windy; Denver 66 partly cloudy; Des Moines 74 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 70 fair; Kansas City 72 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 76 cloudy; Nashville 76 fair; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis
77 hazy.
   _West: Anchorage 54 cloudy; Las Vegas 89 fair; Los Angeles 65
foggy; Phoenix 90 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City 70 fair; San Diego
69 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 63 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 66 fair; Toronto 72 hazy.
