<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Earthquake     07-29 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earthquake,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Earthquake Rattles Washington State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake and aftershock shook the
towns of Packwood, Eatonville and Randle, but there were no reports
of damage, a geophysicist said.
   A quake of 4.2 on the Richter scale was recorded at 10 p.m.
Thursday, centered about 35 miles southeast of Tacoma near Mount
Rainier, said Bruce Presgrave, a geophysicist at the United States
Geological Survey National Earthquake Information Center in Golden,
Colo.
   An aftershock quake registering 3.9 was recorded at 11 p.m., he
said.
   Presgrave said both temblors were felt in Packwood, Eatonville
and Randle. There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries,
he said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as rerded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. A reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 4 on the Richter scale can cause moderate
damage in a local area, while a 7 reading is a ``major'' quake,
capable of widespread heavy damage.
</TEXT>
