<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru     07-29 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackout Hits Peru After President Lashes Out At Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police blamed leftist guerrillas for a power
outage that blacked out central Peru hours after President Alan
Garcia demanded tougher laws against terrorism.
   The outage at 8 p.m. Thursday was the second in less than 24
hours. It plunged Lima and cities along 600 miles of coastline into
darkness, said Jose Acedo, a spokesman for the state power company,
Electro-Peru.
   The blackout and an power outage Wednesday night both were
blamed on members of the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla movement,
Acedo said. He said guerrillas bombed power pylons near Lima on
Wednesday and may have done the same thing Thursday.
   Power on Thursday was restored within 15 minutes in most areas
and police said they had no reports of violence.
   Garcia vowed Thursday that Peru would step up its battle against
drug traffickers and the leftist guerrillas that defend them.
   ``The United States can count on our decided help. Peru will not
resign itself to being and exporter of poison,'' Garcia said in his
state of the nation address, referring to Peru's reputation among
international anti-drug officials as the world's cocaine cradle.
   The government said 4,400 people were arrested this week in Lima
during an operation aimed at preventing guerrilla attacks over the
Independence Days, Thursday and today.
   Garcia said leftist guerrilla violence was Peru's major problem
and proposed tougher laws to combat it, including penalties against
guerrilla leaders who do not participate in attacks and against
media that promote and justify subversion.
   ``The law now favors terrorists ... They are taking advantage of
freedom of the press,'' Garcia said in an obvious reference to the
Lima newspaper El Diaro, considered the voice of the Shining Path.
   He disclosed that an eight-year insurgency by the organization
had claimed 15,000 lives.
   Garcia also charged the Shining Path had become ``the armed hand
of Peruvian drug traffickers.''
   He did not specify what new measures the government would take
to fight drugs. U.S. officials estimate 60 percent of the world's
coca, the raw material of cocaine, is harvested illegally in the
Upper Huallaga Valley of eastern Peru.
</TEXT>
