<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     07-29 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine: Hostages Will Be Released Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weekly magazine Ash-Shiraa reported
today that negotiations are under way for the release of the nine
American and nine other foreigners held hostage by Iranian-backed
factions in Lebanon.
   ``The issue of the foreign hostages held in Lebanon will find
its way to a happy ending soon,'' the magazine quoted an
unidentified informed security source as saying.
   ``High-level contacts are under way between officials of the
hostages' nations, especially the United States, and a state that
has direct influence on the hostages,'' it said.
   It quoted the source as saying that no intermediaries were
involved.
   ``A settlement to the hostages' issue will coincide with the
U.S. presidential elections'' Nov. 8, the report said. It did not
elaborate.
   The magazine gained international fame when it broke the story
of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in return for the release of
hostages in 1986. But most of its recent reports on the hostages
have not proved accurate.
   Iran's Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani said Wednesday his
country would be prepared to help get the hostages released if
President Reagan released frozen Iranian assets.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater responded
to Rafsanjani's offer by saying: ``No deals. The clearest signal
they could send is to release the hostages.''
   The longest held hostage is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized in west
Beirut on March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
