<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish-Bomb Death,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Injured Soldier Dies; Army Experts Defuse Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier who was
injured when a bomb exploded in an IRA stronghold has died, the
army said.
   An army headquarters statement identified the victim as Sgt.
Michael Matthews, 27.
   His death Thursday brought the overall death toll to at least
2,663 since sectarian and political violence flared in Northern
Ireland in 1969.
   The army said Matthews was leading a police and army foot patrol
on the outskirts of Cullyhanna village in southern Armagh Wednesday
when a bomb hidden by the side of the road went off. He was wounded
in the head and body.
   Predominantly Roman Catholic south Armagh, dubbed bandit country
by the army, is a stronghold of the Irish Republican Army, the
mainly Catholic guerrilla group fighting to drive the British from
Northern Ireland.
   Army experts on Thursday defused a bomb consisting of more than
1,000 pounds of explosives packed into beer kegs hidden in a
culvert under the road between Belfast and Londonderry.
   The army said it believed the bomb was intended for one of its
patrols but that IRA guerrillas could not detonate it because of a
technical malfunction.
