<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe-Lyons     07-29 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Lyons,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Cuts Ties With Lyons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Adm. James A. ``Ace'' Lyons, whose name
has surfaced in connection with the Defense Department contract
fraud probe, is also the target of two Pentagon inquiries, a
newspaper reported today.
   The St. Louis Post-Dispatch quoted Pentagon and Navy sources as
confirming that Lyons is the subject of two inquiries independent
of the fraud investigation.
   One inquiry concerns allegations that classified documents were
mishandled, while the other focuses on allegations of misuse of
military personnel and government aircraft, the newspaper said.
   Lyons' role in the fraud investigation apparently involves his
work as a consultant for McDonnell Douglas Corp., which announced
Thursday that the former commander of the Pacific Fleet no longer
works for them.
   ``Lyons is not under contract with us anymore,'' McDonnell
Douglas spokesman James Reed said Thursday. ``His contract expired
... and we did not renew it.''
   Reed declined to comment further on the end of the relationship
or the terms of Lyons' contract, which expired about two weeks ago.
   The company hired Lyons in February to consult on issues
concerning requirements for the F-18 Hornet in the Pacific,
including Taiwan and South Korea, McDonnell Douglas said.
   An FBI search warrant served on the company last month listed
among the items sought any ``agreements, contracts, purchase
orders, invoices'' or other material related to Lyons' work for the
company after December 1987.
   Lyons has said disclosures of the fraud investigation were
``part of a smear campaign'' by his critics in the Navy.
</TEXT>
