<DOCNO> AP880729-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe     07-29 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Keeps Defense Probe Subpoenas Secret; News Groups to Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major news organizations say they will
appeal a federal judge's ruling holding the lid of secrecy on
search warrants in the wide-ranging Pentagon bribery probe.
   ``I think the decision is clearly wrong,'' Rex Heinke,
representing the Los Angeles Times, said after U.S. District Judge
David Kenyon ruled against the Times and Copley Newspapers on
Thursday.
   Attorneys for both organizations said they would go to a federal
appeals court next week to seek a reversal of the order keeping
search warrants and affidavits sealed indefinitely.
   Another request to unseal documents in the probe was denied in
Bridgeport, Conn., on Thursday by U.S. District Judge T.F. Gilroy
Daly, ruling against The Hartford Courant.
   The newspaper has not decided whether to appeal, said Managing
Editor Mike Jenner.
   The investigation, which became public last month, centers on
allegations that defense industry consultants bribed Pentagon
officials for inside information useful in winning
multimillion-dollar contracts.
   Kenyon overturned a federal magistrate's ruling July 15 granting
access to the material. The government had argued that release of
the documents might prompt targets of the probe to destroy evidence.
   Kenyon, who heard arguments from the Times, Copley, NBC and CBS,
said he did not wish ``to minimize the importance of the role of
the press, especially in matters of extreme public interest such as
the investigation concerned herein.''
   ``However, the court finds that, on balance, the public's
interest in a complete and uninhibited investigation strongly
outweighs its need for or right of access to the search warrant
affidavits at this time,'' he said.
   ``All it says is that the government has concern about possible
destruction of evidence,'' said Heinke. ``Anything is possible.
There is no showing that it is probable or likely.'
   Harold Fuson, attorney for Copley, said the government has a
responsibility to allow scrutiny of documents supporting a search.
   The documents detail searches conducted June 14 at Northrop
Corp., Teledyne Electronics, Litton Industries and the home of
defense consultant Fred Lackner. The only segments released so far
were introductions showing that wiretaps had been used in each case.
   News organizations have gone to court in several states to seek
access to search warrants and supporting documents on First
Amendment grounds.
   The Courant had sought access to affidavits used to gain search
warrants for Norden Systems' offices.
   Norden, a subsidiary of Hartford-based United Technologies
Corp., is suspected of benefiting from inside information to build
a battlefield communication system for the Marines, according to
documents already released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SAfrica-ANCGuidelines     07-29 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-ANC Guidelines,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exiled Movement Creates Constitutional Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress has drafted
constitutional guidelines for a multiparty democracy in South
Africa in response to criticism that its political programs are too
vague, The New York Times reported today.
   The guidelines call for an independent judiciary that would
enforce constitutional guarantees including freedom of the press,
freedom of religion and freedom of association, the Times said.
   The guidelines resulted from two years of study by an ANC
committee of lawyers and political scientists, and have circulated
only within ANC ranks and to a select group of experts sympathetic
to its aim of overthrowing white rule in South Africa, the
newspaper said. They are far more specific than the ANC's 1955
blueprint, known as the Freedom Charter, it said.
   The guidelines call for a multiparty democracy but ban parties
advocating racism or tribalism, and would provide for wide
government supervision of the economy to protect the entire
population, the Times said. They do not specify whether there would
be a president or a prime minister, it said.
   ``There is a growing acceptance that apartheid cannot last,''
ANC leader Oliver R. Tambo, 72, told the Times in Lusaka, Zambia.
``But we think there should be greater clarity and consensus on
what a constitution should say.''
   The newspaper said the guidelines are a response to criticism by
some Western leaders and white liberals in South Africa that the
ANC's political program is too vague.
   The right to education, to own property, to employment and
shelter would be established as ideals, but the difficulty of
putting these into practice would be taken into account, the Times
said.
   The guidelines also call for affirmative action to fix the
historical imbalances in employment caused by apartheid, and the
scrapping of the 1913 and 1936 Land Acts, which set aside 13
percent of the country for blacks, it said.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   The Times said land redistribution would be limited because
``property for personal use and consumption shall be
constitutionally protected.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
