<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MissingMan     07-29 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Man,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Vanished From Montana Surfaces in Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Montana man who left his pregnant
wife and three children and vanished under mysterious circumstances
four years ago has been discovered living in Canada.
   Barrie Shaw, 40, has since remarried and is living in Edmonton
with his new wife and their 15-month-old daughter, authorities said.
   The Canadian-born Shaw planned to fly to Montana to try to clear
up his past.
   ``I'm going down to Montana to face the music,'' a tearful Shaw
said Thursday. ``I've got to clear this up, and then I'm coming
directly back here to face the music here.''
   On Wednesday, a co-worker at Canadian Home Assurance saw Shaw's
name and picture in a magazine story on missing persons and
confronted him.
   U.S. authorities said Shaw faked his own death in 1984, but Shaw
said he was suffering a nervous breakdown at the time. He was
looking for a way out of his troubled seven-year marriage, he said,
and described the events on the day he disappeared as ``a blur.''
   ``My head felt like it was in a vice and was going to explode,''
he said.
   Shaw was reported missing on July 10, 1984 after he failed to
return from a fishing trip near Helena. He left behind his wife,
Chris, and their three children, Justin, 9, Sarah-Anne, 6, and
Tyrell, 2.
   Police found Shaw's locked station wagon and his tackle box near
the edge of a river. His fishing pole was found in the water.
   Ed Schild of the Helena area sheriff's office said Shaw may face
charges of aggravated non-support for abandoning his wife and
children. But he said Shaw's first wife might have had the marriage
annulled shortly after he vanished.
   Shaw, who wandered around the United States and Canada before
settling in Edmonton in 1985, said he went back to Helena for one
weekend the year he disappeared but no one recognized him. He said
he learned his first wife had had their marriage annulled.
   Confident he was no longer married, Shaw said he came to
Edmonton and remarried in 1986.
</TEXT>
