<DOCNO> AP880729-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0820EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StickyStamps     07-29 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sticky Stamps,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Stamps Should Stick Better, Taste Same</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN W. CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service is spending $700,000 to
come up with a stickier stamp. But don't expect it to taste any
better.
   ``Taste is a very personal thing. What we've always sought in
taste, and where we think we are, is neutral and bland. And we'd
like to stay neutral and bland,'' said Gordon C. Morison, a senior
assistant postmaster general.
   Morison opened a daylong conference Thursday at Battelle
Memorial Institute with about 100 adhesive industry executives and
technical experts on how to lick the problem of stamps that don't
stay stuck.
   The postal service has a 16-month contract with Battelle aimed
at persuading the industry to develop a gum that will keep stamps
glued to mail zipping through high-speed automated processing
equipment.
   ``Taste is in the tongue of the users, and this contract really
has nothing to do with that,'' Morison said.
   He acknowledged that the postal service regularly gets
suggestions about improving the taste of stamps.
   ``In fact, one other country, I think it was Great Britain,
tried some flavored gums at one point in time. But they got so many
complaints from the people who didn't like the strawberry or the
raspberry flavor,'' he said. ``You can't satisfy everybody because
we all have different tastes.''
   Adhesive now used by stamp manufacturers performs well when mail
is sorted manually or mechanically. But the arrival of high-speed,
automated processing, in which stamps are coated with a compound
that activates processing equipment, requires a stronger adhesive.
   ``Our letters go through our processing equipment very, very
fast. In the time that it takes for a baseball pitcher to throw a
ball 90 miles per hour, we probably process 10 letters or so in
that fraction of a second, almost,'' he said.
   ``In doing that, you are again putting a great deal of stress on
the stamp.''
   Morison said the problem is not acute yet, but some customers
have complained about letters that were destroyed or returned
because the stamps fell off.
   ``When you look at the magnitude of the postal service
operation, it's very minor because we carry so many pieces of mail
every day we have absolutely no problem with,'' he said.
   ``But when we see something developing, and we see there is an
issue here, then in that case we want to fix it, and get it fixed
very quickly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
