<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BogusTickets     07-29 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bogus Tickets,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Writes Bogus Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traffic cop suspected of writing more
than 1,000 bogus tickets in seven years says he didn't have the
heart to hand out the real thing.
   ``I just could not bring myself to write tickets,'' Patrolman
Michael Ghrist said Wednesday in an interview. ``I had a
conscience. I had a heart. ... I started seeing the human beings
behind the drivers' wheels.''
   Ghrist said he began to write one or two bogus tickets a week in
the names of motorists who didn't exist about a year and a half ago.
   However, Judge Donald Smalley said this week that a computer
listing of all the tickets Ghrist has written since 1981 shows that
more than 1,000 are in the names of people for whom no Kentucky
drivers license could be found.
   ``We have to assume that almost all of them are fictitious,''
Smalley said.
   Ghrist, 36, who has been with the department 17 years, was
suspended earlier this month for 25 days.
   Police Chief Richard Dotson concluded that the officer wrote
bogus tickets to maintain ``high enforcement statistics.''
   Safety Director Thomas Kuster, who suspended Ghrist, said
Wednesday he was unaware there may have been more than 1,000
questionable tickets, and Lt. Col. John Aubrey said the
investigation would be reopened.
   In a letter to Kuster, Dotson said he considered recommending
Ghrist's firing but decided on leniency because the officer was not
motivated by personal profit. For example, he passed up special pay
for court appearances.
</TEXT>
