<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CivilRightsMemorial     07-29 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Civil Rights Memorial,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Memorial Designer Unveils Civil Rights Monument</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who designed the stark Vietnam
War memorial in Washington etched with the names of the dead in the
order they were killed took a similar approach in a monument to the
civil rights movement.
   The monument here will bear the names of about 30 people killed
in the battle for racial equality from 1955 to 1968.
   ``The name is one of the most magical ways to bring back a
person,'' said Maya Lin of New York. ``It's more real than any one
image can be.''
   Ms. Lin, the 28-year-old designer of the long, black marble wall
with the names of thousands of Americans killed in Vietnam, on
Thursday attended the unveiling of her plans for the civil rights
memorial, expected to cost $350,000.
   She said learning about the history behind the names was an
important step in designing the memorial. ``Since May I've read
four books on it,'' she said.
   With the Vietnam project, Miss Lin said, she stayed away from
books and documentaries about the war while working on her design
``because I didn't want to get into the politics.''
   The new memorial will sit in front of the Southern Poverty Law
Center, a Montgomery-based, public-interest law firm specializing
in civil rights issues.
   Construction will begin later this year, with completion
scheduled for May 1989. The project will be built with by proceeds
from the recent sale of property adjacent to law center.
   Ms. Lin's design calls for an upper plaza with a quiet pool and
water that cascades down the face of a curved, black wall 40 feet
long.
   Inscribed in gold leaf on the wall will be a section of the Rev.
Martin Luther King's ``I Have a Dream Speech,'' saying: ``We will
not be satisfied until justice rolls down like water and
righteousness like a mighty stream.''
   In a lower plaza, a circular stone table 12 feet in diameter
will be inscribed with the names of people killed during the civil
rights movement. Water emerging from the center of the table will
flow evenly across its surface.
   The memorial will begin with the 1955 slaying of Emmett Till in
Money, Miss. Till, a black man, was lynched after saying ``Bye,
baby,'' to a white woman. The historical review will end April 4,
1968, the day King was assassinated in Memphis, Tenn.
   Also listed will be Medgar Evers, a Mississippi NAACP official
gunned down in front of his home in 1963; four children killed in
1963 in the bombing of a Baptist church in Birmingham, and three
civil rights activists shot to death in Philadelphia, Miss., during
the Freedom Summer of 1964.
</TEXT>
