<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Unrest,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media Report Crackdown on Continued Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media today indicated that a crackdown has
begun against those agitating for Armenian control of a disputed
region in a neighboring republic.
   The labor newspaper Trud said 44 people face criminal charges in
Yerevan, the Armenian capital, following an incident in which
Armenian activists attached slogans to their cars and drove around
the city.
   The newspaper did not indicate the date or the size of the
demonstration. It said 155 drivers had their licenses revoked and
310 were fined, indicating a sizeable turnout.
   The protest involved Aremenians' demand for control of
Nagorno-Karabakh, in the republic of Azerbaijan.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is an Armenian-dominated area. Most Armenians
are Christians, and most Azerbaijanis are Moslems.
   Demonstrations in Yerevan and in Nagorno-Karabakh began in
February. This month, Armenian officials voted to annex the
disputed region, but Azerbaijani leaders refused.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet on July 18 deemed that
Nagorno-Karabakh should remain part of Azerbaijan. The Presidium
also ordered local law enforcement agencies to ensure that order
was restored in the area.
   The official Tass news agency reported today that the situation
was stabilizing in Armenia, but it said that at ``the urging of
instigators,'' some strikes and protests continued.
   Tass said party and government leaders in the regions involved
had been penalized for failing to take appropriate action against
those organizing the unrest.
   It praised the ``vigorous stand'' taken against continued
activism.
</TEXT>
