<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FloridaGuard-Drugs     07-29 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Guard-Drugs,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guard to Assist Fight Against Drug Smuggling in South Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida will use the National Guard to
defend its borders against drug smuggling in a federally funded
program that could lead to wider use of the military in the state's
battle against narcotics.
   Maj. Gen. Robert F. Ensslin Jr., adjutant general of the
Department of Military Affairs, said only volunteers will be used
in the monthlong mission primarily in southeastern Florida, where
most of the drug activity is based.
   Ensslin said Thursday the Guard will concentrate on surveillance
and intelligence in the program beginning next week. ``There is a
very, very low danger quotient and practically no opportunity for
confrontation,'' he said.
   Guard personnel trained as military police or in the Special
Forces are particulary well suited for the job, Ensslin said.
   The pilot program will be evaluated within about a month to
decide whether it should be expanded, Ensslin.
   Authorities have estimated that up to 70 percent of the illegal
drugs entering the United States come through Florida, which has
1,350 miles of coastline.
   It is not the first time the Florida Guard has been used in
anti-drug work. In 1986, several units took park in a week-long
exercise helping state law officers search the piney woodlands of
northern Florida for marijuana fields.
   Ensslin, who would not reveal the size of the new operation.
Salaries and other costs will be covered by the federal government.
   In recent months, Gov. Bob Martinez has sought to boost federal
anti-drug assistance in Florida, meeting with Vice President George
Bush and Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
   Carlucci told Martinez he opposed using active-duty forces in
the drug war but was willing to discuss a larger role for National
Guard units.
</TEXT>
