<HEAD>Sikhs Left on Abandoned Ship to be Deported to Belgium</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT location to Nova Scotia, sted
Newfoundland.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one Indian Sikhs who were
abandoned aboard a ship off the Danish coast will be sent back to
Belgium, police said today.
   The Sikhs had been en route to Canada aboard the Belgian coaster
Byrding, which is registered in the Cayman Islands, when the crew
abandoned ship after it developed engine trouble. They were brought
ashore Tuesday by a pilot boat.
   The Sikhs, who carried no travel documents, will be deported to
Belgium, where they boarded the ship, police spokesman John
Steffensen told The Associated Press.
   The Sikhs paid for passage to Canada in India, Steffensen said.
They arrived in Belgium by airplane a few days before boarding the
Byrding last week.
   According to Danish press reports, the men eluded Belgian police
in a rubber dinghy to board the ship waiting in international
waters. The reports said they paid $3,000 to $4,000 each for the
trip.
   The Copenhagen daily Det Fri Aktuelt quoted Belgian police today
as saying the ship's captain, Rolf Nygren, a Swedish citizen, was
arrested on a beach near Veurne south of Oostende, along with 51
Sikhs who didn't manage to board the ship.
   Nygren was sentenced to one year in prison and fined $500 last
year in Nova Scotia after attempting to help 174 Sikhs enter Canada
illegally, Det Fri Aktuelt quoted court officials in Nova Scotia as
saying.
</TEXT>
