<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HelsinkiConference     07-29 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helsinki Conference,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Chief Delegate Says Agreement Still Far Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief U.S. delegate to the stalled
Helsinki conference said today the meeting ``still has a long way
to go,'' despite some progress in the human rights field by the
Soviet Union and its allies.
   The conference of Security and Cooperation in Europe had been
tentatively scheduled to end today, but delegates say it is likely
to continue into the fall.
   Despite ``some fairly substantial progress in a number of
countries, including, of course, the Soviet Union, there is still a
long way to go'' to reach agreement on a final document, U.S. chief
delegate Warren Zimmermann told reporters.
   Zimmermann said that in the Soviet Union, prisoners of
conscience and activists were in labor camps or forced exile
``because of things they have thought or things they have said.''
   ``I think time is long past when that kind of violation should
continue,'' Zimmermann said, adding that some Western radio
broadcasts, including Israeli and West German radio programs for
Soviet listeners, are still jammed in the Soviet Union.
   The Vienna meeting, attended by the Soviet Union, the United
States, Canada and all European states except Albania, began in
November 1986 to review compliance with the 1975 Helsinki Accords
on military security in Europe, economic cooperation and
humanitarian issues, including human rights.
   The delegates have been deadlocked over a final document.
Western delegates say the document should advance the provisions
contained in the 1975 accords and documents concluded at previous
follow-up meetings.
   Zimmermann singled for criticism a Romanian government project
to raze 7,000 villages in a nationwide resettlement plan that
critics say will destroy the traditional life of ethnic Hungarians.
   In Bulgaria, Zimmermann said, the 900,000-strong Turkish
minority was still being deprived of its ethnic rights.
   In May, Europe's nine neutral and non-aligned countries
introduced a draft compromise document designed to help East and
West reach a successful conclusion, but Western diplomats say
disagreement persists in the human rights area.
   ``We still have to get good agreement on such important issues
as freedom of religion, .... rights of national minorities and the
right of radio broadcasts to enter freely,'' Zimmermann said.
``Until we get an agreement on these issues, it's hard to see how
we can end this meeting.''
</TEXT>
