<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeSillers     07-29 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: DeSillers Would Be `Unjustly Enriched' By Sons Donations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money donated for Ronnie DeSillers' three liver
transplants will be used to pay medical bills, debts and help other
children in need of transplants _ and not a penny will go to the
boy's mother, a judge ruled.
   Maria DeSillers has been accused of misusing some of $689,000 in
donations that poured in before her 7-year-old son died awaiting a
fourth transplant at a Pittsburgh hospital in 1987. The donations
included $1,000 from President Reagan.
   Circuit Judge Francis Christie on Thursday refused to give Ms.
DeSillers and her former husband, Ronald, any claim to the
remaining $243,500. He said to do so would be ``erroneous and a
judicial absurdity.''
   ``To allow the contributions donated by caring and affected
American people to ... descend to Ronnie's parents ... would
unjustly enrich persons not entitled to the same,'' Christie wrote.
   The judge ordered that money in the boy's estate be used to pay
hospital bills and other debts, with any remaining money going to
other needy ill children.
   Court-appointed curator Karen Gievers, ordered to oversee the
money, hailed the decision. ``I think that this should reassure
people who gave money that it'll be used for the purpose
intended,'' she said.
   Ms. Gievers said she will try to recoup some of the $200,000 Ms.
DeSillers allegedly gave to friends and relatives or spent on such
items as jewelry and a BMW sports car.
   ``There were things done by people that should not have been
done. If they are substantial, we'll litigate,'' Ms. Gievers said.
``We'll be looking at each and every person who received the
funds.''
   The curator charges that Ms. DeSillers paid herself $96,526 from
donations, $23,700 to her boyfriend, $13,500 for the BMW, $10,850
in jewelry, $6,000 in rent for her high-rise bayfront apartment and
$8,000 in clothing and furniture. Only $44,359 was spent on other
children who required transplants, Ms. Gievers said.
   A teary-eyed Ms. DeSillers' refused to speak with reporters and
did not return a telephone call. Her attorney, Harry Robbins, said
the decision would be appealed.
   ``Maria had a dream that she wanted to realize, and now that
dream cannot come true,'' he said.
   Mrs. DeSillers is under investigation by the Dade County state
attorney's office and the Florida attorney general's office, which
are trying to determine whether she misused any of donations.
   DeSillers has denied misusing the money and said about $150,000
was sent to her directly but had been mistakenly mingled in her
son's account.
</TEXT>
