<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0450 07-29 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wooing Jackson Support; Focusing On Jobs Theme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis at auto plant, subbing top 3 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis toured a General Motors plant and campaigned among United
Auto Workers today while continuing to woo supporters of former
rival Jesse Jackson.
   ``I don't care who you were with in the primary, you're all
Democrats,'' Dukakis told a crowd of about 500 people when he
arrived at the Flint airport Thursday night. ``We're going to win
the state of Michigan and win it decisively,'' said Dukakis, who
lost this state's primary to Jackson before running off a string of
victories that secured the nomination.
   Today, Dukakis got a tour of the GM plant, ending it by driving
a new Chevy Blazer off the assembly line before meeting with the
union workers. From Flint, Dukakis was headed to Racine, Wis., to
visit a minority-owned technology company that has established
retraining programs for its workers.
   He arrived here after campaign stops in Cleveland and Secaucus,
N.J., taking time at both places to depart from his standard pledge
of ``good jobs at good wages'' to step up his attack on the ethical
standards of President Reagan and Vice President George Bush _
particularly their support of Attorney General Edwin Meese III even
after two top Meese aides quit because of his legal troubles.
   ``In a Dukakis White House, the ethics office will be in the
Oval Office, not some place down the hall,'' Dukakis said in a
swipe at the handling of Meese's troubles and Bush's call for an
ethics office in the White House.
   Dukakis also took time in Ohio and New Jersey to meet with
prominent Jackson supporters, including Newark Mayor Sharpe James
and Cleveland City Council President George Forbes.
   Also at the Ohio meeting was Arnold Pinkney, Jackson's 1984
campaign manager.
   Dukakis deputy field director Donna Brazile, a Jackson aide four
years ago, described the sessions as ``very positive'' and said the
Jackson supporters, nearly all black, had pledged their support to
Dukakis.
   Dukakis said the Jackson backers were ``very enthused and ready
to go to work.''
   James, after a meeting with Dukakis in Newark, said: ``Now we
are ready to support Michael Dukakis _ he won.'' Fingering a
campaign button on his lapel, James added: ``I have now replaced my
Jesse Jackson button with a Michael Dukakis button. We're ready to
win.''
   In Ohio, during a series of live and satellite television
interviews, Dukakis faced questioning about his selection of Texas
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate instead of the home state
favorite there, Sen. John Glenn.
   ``In the end, I just felt that Sen. Bentsen was the right
choice,'' he said.
   He also interrupted his Ohio campaigning to speak via satellite
to the United Food and Commercial Workers convention in San
Francisco, promising that if elected he would appoint members to
the National Labor Relations Board sensitive to labor needs.
   In that speech and his addresses to rallies in Secaucus and
Cleveland, Dukakis repeated many of the themes of the speech he
gave when he accepted the nomination at the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta.
   ``We can take the easy road, the downhill road, or we can put
America on the path to greatness once again,'' Dukakis told the
union conference.
   At each stop he repeated his support for an increased minimum
wage, universal health care and a trade bill containing a provision
providing advance notification for workers of plant closings.
   And he said that despite economic growth during the Reagan
administration, that prosperity has reached only the ``privileged
few.'' He predicted he would defeat Bush in November because
average Americans are concerned about the country's economic future.
   ``You cannot build a strong economic future on a credit card,''
Dukakis said in Cleveland. ``We cannot continue to borrow and spend
and borrow and spend to prosperity.''
   After the Wisconsin stop, Dukakis was headed to Illinois and
Kentucky. He was to spend tonight in Kentucky and attend events
there and in North Carolina on Saturday before returning home.
</TEXT>
