<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0493 07-29 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters' Lament: `My Gosh, I Wish It Would Rain'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with first prediction of
containment, 80 percent contained, no looting reported and
volunteer fire depts; PICKS UP the 8th graf pvs, `Gov. George...';
ADDS one graf with Wisconsin fire.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto YNP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters raced the wind today in an
attempt to beat back a forest fire that raged out of control after
destroying 15 homes on the city's edge. Officials offered a $10,000
reward in the suspected arson.
   Winds dropped to 5 mph early this morning, prompting a major
assault to take advantage of the lull and cooler temperatures. The
weather service said the wind was expected to pick up again,
reaching 15 to 25 mph by afternoon.
   But higher humidity _ a boon to firefighting _ also was expected
and crews said they hoped to complete a fire line around the
3,000-acre blaze by early Saturday, a spokesman said today. The
fire was considered 80 percent contained.
   ``It's looking a lot more positive than it has,'' said Mike
Ball, fire information officer. It's the first time since the fire
started Tuesday that firefighters have estimated when they might
get a handle on the blaze.
   In Wyoming, fire crews in Yellowstone National Park today took
the calculated risk of lighting ``burnouts'' _ igniting dead timber
and brush in an attempt to keep isolated blazes from combining into
bigger fires.
   Fires fed by drought-dried fields and forests also blackened
regions of Alaska, Montana, Idaho, California, Washington and
Wisconsin.
   In Rapid City, 15 homes and 32 outbuildings had been destroyed
and 2,800 acres burned by Thursday evening.
   ``They're going to have trouble holding the lines on the south
and southeast,'' Mary Sue Waxler, U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman,
said Thursday night. ``My gosh, I wish it would rain.''
   Earlier Thursday, officials evacuated hundreds more homes in
three subdivisions on the west side. On Thursday evening they
suggested that people leave another large rural area. Two
subdivisions remained evacuated today.
   Police Chief Tom Hennies said he had received no reports of
looting in the hundreds of homes left vacant.
   Volunteer firefighters saved 100 houses on Thursday, Ball said.
Small fire departments from around the state have brought in 65
engines to pump water onto houses to keep them from igniting while
the fire burns around them.
   Gov. George Mickelson offered the $10,000 reward in the
suspected arson. He said the state and businesses had put up the
money.
   A 14-year-old boy was arrested in connection with a small fire,
but police said they did not think he was responsible for setting
the main fire on Tuesday.
   In Yellowstone, officials acknowledged the risk of burnouts.
``But we'd rather burn this out under the best conditions we can
control instead of letting the fire run in on us uncontrolled,''
said Ken Briggeman, a fire official at the Shoshone blaze near
Grant Village.
   An update Thursday night by infrared mapping showed the number
of acres on fire down from 95,000 to about 93,000 in the 2.2
million acre park.
   The forecast for today called for ideal burning conditions _
good for the wildfires and encouraging for the burnouts _ with high
temperatures of 75-85 degrees and relative humidities of 15 percent
to 22 percent.
   A burnout is meant to destroy fallen trees, snags and brush in a
controlled manner to rob a fire of fuel to advance.
   In the 10,100-acre Shoshone fire, fire crews carrying hand-held
drip torches ignited brush and fallen trees Thursday, moving fast
to avoid the flare-up as the tinder-dry wood was torched.
   Meanwhile, heli-torches _ flame throwers on choppers _ continued
setting burnouts on the northeast flank of the 8,500-acre fire that
is threatening Old Faithful and the huge complex that surrounds the
famous geyser.
   ``We're happy with the burnout so far,'' said fire spokesman
Brian Fox. ``Once we get the northeast head of the fire dealt with,
it can go north, away from Old Faithful.''
   About 50 people forced from their houses by the marauding
900-acre Madison Gulch timber fire in western Montana were expected
to return to their homes today, the U.S. Forest Service said.
   In Alaska, firefighters were battling only 16 of 51 wind-whipped
fires. Bureau of Land Management spokesman Bill Rockwell said
summer fires have blackened 1.4 million acres in Alaska.
   Ten families remained evacuated from their homes near the
3,000-acre Willis Gulch fire northeast of Boise, Idaho, as the
state imposed strict fire restrictions on government land
throughout the dry southern part of the state.
   Hundreds of firefighters in Washington state continued to battle
a stubborn 3,600-acre forest fire that consumed old-growth timber
and logging trees in the Cascade Mountains.
   In California, firefighters were working on scores of small
fires throughout the Sierra Nevada range, most of them caused by
lightning. But a fire that burned about 30 acres Wednesday near
Coulterville, destroying four structures and forcing the evacuation
of up to 70 homes, was blamed on a careless 13-year-old smoker.
   Near Washburn, Wis., firefighters from Minnesota, Missouri and
Illinois joined today to help fight a fire that has burned about
350 acres at the Chequamegaon National Forest, officials said.
</TEXT>
