<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zimbabwe-SouthAfrica     07-29 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zimbabwe-South Africa,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Charged with Murder and Terrorism for Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two white Zimbabweans and a black former
policeman were indicted today on charges of murder, terrorism and
sabotage for a car-bomb attack on guerrillas fighting the South
African government.
   Kevin Woods, 35, Michael Smith, 34, and Phillip Conjwayo, 54,
are accused of being South African agents. They were arrested after
a car bomb demolished part of a house occupied by officials of the
African National Congress in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe on Jan. 11. Some
occupants of the house were injured.
   The African National Congress is the main guerrilla group
fighting South Africa's government.
   In a brief hearing at the Chikurubi maximum-security prison near
Harare, prosecutor Yunus Omerjee said the murder charges related to
the death of Obert Mwanza, the driver of the car.
   Mwanza apparently was hired to drive the car and did not know it
was booby-trapped.
   In the hearing, the state alleged that Woods, Smith and
Conjwayo, acting as agents for Pretoria, carried out the
car-bombing and other acts of terrorism and sabotage punishable by
death or life imprisonment under Zimbabwe laws.
   Fourteen whites and three blacks are awaiting trial on capital
charges for attacks on ANC facilities in Zimbabwe.
   Woods is a former officer in Zimbabwe's central intelligence
organization. Conjwayo served as a special branch police officer
before white-ruled Rhodesia became black-governed Zimbabwe in 1980.
   The three were ordered to appear in court October 12.
   Hearings on security charges have been held in jails rather than
courts since an abortive attempt June 30 to free Woods and four
other alleged South African agents on their way from Chikurubi
prison to the main courthouse in Harare.
</TEXT>
