<DOCNO> AP880729-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SonofHeaven 1stLd-Writethru a0473 07-29 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Son of Heaven, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0473,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Son Of Heaven: Treasures Of Chinese Emperors Get First U.S.
Showing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `By sharing ...' to CORRECT to two-city sted
eight-city tour.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RENEE SCHOOF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasures hoarded by China's emperors for more
than 2,000 years go on display here today, with jewels, terra cotta
warriors, a golden dragon throne and jade burial costume rivaling
the splendors of King Tut.
   More than 90 percent of the 221 artifacts on loan from the
People's Republic of China in the Son of Heaven exhibit have never
been seen in the United States, and 80 percent have never left
China, officials said.
   ``Through it, all Americans will come to know China as few in
the world ever have,'' former President Richard Nixon said in a
letter to his brother Ed, who lives in the Seattle area, that was
shared with Chinese officials.
   The scope and quality of the exhibits are the greatest ever lent
by the Chinese government, according to Xie Chengsheng of China's
Ministry of Culture.
   Nixon, who normalized U.S. relations with China in the early
1970s, wanted to attend today's opening but couldn't for health
reasons, said Jeri McDonald of Son of Heaven Inc., a local group
that helped organize the exhibit.
   The 74-year-old former president, who lives in Saddle River,
N.J., had prostate surgery last month.
   The exhibit, which promoters say is four times larger than the
King Tut show that thrilled America a decade ago, was created
largely from archaeological discoveries and research in China since
the Communists took power in 1949. Its treasures come from 21
museums and institutions in eight provinces and Beijing.
   The exhibit at the Seattle Center, coming soon after the success
of the Academy Award-winning movie ``The Last Emperor,'' is
expected to draw more than a million people before closing Dec. 31.
It will move to Columbus, Ohio, for a March-September run before
returning to China.
   ``The objects in this exhibition reflect the special traits of
Chinese art as well as the high level of archaeological discoveries
and research in contemporary China,'' Xie said here earlier this
summer.
   ``By sharing them, we hope to strengthen the bonds of mutual
friendship and understanding between our two countries,'' said Xie,
who led a delegation from the Cultural Relics Bureau that selected
Seattle and Columbus for the two-city tour.
   Preview glimpses of the exhibit were offered Thursday.
   It consists of a video show on China's imperial history and five
galleries illustrating the emperor's ritual, public and private
life, his role in Chinese religious teachings and his belief in an
afterlife.
   The emperor of China was considered the son of heaven, and was
believed to own and control everything under heaven.
   Like high officials of 18th century China, visitors approach a
dragon throne of gold, silk and lacquer, with peacock feathers
above and an intricate carpet beneath that represents imperial
China in a time of great strength.
   While not arranged chronologically, the exhibit illustrates how
emperors lived and ruled over 26 centuries from 221 B.C. until 1911.
   Among the treasures are a set of 26 bells from the 6th century
B.C., robes only the emperor could wear, paintings, jewelry,
household items, and a 2nd century jade burial suit believed to
possess magical properties to preserve the body of the princess
placed inside it for eternity.
   The life-size terra cotta figures, four warriors and two horses,
were selected from thousands found near the famed tomb of Qin
Shihuang Di in Xian, in central China, in 1974.
   The exhibit was planned over nearly four years by the Chinese
Overseas Archaeological Exhibition Corp. of Beijing, a division of
the Ministry of Culture, and Son of Heaven Inc.
   The idea for the show came from Deng Pufang, son of Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping, who passed it to Harvey West, a former
director of the University of Washington's Henry Art Gallery, Ms.
McDonald said. West arranged for private sponsorhip of the exhibit.
   General admission to the show is $7.50. The proceeds will
benefit Chinese archaeology and other causes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
