<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Jackson     07-29 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Jackson,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson's Secret Service Protection Extended One Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan approved a 30-day extension
of Secret Service protection for Jesse Jackson, at a cost of
roughly $600,000, because of Jackson's concerns regarding threats
against his life, Reagan's spokesman said today.
   Marlin Fitzwater said the president would not approve extension
of the protection through the fall election campaign.
   Reagan's decision authorized an extension from the day after the
Democratic National Convention concluded to Aug. 22.
   Fitzwater said Jackson's request for an extension was ``based on
his assessments of threats against his life and his plan to be an
active participant'' in the campaign.
   Jackson's Secret Service protection technically was to have been
withdrawn on July 22, after his presidential candidacy ended with
the Democratic nomination of Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts.
But Fitzwater said the protection had been maintained without
interruption while Reagan weighed whether to approve the extension.
   Fitzwater said the 30-day extension would give Jackson a
transition period in which to arrange for private bodyguards.
   ``The feeling was that, first of all, he's not the nominee of
the party,'' the spokesman said.
   However, he said there had been precedents for extending normal
Secret Service protection for government officials because of
extenuating circumstances.
</TEXT>
