<HEAD>Court Tosses Out Trustee's Open Meeting Law Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has overturned the
conviction of the first public official sent to jail for violating
Oklahoma's open meeting law.
   The Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals cited new evidence in the
case in throwing out the 1986 conviction and the one-year jail term
and $5,400 fine handed Melvin Weeks, 41, a former Wister town
trustee.
   Meeks was convicted on 11 violations of the 1977 law. Two others
on the Wister Board of Trustees pleaded guilty to one violation and
testified against Meeks.
   Weeks was accused of failing to post agendas, failing to keep
minutes and holding illegal executive sessions in 1985 while a
member of the town board and the Wister Public Works and Wister
Economic Development authorities.
