<HEAD>McDonald's Restaurant Drops Age Restriction That Sparked Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A McDonald's restaurant has lifted its
nighttime ban on customers under 16, says a lawyer for a
13-year-old who sued over the policy.
   The age-discrimination suit, filed by attorney Gloria R. Allred,
alleged that Tracy Tellez was told to leave the Valencia restaurant
halfway through her meal Jan. 22 under a policy aimed at curbing
teen-age vandalism.
   ``I'm glad this is settled because I think teen-agers should be
treated equally,'' the girl said as she ate a McDonald's
cheeseburger in Allred's office Thursday.
   A spokesman for the restaurant said the policy against
youngsters after 9 p.m. had already been rescinded when the suit
was filed March 15.
   The policy was initiated earlier this year after Friday night
crowds tore out chairs and defaced table tops with graffiti,
employees said.
