<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-USBases     07-29 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-US Bases,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.,Greece Conclude Eighth Round of Base Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American negotiators today
wrapped up an eighth round of talks on a new U.S. military bases
agreement to replace an accord that expires in December.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said the negotiations
were held in a ``professional atmosphere'' but added that there
``continued to be a difference of views on the issues being
discussed.''
   Negotiations for a new U.S. base agreement are moving more
slowly than U.S. officials would like.
   On July 13, the government issued a formal shut-down notice for
all U.S. military bases operating in Greece. The notice, a legal
formality, is not expected to result in any of the bases being
closed.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou insists that the United States should
help solve Greek-Turkish disputes over military control of the
Aegean and the divided island of Cyprus in return for a new base
agreement.
   But the United States doesn't want to link a new accord with
regional politics.
   Kostopoulos described as ``completely inaccurate'' a report in
Jane's Defence Weekly that U.S. air base facilites in Athens would
be transferred to Souda Bay in Crete.
   According to the report, the United States agreed to remove the
U.S. Air Force base from Hellenikon Airport and transfer it to
Souda Bay in Crete as part of an ``alternative solution.''
   Since the 1950s, the United States has operated four military
bases in Greece _ two near Athens and two on the southern island of
Crete. As a form of rent for the bases, Greece receives more than
$300 million yearly in U.S. military credits.
   Papandreou, who came to power in 1981 pledging to shut down the
American bases, now says his socialist government is willing to
sign a new agreement, provided it is first approved in a referendum.
   Further negotiations are scheduled for September in Athens,
Kostopoulos said.
</TEXT>
