<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlantBlast     07-29 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Blast,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Safety Officials Seek Fines In Rocket Fuel Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of a rocket fuel plant
destroyed in an explosion May 4 says he will contest $36,455 in
fines for 30 alleged safety violations.
   The Nevada Division of Occupational Safety and Health is seeking
the fines against Pacific Engineering and Production Co. The blast
killed two employees at a Henderson plant, injured 326 others and
caused about $73 million in damage.
   The fines were disclosed Thursday by Joseph Kirkbride,
information director for the U.S. Department of Labor's regional
office in San Francisco. Under state law the Nevada agency is
barred from discussing the case.
   Fred Gibson, chairman and chief executive officer for the
company, called the allegations ``wholly without merit, all of
them, based on unsubstantiated allegations that have not yet been
proven.''
   ``We have asked for the evidence and whatever other data these
charges are based on. DOSH has absolutely refused to furnish us
anything,'' he added.
   ``We understand these charges are based on interviews subsequent
to the May 4 explosion, so there is no evidence other than the
allegations.''
   Gibson said the company will contest the fines before an
occupational safety and health review panel and, if ncessary, in
court.
   Company executives blamed the explosion on a leaking natural gas
line that ran under the plant, but the Clark County Fire Department
said earlier this month that it was sparked by a welder's torch.
   Fire Chief Roy Parrish said 8.5 million pounds of ammonium
perchlorate, a fuel oxidizer used in the space shuttle and military
missiles, was destroyed in the series of blasts at the plant 20
miles from Las Vegas.
   The charges include four willful violations such a exposing
employees to possible fire or explosion through a lack of
manufacturing controls and operating procedures, Kirkbride said.
   The state also charged a lack of emergency evacuation and
response procedures, inadequate access to respirators and a lack of
entry procedures exposed workers to potentially hazardous levels of
toxic fumes, suffocation and death.
</TEXT>
