<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Navy-Doves     07-29 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Navy-Doves,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dove Project A Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy operation to frighten away
doves that damaged engines and got in the way of planes at
Jacksonville Naval Air Station was such a success that it ended a
day early.
   Navy volunteers this week set off fireworks and fired guns to
frighten the flock of doves, and on Thursday spotted only four
doves in three hours.
   ``Those four were in the air. They were trying to get out of
town. I consider the bird program almost 100 percent successful,''
said W.J. Meyer, airfield manager.
   Fifteen volunteer bird hunters began working Tuesday and had
expected to be busy through Friday. Thirty to 35 birds were shot
this week, most of them on the ground, Meyer said.
   Birds began flocking to the runway July 22 after grass was mowed
and grass seeds dropped to the ground.
   A P-3 Orion had to abort a takeoff after birds damaged two of
its four engines. In addition, a bird flew into and damaged another
P-3 engine.
</TEXT>
