<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusShooting     07-29 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Shooting,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunfire on Bus Kills Driver, Wounds Passengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four young men boarded a bus at a
downtown stop early today and sprayed the vehicle with
semi-automatic gunfire, killing the driver and wounding four
passengers, police said.
   The gunmen, in their late teens and early 20s, fled on foot,
police said.
   The motive in the attack was not immediately known, but robbery
was ruled out, said Lt. Jim Hahn.
   Investigators were examining whether the attack was drug-related
retaliation against one of the passengers, or a revenge shooting
against the bus authority, Hahn said. At least a dozen shots were
fired, police said.
   ``As the bus passed the shop where I was working in the window I
heard _ Bang! Bang! Bang! Bang! And Bang! _ six to 10 shots, and
then the bus stopped,'' said a 15-year-old girl who did not want to
be identified.
   She said she saw at least three people run from the bus, one of
whom collapsed on the ground holding his stomach. She said the
driver was slumped in his seat, with wounds to the head and torso.
   Driver Billy ``B.J.'' Givens, 43, died about an hour after he
was hit by gunfire several times, Hahn said.
   Passengers suffered wounds ranging from minor to critical, he
said. Details on their injuries were withheld.
   The bus line on which the attack occurred runs through one of
the city's poorest and most violence-plagued neigbhorhoods.
   Givens was a dapper man who had worked for the transit authority
for 20 years, receiving several citations for politeness and
helpfulness, awards determined by customer praise, said Mike Mills,
a spokesman for the agency.
   ``I think if one were to characterize the feeling here it would
be one of shock, of grief, of puzzlement, of why this sort of thing
would happen, and to this man,'' Mills said.
</TEXT>
