<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PremaritalViolence     07-29 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Premarital Violence,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds More Violence Among Unmarried Couples Living Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Couples who live together are more likely
than married couples to be involved in violent conflicts, possibly
because married partners have a greater emotional investment in the
relationship, a study says.
   The study by University of New Hampshire professors Murray
Straus and Jan Stets found violence occurred among 35 percent of
the 237 cohabiting couples surveyed, 14 percent of the 5,005
married couples and 20 percent of the 526 dating couples.
   ``Every kind of intimate relationship has a risk of violence,''
Straus said Thursday.
   Cohabiting couples often are socially isolated, lacking the
network of relatives that many married couples rely on to help
resolve conflicts, he said. They also lack the material and
emotional investment of married couples, he said.
   Though both married and cohabiting couples may share a high
level of conflict from living together, a married couple is more
likely to shun violence to avoid risking the relationship and
losing the investment, he said.
   About two-thirds of the violence involved slapping, throwing
objects, pushing or shoving, he said. Some violent episodes were
more severe, involving kicking and punching.
   The findings will be presented to the American Sociological
Association conference Aug. 25 in Atlanta.
 
</TEXT>
