<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-BeginBirthday     07-29 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Begin Birthday,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Wishes Happy Birthday To Reclusive Begin on 75th Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin, who
received two birthday cakes and 75 roses for his 75th birthday,
chatted Friday with his successor Yitzhak Shamir about everything
from Soviet-Israeli relations to recent Arab unrest.
   In a rare interview with Israel radio, the reclusive Begin, who
marks his birthday Saturday, said in a hoarse voice that he would
spend the day reading. ``Those who remember (my birthday) and want
to come _ come,'' he said.
   Begin's longtime aide Yehiel Kadashai said about 150 friends and
relatives of the former prime minister will visit his home at the
edge of the Jerusalem Forest on Saturday to offer birthday
greetings.
   Begin, who led his country to war in Lebanon and to peace with
Egypt, was once the fiery leader of the right-wing Likud bloc, now
led by Shamir.
   Today, the Nobel Prize winner rarely leaves his house and
entertains guests infrequently. But on Friday he met his successor
for 35 minutes.
   ``Mr. Begin is in a good mood and excellent health,'' Shamir
told reporters outside Begin's house. He said the two had spoken
``about everything, of course, including politics.''
   Shamir's aides said Shamir did not bring Begin a present. But
Jerusalem's Plaza Hotel brought in a huge round cake decorated with
the figure 75, and the city's King David hotel sent a heart-shaped
marzipan cake and a basket with 75 white and red roses.
   Passers-by stopped to look at the modest home, which is
protected by metal bars on the windows and guarded by a security
officer in a glass booth.
   ``I wish Begin (to live) until 120,'' a young woman named Geula
shouted in a popular Israeli expression.
   Shamir said he and Begin discussed the nearly 8-month-old
Palestinian rebellion in the Israeli-occupied territories, and that
the former leader ``thinks it will pass.''
   He said Begin was very pleased to hear about the first trip of
an Israeli diplomatic group to Moscow since 1967 and ``hopes to see
positive developments.''
   Shamir said the two men also discussed elections scheduled for
November, but he was not sure if Begin would use his popularity to
give Likud a boost in the campaign. ``It depends on him,'' Shamir
said.
   Begin's 45-year-old son, Benny, has been chosen by Likud to run
as a candidate for parliament in the Nov. 1 elections.
   Shamir added that he regularly confers with Begin about current
political affairs.
   Begin was elected prime minister in 1977. In 1978 he shared the
Nobel Peace Prize with Egyptian President Anwar Sadat for the
process leading to their historic peace treaty, signed the next
year.
   In 1982, Begin led Israel's invasion of Lebanon, beginning a
three-year war. He resigned in 1983, never publicly giving a reason.
   Aides said he was depressed by Israeli casualties in Lebanon and
the death in 1982 of his wife, Aliza.
</TEXT>
