<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0418 07-29 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0418,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General Says Talks Not In Trouble</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 11 grafs with Perez de Cuellar denying talks in
trouble, scheduling meeting with Iranian envoy but not Iraq. Picks
up 8th pvs, `U.N. negotiations...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
today denied that his peace talks with Iran and Iraq are in trouble
because of Iraq's insistence on a face-to-face meeting with its foe.
   The secretary-general scheduled a meeting later with the Iranian
foreign minister, but not with Iraq's envoy.
   ``Be patient,'' he told reporters. ``And we will make progress
rather soon ... I am constantly in touch with the parties. I keep
working.''
   Perez de Cuellar said he would speak to Foreign Minister Tariq
Aziz of Iraq when he needs to see him.
   Aziz has not met Perez de Cuellar since their first two meetings
Wednesday, when Aziz stated that there could be no cease-fire in
the Iran-Iraq war without direct talks with Iran.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, has met the
secretary-general four times. Iran has rejected direct talks with
Iraq before a cease-fire.
   Perez de Cuellar said he set no deadline for the talks and would
work through the weekend.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, have
said the talks are faltering over Iraq's insistence on direct talks.
   U.N. officials said a U.N. team of military experts would arrive
in Baghdad tonight to work out details for a cease-fire. The team
has been in Tehran.
   Iran and Iraq accused each other Thursday of blocking the U.N.
efforts to end their 8-year-old war.
   Perez de Cuellar acknowledged an impasse and, when asked if he
had a formula for breaking it, said: ``I'm working on that.'' But
he added, ``At some stage, direct talks are indispensable.''
   U.N. negotiations toward ending the war are being conducted
under Security Council Resolution 598, which Iraq agreed to soon
after it was adopted in July last year but which Iran did not
accept until this month.
   It provides for a cease-fire followed by withdrawal to
recognized borders, prisoner exchange, peace negotiations and an
investigation of which side started the war.
   ``The policy of Iraq is to put obstacles in the way of the
secretary-general's peace efforts,'' said Mohammad Javad Zarif,
counselor at Iran's U.N. Mission. ``This whole Iraqi exercise is
planned to sabotage the efforts upon which the international
community is looking with hope.''
   Velayati accepted all of Perez de Cuellar's proposals on
implementing the peace plan. Iraq has not yet responded, and
details of the proposals have not been disclosed.
   Iraq's U.N. mission accused Iran of ``simply seeking a hasty
truce without giving any commitments that it will comply honestly
and sincerely to the full implementation of the resolution as a
plan for comprehensive and durable peace.''
   Both sides reported fighting Thursday at Eslamabad, 60 miles
inside Iran. Iraq, which says it has withdrawn from Iranian
territory, describes the invaders as Iranian rebels, but Iran says
they are Iraqi troops.
   In Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, Saadun Hamadi, the acting foreign
minister, summoned the ambassadors of the five permanent Security
Council members _ United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and
France _ and insisted on a peace treaty.
   ``This is the only way to secure a peaceful settlement'' of the
war, Iraqi television quoted him as saying.
   But he added that ``Iraq is for an early, immediate cease-fire
as a means to end the war within the framework of a comprehensive
peace settlement.''
   Pressure was increasing on Iraq in the 15-member Security
Council to drop its direct talks demand and other proposals that
could prolong the fighting, said U.N. diplomats who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Velayati and Aziz did not visit U.N. headquarters Thursday.
Perez de Cuellar suspended talks for a day to study his exchanges
with the Iraqi and Iranian envoys since Tuesday.
   Perez de Cuellar said he hoped Iranian officials ``are
reflecting on the possibility of having direct talks at some
stage,'' but said he cannot compel the two sides to do so if Iran
is unwilling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
