<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Red Flag,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China to Produce Red Flag Limousines Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Flag, the hulking black limousine
preferred by China's top revolutionaries, will return to production
in 1989 after an eight-year suspension, the official People's Daily
reported Friday.
   The Changchun No. 1 Motor Vehicle Plant in northeast China is to
resume production of the CA770, one of three models of the Red Flag
produced at the plant between 1958 and 1980, the overseas edition
of the paper said.
   China produced 1,516 Red Flag limos in the past for use by
Chinese leaders such as Mao Tse-tung and visiting foreign
dignitaries.
   Some top leaders, including Deng Xiaoping, still use Red Flags,
although Mercedes Benz and Japanese luxury cars have generally
replaced the Red Flag as favored transportation for ranking Chinese.
   China's auto industry went into decline around the time the Red
Flag went out of production, but has recently shown signs of
revival following the imposition of high tariffs on imports.
</TEXT>
