<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cyprus     07-29 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cyprus,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cypriot President Appealing For Removal Of Turkish Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus, in the
United States on a 10-day visit, will appeal to President Reagan to
persuade Turkey to withdraw its troops and Turkish settlers from
the island.
   Cyprus has been divided since a Turkish invasion 14 years ago.
Vassilou proposed the demilitarization of the country and the
creation of a federalized republic.
   His schedule called first for a meeting late Friday with
Secretary of State George P. Shultz to be followed on Monday by a
30-minute meeting with Reagan and a separate session with Lt. Gen.
Colin Powell, the president's national security adviser.
   Vassilou will meet also with the Republican and Democratic
presidential aspirants, Vice President George Bush and Gov. Michael
S. Dukakis, as well as congressional leaders.
   ``The United States can play a very important role in assisting
in the achievement of a settlement of the Cyprus problem ... not by
pressuring, but by persuading Turkey to withdraw its troops,''
Vassiliou said before his departure from Cyrpus.
   ``I will tell Mr. Reagan that the settlement of the Cyprus
problem is very simple. He is the greatest advocate of the
withdrawal of foreign troops and the full implementation of human
rights. I will tell him, I want only this, and nothing more.''
   Vassiliou added that a Cyprus settlement ``is to everyone's
benefit, including Turkey.''
   He said the continuation of the Turkish occupation of the
northern part of the east Mediterranean island poisons relations
between Greece and Turkey. The two NATO allies have approached the
brink of war in recent years because of long-standing differences
over Cyprus and oil-prospecting rights in the Aegean Sea.
   Vassiliou said violation of human rights in Cyprus by Turkey
caused by the occupation also were an obstacle to Turkey's
application for full membership in the European Economic Community.
   Vassiliou, the leader of the majority Greek Cypriot community on
the island, said ``the United States has every reason to want
progress on the Cyprus problem, and I believe that it will help
toward a Cyprus settlement.''
</TEXT>
