<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MissouriPrimary     07-29 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missouri Primary,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearnes, Cryts Expected To Win Primary Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri voters decide Tuesday
whether to raise the jackpot limit on their struggling lottery and
whether to give former first lady Betty Hearnes a chance to be the
state's first female governor.
   In other primaries, Rep. Richard Gephardt, who filed at the last
minute for a seventh term after dropping his presidential bid,
faces three little-known Democrats. Several candidates from both
parties had entered the race for the 3rd District, which includes
part of St. Louis and its suburbs, but most of the Democrats bowed
out when Gephardt's plans changed.
   And Democratic farm activist Wayne Cryts will try to win his
party's nomination for the 8th District congressional seat. That
would entitle him to a rematch with Republican Rep. Bill Emerson,
who won by 8,000 out of 150,000 votes cast in 1986.
   In 1981, Cryts gained national attention by taking 32,000
bushels of his family's soybeans out of a grain elevator that went
into bankruptcy and was padlocked.
   Cryts is expected to easily knock off his three primary
opponents.
   Mrs. Hearnes, 61, who paints herself as a compassionate friend
of working Missourians, is considered the Democrats' best bet for
unseating Republican Gov. John Ashcroft.
   She's expected to face little trouble with her only primary
opposition, Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed, a St. Louis area teacher who is
making his second bid for governor.
   ``Sure, lightning could strike and something could happen, but
the Democrats don't seem to have much of a primary fight,'' said
Todd Patterson, executive director of the Missouri Democratic
Party. ``I just can't imagine Betty and Wayne not winning.''
   Mrs. Hearnes' husband, Warren, served as governor during
1965-73. She was first elected to the state House in 1979. She has
the backing of party regulars and has already launched a television
campaign.
   Primary races have been overshadowed by campaigns for key
constitutional amendments that will be on the primary ballot.
   One would remove most spending restrictions on Missouri's
2{-year-old lottery, a change supporters call crucial in light of a
$24 million drop in sales during the last fiscal year. Officials
say the decline was probably caused by a lack of advertising.
   Current restrictions require that 45 percent of lottery proceeds
go for prizes, 45 percent to the state and 10 percent for
administrative costs, including advertising.
   Critics say the 45 percent prize limit does not allow the
lottery to compete with neighboring states with higher prize
structures. The amendment would change the prize limit to a minimum
of 45 percent, and lottery officials would like to give out about
50 percent in prizes. It would also permit the state to spend more
on advertising.
   Another constitutional change would reduce from two-thirds to
four-sevenths the vote majority needed to pass bond issues for
street and bridge repairs, schools and other facilities.
   Supporters say Missouri is one of only five states that require
the two-thirds majority, which they say unfairly limits school
districts and cities in their abililty to make improvements.
   In five of Missouri's six statewide offices up for election this
year, Republican incumbents, such as Ashcroft and Sen. John
Danforth, face no primary opposition.
   And although neither Danforth nor his Democratic challenger,
state Sen. Jay Nixon, face primary opposition, the race has turned
into one of the hottest of the summer as Nixon tries to chip away
at Danforth's support.
   One of the most crowded primary races is the shoot-out going on
in southwest Missouri's 7th District congressional district, where
four Republicans and three Democrats are running to replace
retiring Rep. Gene Taylor, a Republican.
   About 900,000 voters, or one-third of the state's registered
voters, are expected to go to the polls Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
