<HEAD>Turtle Found Shot To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bullet-tattered carcass of a
1,000-pound leatherback turtle, spanning seven feet, has washed
ashore, officials said.
   The female turtle was shot in the back six to eight times,
lifeguard Stuart Fraser said after the turtle was found Thursday
morning at Victoria Beach.
   John Cunningham, a former lifeguard and director of Friends of
the Sea Lion, said a representative from the National Marine
Fisheries, the federal agency responsible for marine life, will
participate in a necropsy Friday.
   The turtle was at least 70 years old, Cunningham said. It is
breeding season for the turtles, but it was unknown if she was
bearing eggs.
   The turtle had been dead about two days, he said.
   Friends of the Sea Lion is a non-profit, educational
organization that runs a rehabilitation center for injured marine
animals. It usually takes care of seals and sea lions.
