<HEAD>Japanese National Arrested For Tearing Up Philippine Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a Japanese man on
Friday after he ripped up Philippine currency in front of customs
officials.
   Chiaki Uneoka, 37, who was preparing to leave for Tokyo, tore up
1,320 pesos ($65) after learning that departing tourists are only
allowed to bring 500 pesos ($25) out of the country, said customs
officer Clarita Balite.
   The government news agency said Uneoka was charged with
violating a Central Bank circular prohibiting the mutilation of
Philippine currency.
   Under Philippine law, a person can be fined 20,000 pesos
($1,000) or imprisoned for five years if convicted of mutilating or
defacing currency.
