<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Harris     07-29 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Harris,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Pilot Claimed He Was First To Save Life With Parachute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold R. Harris, an aviation pioneer and
airline executive who claimed to be the first person to save his
own life with a free-fall parachute, has died at the age of 92.
   Harris, who rose to the presidency of Northwest Airlines, died
at home Thursday.
   He began his aviation career in 1917 in the Army Signal Corps,
which sent him to test Caproni bombers in Italy.
   His live-saving use of a free-fall parachute, activated by the
user rather than by a static line on the plane, occurred Oct. 20,
1922, while he worked as a test pilot. He said he had to jump when
the experimental plane he was flying over Dayton, Ohio, began
breaking up.
   ``I pulled the parachute release ring, or what I thought was the
release ring ... found I was falling with my head down, my feet
pointing to the sky and my body rotating,'' Harris said in a 1987
interview.
   ``I pulled the release ring and the parachute promptly turned me
rightside up. I remember looking at the parachute and wondering how
such a great expanse of white silk could be so clean, even though
it had plenty of opportunity to be soiled in a dirty hangar.''
   He landed on brick pavement under a grape arbor near McCook
Field, where the flight had begun.
   Harris also flew as a cropduster in the Midwest and Latin
America, and helped set up the Peruvian Airways Corp., the first
U.S. flag airline south of the equator.
   In 1942, he returned to military service to help organize the
Air Transport Command. He retired from the Air Force in 1945 as a
brigadier general.
   In the next two decades, Harris was vice president of American
Overseas Airlines, Atlantic Division vice president of Pan American
World Airways, president of Northwest Airlines and president of
Aviation Financial Services. He retired in 1965.
   He is survived by a son, a daughter and four grandchildren.
   A memorial service is planned Sunday in Falmouth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
