<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WaterRights     07-29 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Rights,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Says Wilderness Areas Have No Implied Rights to Water</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel, proclaiming a
major victory for water users in the West, said today the Reagan
administration has taken the position that wilderness areas have no
implied rights to water.
   Hodel told a news conference that Atty. Gen. Edwin Meese III has
concurred with the department solicitor's legal opinion that
Congress must specifically award water when it creates a wilderness
area.
   Hodel noted that there are conflicting U.S. District Court
opinions taking opposite sides of a major question in the arid
West: without a specific statement by Congress, is a wilderness
area guaranteed the water it needs for proper management?
   ``The current administration feels threatened in the West
because of the all-out offensive by (Democratic presidential
nominee) Michael Dukakis,'' said Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo., who sat
in the audience at the news conference, which he said simply
reiterated policy the administration has been following.
   The action runs counter to a U.S. District Court ruling in
Colorado in 1985 and to a 1979 ruling by an Interior Department
solicitor during the Carter administration, said Maggie Fox of the
Sierra Club.
   ``This marks a new low in Meese's and Hodel's flagrant disregard
for the law,'' she said. ``I am surprised that they could find an
attorney willing to sign his name to the document.''
   Hodel said the administration was coming down on the side of a
recent ruling in New Mexico that there are no water guarantees
unless Congress writes them into wilderness legislation.
   Congress has been skirting the issue in wilderness bills,
remaining silent on water rights and leaving the question up to the
Interior and Agriculture departments and court rulings.
   Hodel noted that very frequently, ``in order to get this water
(for wilderness), you have to take it away from someone else.''
   He said that under the policy, the administration would not go
to court to argue that wilderness areas have implied water rights.
   In a letter to Hodel, Meese said that without directives from
Congress, the government will handle water needs of wilderness
areas under the various state mechanisms that apportion water among
often-competing users.
   Hodel said the policy has ``the distinct possibility'' of
extending beyond the current administration because ``there would
be a substantial burden of proof on a new attorney general to sweep
this aside.''
   ``This is a major victory for the western states, water users
and the principles of federalism,'' said Hodel, flanked by a group
of Republican lawmakers from the West.
   ``Congress did not intend to reserve federal water rights for
wilderness purposes when it created the national wilderness
preservation system in 1964,'' he said.
   Hodel said the rights of existing water users, including federal
forests, parks and wilderness areas and Indian tribes, would be
protected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
