<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-29 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats Say Foreign Missions Sending Staff Home From Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several countries have begun calling
their diplomats home from Kabul after a barrage of guerrilla rocket
attacks on the Afghan capital, Western diplomats said Friday.
   Within one week in mid-July, as many as 200 rockets blasted
Kabul.
   A rocket smashed into a wing of the French Embassy on Saturday,
damaging the ambassador's residence but causing no injuries.
Another rocket landed near the U.S. Embassy compound, blowing out
windows in a nearby apartment building and the Radio Afghanistan
complex, the diplomats said.
   Earlier this month, a rocket hit a club that is a gathering spot
for diplomats, and one person was injured.
   Western diplomats said most foreign missions have already sent
dependents home while others are planning to soon. They spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In Washington, Charles E. Redman, the State Department
spokesman, said he did not know of any damage to the U.S. Embassy
in recent days. He declined to say how many U.S. officials were
assigned to Kabul.
   ``I don't know of any plans to change our presence,'' he said.
   The thinning out of foreign personnel in Kabul has been a
two-phased exercise, said diplomatic sources, with the Eastern
European missions making the first move. Most senior personnel at
these missions left the Afghan capital under the pretext of
``vacations,'' said diplomats.
   ``Very junior personnel'' now head most East European missions,
they said.
   The diplomats continued to emphasize the increased role of
Soviet forces in the defense of Kabul. After a year's absence,
Soviet armor has been redeployed to the west of the city in the
Lake Kargha and Paghman area.
   Western diplomats said the government's control of the key
district town of Paghman, nine miles west of the capital, is in
jeopardy.
   Earlier reports claimed 4,000 Afghan guerrillas massed around
Paghman, and diplomats said Soviet and Afghan army troops as well
as officers with the Afghan secret service, Khad, and army commando
units moved into the Paghman plain to reinforce embattled
government troops.
   The growing involvement of Soviet forces in the defense of the
capital has increased speculation about the Afghan government's
chances of survival once the Soviet troop pullout is completed.
   An April 14 accord negotiated by the United Nations provided for
the phased withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan. Half of
the estimated 100,000 troops are to be out by Aug. 15 and the
remainder by Feb. 15.
   Soviet troops and tanks moved into Afghanistan in December 1979
to prop up the struggling communist government.
   The diplomats also said Soviet forces backing Afghanistan's
Marxist government are now fully responsible for defense of Kabul
airport, which is a consistent target of rocket attacks by Afghan
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     07-29 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Paralyzes Occupied Lands, Three Reported Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arabs in the occupied territories staged a
near-total commercial strike Friday in a show of solidarity with
Arab women held in Israeli jails. Three Arabs were reported wounded
in clashes in the Gaza Strip.
   An extremist faction of the Palestine Liberation Organization
called on residents of the West Bank and Gaza Strip to reject
negotiations with Israel.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine put out a
leaflet calling dialogue with Israel an illusion. It criticized PLO
spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif, who recently advocated
Palestinian-Israeli talks under the auspices of an international
conference.
   ``At the same time your uprising is getting better and better,
some in the field are going back to their old tactics and trying
the way of dialogue and negotiations,'' said the leaflet, which was
distributed in Arab east Jerusalem. ``These are nothing but
illusions.''
   In another development, Palestinian leaders were divided in
their reactions to Jordan's decision on Thursday to cancel a $1.3
billion development fund for the occupied territories.
   Pro-Jordanian figures who favor continued Jordanian involvement
in the territories said the cancellation would increase hardships
for Palestinians, who have already suffered considerably during the
uprising.
   Deposed Gaza City Mayor Rashad Shawaa, alligned with Jordan,
said the move was ``regrettable because people here need help, and
this was an important source of help.'' But pro-PLO figures did not
oppose the move, which was seen as an effort by Hussein to
disengage himself from leadership in Palestinian affairs and give
the PLO more responsibility.
   ``The Amman decision will not affect anybody,'' said Mustafa
Natsche, deposed mayor of the West Bank city of Hebron and a PLO
supporter. He said that although Palestinians need aid from all
Arab countries, they mostly need to remain steadfast in their
opposition to Israeli rule.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   Observation of Friday's general strike on behalf of female
prisoners was almost complete, a reflection of the continued
influence wielded by underground Palestinian leaders.
   Neither Israeli nor Palestinian sources were able to provide a
current figure for the number of women jailed since the uprising
began last Dec. 8. About 5,800 Arabs have been detained, according
to last month's military figures, but the overwhelming majority are
men.
   Protests occurred Friday in the Shati refugee camp in the
seaside Gaza Strip, a military spokesman said. He said he did not
know if troops fired on demonstrators, but a local reporter said
three men in their 20s were brought to Gaza City's Ahli Hospital
with bullet wounds in their legs. Since the uprising began 235
Palestinians and four Israelis have died.
   The army also demolished homes belonging to three Gazans
suspected of instigating anti-Israeli protests, the Itim news
agency said Friday. The demolitions took place Thursday in the
Nusseirat refugee camp.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, the only movement was of
children selling newspapers door to door, residents said. Central
roads were blocked with rocks and burning tires and outlawed
Palestinian flags hung from an electricity pole.
   In Bethlehem, also on the West Bank, Palestinian activists
poured oil on the streets to prevent workers from going to jobs in
Israel. On a wall, someone had written in red spray paint: ``Death
to the Zionists.''
   Streets of Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, and the
occupied Gaza Strip were deserted except for soldiers and military
jeeps, reporters said.
   Weekly Moslem prayers passed without incident. The general
strike prevented many worshipers from reaching Jerusalem's Al Aqsa
mosque, where 300 policemen were on alert for possible violence.
</TEXT>
