<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0623 07-29 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Secrets: ``Going to Be President,'' Won't Name Veep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of toddler in 4th graf, While there</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush talked of secrets, both political
and playful, as he continued his quiet search for a running mate
and bantered with kids at a day-care center Friday.
   Bush, the expected Republican presidential nominee, also took a
swipe at Michael Dukakis, saying the Democratic nominee has
suggested that ideology doesn't matter. Such talk ``just masks over
his far-left philosophy,'' Bush said.
   He toured the child-care center in suburban Tyson's Corner, Va.,
bringing attention to his $2.2 billion proposal that would provide
tax credits for relatively low-income families with children.
   While there, he played catch with children, pushed several
toddlers on a tire swing and helped put tropical fish in a fish
tank.
   ``When you put a fish in, don't ever hold it by the hand,'' Bush
said. He joked that he was special because ``I can talk to fish.''
   One child asked him, ``Are you really going to get to be
president?''
   ``It's a secret _ don't tell the others,'' the vice president
responded.
   He said little about the last real question lingering before the
Republican National Convention: whom he will choose as his vice
presidential running mate.
   Bush told reporters he thinks too much attention is being given
to the matter, since ``I really believe the election will be
decided at the presidential level.''
   He has already contacted more than 12 possible contenders for
the spot, according to aides. Asked whether he planned to call
additional prospects, Bush said, ``Probably.''
   ``We're going through some mandatory investigations,'' he said.
``I will make the selection in my own mind before I go down to New
Orleans'' for the Aug. 15-18 convention. In the meantime, he said,
``I will keep my own counsel.''
   Bush has said he does not plan to announce his choice until the
convention.
   Those already contacted by Bush include former
presidential-campaign rivals Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and Rep. Jack
Kemp of New York, Dole's wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, and several people whose names did not figure in
earlier speculation, including Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., also has said he has been asked
to submit background information.
   Bush has now talked with nearly everyone on his ``long list'' of
vice presidential candidates, aides said.
   Campaign sources said the list to date also includes Sens. Alan
Simpson, R-Wyo.; William L. Armstrong, R-Colo.; John Danforth,
R-Mo. and Nancy L. Kassebaum, R-Kan.; Govs. Thomas H. Kean of New
Jersey, John Sununu of New Hampshire, Carroll A. Campbell of South
Carolina, George Deukmejian of California, and former Govs. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee and Richard Thornburgh of Pennsylvania, who
recently was nominated by President Reagan to be attorney general.
   Bush has said he hoped to have a tentative list completed by
week's end.
   As for child care, Bush, who has proposed a $1,000-per-child tax
credit primarily aimed at low-income working mothers, voiced
opposition Friday to a $2.5 billion Democratic child care plan that
would give the federal government a more direct role.
   ``I am absolutely convinced the problem is so big and so diverse
that the federal government alone cannot have a bricks-and-mortar
child care program that's going to be effective,'' Bush said.
   ``You have to have choice, parental choice, family choice, and
you have to have diversity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
