<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pakistan     07-29 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Satisfied with Afghan Withdrawal Pace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan's foreign minister said Friday that
Aug. 15 will be ``the critical date'' in judging whether the Soviet
Union is meeting its commitment to withdraw military forces from
Afghanistan.
   ``We need to withhold final judgment on the withdrawals until
that date,'' Foreign Minister Sahabzada Yaqub Khan told reporters.
   The Soviet Union, in an agreement signed in Geneva, committed to
withdrawing half its force of more than 110,000 by Aug. 15.
   ``Our hope is that this in fact will materialize,'' Yaqub Khan
said.
   The withdrawals ``on the whole seem to be going pretty well as
expected, give or take some figures that are not really relevant.
... Meanwhile, we are not particularly apprehensive about the
withdrawal,'' he added.
   Yaqub Khan met reporters at the White House after greeting
President Reagan on behalf of Pakistan President Mohammed Zia
Ul-haq and congratulating Reagan for what the minister called ``a
foreign policy that has brought much credit to him, to his
administration and to his country, and has indeed been a historical
event.''
   He said he and Reagan did not discuss the pace of Soviet
withdrawal from Afghanistan but he thanked the president for U.S.
backing of the Geneva agreements on Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
