<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Protection Bjt   07-29 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Protection, Bjt,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Approves Extension of Jackson's Secret Service Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan extended Jesse Jackson's
Secret Service protection 30 days to give Jackson time to arrange
private security against death threats the former Democratic
candidate says he has received, a White House spokesman said Friday.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Jackson had asked that
government protection be continued, based on the defeated
presidential candidate's ``assessment of threats against his life''
and Jackson's plans to campaign for Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis.
   In Chicago, Eric Easter, a spokesman for Jackson, said he had no
immediate comment on Reagan's decision. Jackson has been resting in
Chicago the past few days.
   Losing candidates for presidential nominations generally have to
relinquish their Secret Service detail as soon as the party
standardbearer is chosen. So Jackson technically had exhausted his
right to such protection on July 22 _ the day after the end of the
Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   However, Fitzwater said that Jackson ``asked for an extension of
Secret Service protection, presumably through the election. He
indicated that on the basis of threats against his life.''
   Asked if Jackson had furnished any details of death threats, the
spokesman replied, ``No.'' Asked whether the White House had tried
to verify threats against Jackson's life, he said he could not
comment on such security matters.
   Only the president is authorized to grant Secret Service
protection to non-presidential candidates. A joint House-Senate
committee in Congress screens declared candidates and recommends to
the Treasury Department which ones merit Secret Service protection.
   Secret Service spokesman Bob Snow said only that ``we do our
continuing assessments of (the security needs) of anybody we
protect.''
   Candidates are generally as tight-lipped as the government in
refusing to give specifics of threats they receive, although
Jackson has spoken several times in general terms of threats
against him during this year's campaign.
   Fitzwater said Jackson's Secret Service protection had been
maintained without interruption since the Democratic convention _
during which Dukakis formally won the nomination over Jackson _
while Reagan weighed whether to approve the extension.
   Reagan's decision was made ``within the last few days,'' the
spokesman said.
   He said that giving Jackson an additional 30 days of Secret
Service protection would cost roughly $600,000.
   Reagan's decision specifies that there will be no further
extension, the spokesman said.
   ``The feeling was that, first of all, he's not the nominee of
the party, which is what the law allows,'' he said. ``Secondly,
that it didn't seem reasonable to grant this extension once he
transitions into a private security situation.''
   He said there had been precedents for extending normal Secret
Service protection because of extenuating circumstances. For
example, protection was continued for a time for the widow of Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy after he was assassinated while running for the
Democratic presidential nomination in 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
