<DOCNO> AP880729-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic     07-29 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leadership Proposes Tougher Measurs on Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Communist Party
leadership said on Friday that security forces may take stronger
action to quell ethnic strife in Kosovo, a southern province
dominated by Albanians.
   The proposal was made during a Central Committee meeting on ways
to reduce tension in Kosovo between the ethnic Albanians and the
Slavic minority, made up of Serbs and Montenegrans. It was
broadcast on state television.
   Stane Dolanc, a member of Yugoslavia's collective presidency,
said without elaboration that the leadership ``is considering the
additional engagement of ... a federal police unit'' stationed in
Kosovo since last October.
   The paramilitary, trained and equipped to quell large public
disturbances, was sent there to thwart an expected increase in
ethnic strife.
   It has taken little action since its arrival, however, and it
was not clear whether Dolanc wanted it to play a more active role
or was suggesting more units be sent.
   Vidoje Zarkovic of Montenegro called for the dispatch of
``additional public security forces from the entire country to help
in keeping law and order in Kosovo.''
   About 200 Serb and Montenegrans from Kosovo arrived in Belgrade
on Friday to demonstrate against what they say is persecution by
the ethnic Albanian majority.
   The original plan was for thousands to make the trip, but most
apparently heeded appeals by authorities not to protest during the
Central Committee meeting.
   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population.
About 30,000 Serbs and Montenegrans have left the province, the
least-developed area of Yugoslavia, since riots in 1981.
   Franc Setinc, a Central Committee member from Slovenia, said:
   ``We cannot allow the current ethnic strife in Kosovo to turn
into a clash between different nationalities, because that would
have catastrophic consequences on this part of Europe.''
   Ethnic strife in the Balkans once earned the peninsula the
nickname ``the powder keg of Europe'' and its local conflicts
brought on World War I.
   Kosovo is an administrative part of the Servian republic.
Slobodan Milosevic, party leader of Serbia, told the Central
Committee constitutional that changes are necessary so Serbia can
exercise its authority in Kosovo and act against ethnic Albanians.
   He said ``counterrevolution'' by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
``represents a danger to socialism and to Yugosavia.''
   The 1974 Yugoslav constitution granted a large measure of
autonomy to Kosovo.
</TEXT>
