<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dearden     07-29 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dearden,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Gravely Ill; Has Inoperable Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Cardinal John Dearden has been
hospitalized with inoperable cancer of the pancreas, a church
spokesman said Friday.
   Dearden, 80, retired as Archbishop of Detroit following a heart
attack in 1980, but has remained active in the College of
Cardinals, where he is a member of the Sacred Congregation for the
Sacraments.
   ``The cardinal is gravely ill, but he is resting comfortably,''
archdiocese spokesman Jay Berman said. ``Death is soon but not
imminent.''
   Last rites have not been administered, Berman said. Dearden has
been at Providence Hospital in Southfield for a week.
   ``The Cardinal does hope that it will be possible for him to be
discharged and go home,'' Berman said. ``It's not ruled out that he
might be able to go home for some time.''
   Dearden was named archbishop in January 1959, and his
resignation was accepted by Pope John Paul in July 1980. Dearden
continued to administer the diocese until May 1981, when Bishop
Edmund Szoka was named archbishop of the 1.5 million-member
diocese. Dearden was named a cardinal by Pope Paul VI in 1969.
Szoka was elevated to cardinal earlier this month.
   In a letter to priests, Szoka said Dearden's heart condition had
been successfully treated but he has suffered severe loss of
appetite, weight and energy. Tests showed the presence of tumors,
which have been found to be malignant.
   ``Cardinal Dearden has spent himself faithfully with loyal
dedication to the church for more than 55 years of priestly
ministry, 40 of those years as bishop,'' Szoka wrote. ``I ask for
your continuing prayers in his behalf especially now in his time of
need.''
</TEXT>
