<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BizWeekProbe 2ndLd-Writethru a0653 07-29 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0653,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advest Suspends Broker in Business Week Leak Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to update with Prudential Bache firing
broker, picking up at the 4th graf previous. A version moved on the
business wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second brokerage sacked a stockbroker today in
a widening investigation of improper trading based on apparently
leaked tips of impending Business Week magazine articles.
   Prudential Bache Securities Inc. dismissed Brian Callahan, a
broker in its Anaheim, Calif., office, after it detected suspicious
trading by him, said spokesman Peter Costiglio. He said Callahan
had worked for the firm for about 3{ years but had no further
information about him.
   Business Week confirmed last week it had initiated an inquiry
into suspected leaks of its ``Inside Wall Street'' column.
   The Hartford, Conn., investment firm Advest Inc. suspended a
broker in its New London, Conn., office, where 10 brokers are
based, spokeswoman Martha Payne said today. She declined to
disclose the broker's identity or career history.
   ``The suspension was the result of an internal investgiation
which we conducted,'' she said. ``We've notified the Securities and
Exchange Commission. The investigation is continuing.''
   Officials at the New London office referred all inquiries to Ms.
Payne.
   The disclosure came a day after Wall Street giant Merrill Lynch
& Co. disclosed it had fired one employee and was questioning
another in connection with suspected trading based on
pre-publication tips from ``Inside Wall Street.''
   Merrill said it fired William Dillon, 33, a financial consultant
in its New London office, after company lawyers uncovered records
suggesting he bought and sold stocks with information from the
column.
   People familiar with the Merrill inquiry also said the firm was
examining the actions of a Merrill Lynch vice president, James
Smith, in the New London office.
   Smith had approved some of the questioned trades under a company
policy requiring junior employees trading for their own account to
get prior approval from senior executives, they said. No
disciplinary action has been taken against him.
   Company spokesman William Clark said Dillon had worked at
Merrill Lynch's New London office since 1986, but little other
information was available on the former employee. He said that to
his knowledge no charges had been filed against Dillon.
   A man who identified himself as Dillon's father in telephone
calls to Dillon's home in Old Lyme, Conn., said his son was
unavailable for comment. He declined to discuss the matter or
answer any questions. Smith did not return telephone calls.
   In its Aug. 8 issue, released to the press late Thursday,
Business Week acknowledged to readers it had discovered unusual
trading in shares mentioned in the Wall Street column and had
initiated an investigation.
   ``The relationship between Business Week and its readers is our
most valuable asset, and we intend to protect it,'' said the note
to readers.
   The note also said the magazine was cooperating with authorities
in the probe and had tightened its ``already stringent'' internal
security.
   Business Week, published by New York-based McGraw-Hill Inc.,
said last week its legal counsel was examining the entire operation
for possible leaks. Magazine officials believe the information
probably was leaked by workers at one of four plants that print
Business Week or by a postal employee rather than a member of its
editorial staff.
   Business Week confirmed it was investigating the situation after
Dow Jones Professional Investor Report made the initial disclosure
about possible leaks of information involving the column.
   Professional Investor Report said its analysis of 20 stocks
mentioned in the Business Week column had found at least eight
stocks rose sharply the day the magazines came off the presses but
before they were available to the public.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission and the major stock
exchanges also are investigating the matter.
   Most securities lawyers agree that the past conviction of a Wall
Street Journal reporter who leaked advance information to a
stockbroker would deter journalists from committing a similar act.
   R. Foster Winans was sentenced to an 18-month prison term
following his conviction of wire fraud in 1985 for passing tips
about items scheduled to appear in the newspaper's influential
``Heard on the Street'' column. A federal judge this week reduced
Winans' sentence to one year.
   Business Week, circulation 960,000, is printed weekly at four
plants, including one in Old Saybrook, Conn., located near New
London.
   R.R. Donnelley & Sons Co. of Chicago, which operates the Old
Saybrook plant, said the company was conducting its own
investigation into possible leaks at the 550-employee plant and at
another plant in Torrance, Calif., and that anyone accused of
wrongdong faced disciplinary action.
</TEXT>
