<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia GOP,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Party, Not Courts, Must Settle Georgia GOP Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court ruled Friday that the feud
between rival Georgia delegations to next month's Republican
National Convention must be settled by the party at the convention,
not in the courts.
   Georgia GOP Chairman John Stuckey hailed the decision as a
victory, but former Chairman Matthew Patton, who sided with a group
of party dissidents, said the group intended to appeal further.
   The battle is between a delegation headed by party regulars,
including Stuckey, and one chosen by dissidents who took over the
party's state convention after Stuckey abruptly adjourned it in May.
   The national party's Committee on Contests will hold a hearing
on the dispute Aug. 8, a week before the GOP convention in New
Orleans. Both sides already have filed briefs with the committee.
   Eighteen at-large delegates are involved. Thirty of the state's
48 delegates to the national convention had already been chosen
before the state convention.
   At a news conference shortly after Friday's ruling, Stuckey
said, ``Today we're taking off the gloves'' in the battle with the
dissident faction.
   In court Wednesday, W.W. Larsen of Dublin, representing the
dissidents, said Stuckey and other party officials were trying to
disenfranchise political newcomers drawn into the party by the
candidacy of Christian broadcaster Pat Robertson.
   Larsen said party officials had arbitrarily used party rules to
bar Robertson supporters from participating in the state convention
in Albany.
