<HEAD>Reagan Plans To Nominate Ambassador To Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plans to nominate James E.
Goodby, a veteran Foreign Service officer now a diplomat in
residence at the Foreign Service Institute, as ambassador to
Greece, the White House announced Friday.
   Goodby, 58, will succeed Robert Vossler Keeley on his
confirmation by the Senate.
   Goodby entered the Foreign Service in 1952. He was ambassador to
Finland in 1980-81, vice chairman of the U.S. delegation to the
Strategic Arms Reduction Talks from 1981-83, and U.S.
representative to the Conference on Security Building Measures and
Disarmament in Europe from 1983-85.
   He was diplomat in residence at Georgetown University in 1985-86
and since 1987 has been diplomat in residence and senior fellow for
the Center for the study of Foreign Affairs at the Foreign Service
Institute, the State Department's training agency.
   The White House also announced that the president plans to
nominate Sonia Landau, a New York city consultant and former
chairman of the board of directors of the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting, as coordinator for international communications and
information policy at the State Department. She would succeed Diana
Lady Dougan.
