<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-29 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARLINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best advice for those attending the
biggest convention in town is don't pack any clothes, don't forget
the suntan lotion and for goodness' sake don't stare.
   Nudists _ hundreds of men, women and children _ are meeting to
have fun and get naked.
   ``Looking is not a no-no, but staring is,'' said Turner Stokes,
60, of Leesburg, Va., an electronics engineer who is president of
the 30,000-member American Sunbathing Association. ``I'm sure the
staring is much worse out among the textiles.''
   ``Textiles'' is a nudists' term for people who wear clothes.
They are the outsiders at the 106-acre White Thorn Lodge, a
pleasant, wooded campground on the Ohio-Pennsylvania border.
   Members of the Eastern Sunbathing Association, a division of the
national group, are meeting through Sunday to elect officers,
organize committees, lie in the sun, swim and play games.
   ``It's the freedom. It's the comfort. Our society equates nudity
with sexuality, but this is a totally non-sexual setting. People
are just people here,'' said Mary Lou Schloss, 40, of Rochester,
N.Y., a nudism activist who brought her husband and children to the
convention.
   ``I just like the swimming pool, the hot tub and the food,''
said her son, Evan, 8, a third-grader who wore only cherry soda on
his face Thursday.
   ``Most people seek the breeze, the sun, the rain and the freedom
of wearing no pantyhose,'' said Lynn Arnett, 44, a free-lance
writer from Paradise Lakes, Fla. ``You tell the first lie of the
day when you put your clothes on.''
   Security is very tight for the convention. Clothed and nude men
guard the gate. ``Textile'' reporters who shed only their ties are
escorted among friendly families sharing lunch on picnic tables,
smiling couples sitting on shaded lawn chairs and naked children
running across the grass.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Dorothy Davis opened her monthly
electric bill, she got quite a charge. It said she owed more than
$3 million.
   It was $3,500,043.00, to be exact.
   ``I nearly died. I called the company, and they said it was
bound to be a mistake,'' Mrs. Davis said. ``I said, ``Yes, it is.'''
   The error apparently occurred when a Kentucky Utilities Co.
employee changed Mrs. Davis' monthly bill, said company spokesman
Ed Van Hook.
   Mrs. Davis pays her bills on the company's budget plan. A
billing clerk was supposed to raise the bill from $43 to $50
because Mrs. Davis was using more electricity, Van Hook said. But
the clerk forgot to press a computer key to substitute the new
amount for the old amount, he said.
   Then another three and some zeros got combined with both the old
and new bills.
   ``If I had a bad heart, it would have given me a heart attack,''
Mrs. Davis said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials were ordered to put their
weekly Cabinet meeting reports in sealed envelopes after
confidential papers from the governor's office were found in a
men's restroom at the Capitol.
   The order came after a July 11 meeting, when a 10-page report
called ``Memorandum to Gov. Garrey Carruthers from staff'' was
discovered in the bathroom two floors away, said Carruthers'
spokesman, Don Caviness.
   A member of the Legislative Finance Committee found the document
when he was washing his hands, said committee director Phil Baca.
   ``To be frank with you, I never got around to reading the thing,
but some of the staff got a kick out of reading this stuff,'' he
said.
   Caviness said the report, which contained weekly highlights from
Cabinet secretaries and the governor's staff, was not ``designed to
be widely distributed.''
