<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You might say E.H. ``Curly'' Schukar and
the neighborhood squirrel see eye to eye at feeding time.
   Schukar has trained the animal to take peanuts as he holds them
in his teeth.
   ``Everybody that sees me do that thinks I'm nuts, of course.
Naturally, with nuts you get nuts,'' Schukar said.
   Schukar, 80, and his neighbors adopted the squirrel this spring.
   ``No other squirrel would do that,'' Schukar said. ``No other
squirrel would I trust.''
   The squirrel is reluctant to perform when people gather to watch
but has no fear of Schukar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOBOSO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 90 residents of this central Ohio
village couldn't wait any longer for work to finish on the bridge
that links them with the rest of the world.
   Although reconstruction on the Toboso Bridge is not expected to
be completed for two to three weeks, the excitement over the
reopening gave way to a village party on the bridge, complete with
food, music and even a ribbon-cutting ceremony. A construction
crane and piles of gravel served as the backdrop.
   ``It's a test, really,'' Mike Scott said Wednesday night as he
sat at a table on the concrete span over the Licking River. ``If we
can get 200 people on the bridge and it holds up, they'll let the
cars across.''
   The bridge closed in April, and since then getting anywhere
since has meant miles of detours on winding county and township
roads.
