<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Swaggart     07-29 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Swaggart,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart Conducts Service At Garden Tomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television preacher Jimmy Swaggart asked his
congregation to judge themselves, not others, during a service
Friday in the garden where tradition says Jesus was buried.
   ``Look into your own hearts today,'' said Swaggart, reading from
the Bible. ``Don't judge others.'' Turning to his 350 listeners, he
asked: ``Did you hear what I say?'' Several responded: ``Yes.''
   Swaggart, who arrived in Israel on Thursday for a 10-day tour of
biblical sites, lost his credentials as an Assemblies of God
minister earlier this year after he refused to stop preaching for a
year as punishment for meeting with a prostitute in New Orleans.
   After the service, Swaggart told reporters: ``God is the one who
puts things in the past ... That's the beautiful thing about
Christianity. People love, they forgive and they forget.''
   He said he had been humbled by the public scandal that occurred
after the disclosure of his sexual activities in February. The
disclosures led him to confess tearfully on nationwide television
that he had sinned.
   ``I think that I have more love for people now,'' said Swaggart.
``I think that I feel their pain a little more ... This world is a
hurting world and maybe I'm a little less condemnatorial, maybe I'm
a little bit less accusatorial.''
   Swaggart's congregants appeared moved by his 45-minute sermon.
Some cried. Others raised their hands in the air and uttered,
``Hallelujah'' or ``Praise the Lord.''
   ``I love him, I love him,'' said Ray Grant, 55, of Houston.
   But others voiced criticism of Swaggart.
   ``I wouldn't say his deeds enhanced his image,'' said Oleda
McCurdy of Fort Pine, Ala. ``But you have to forgive.''
   ``I was bothered by how the scandal was handled,'' said Charles
Kester, 20, of Siloam Springs, Ark. ``I wonder about the soundness
of his leadership.''
   Kester, in Israel for the first time, said the country was ``a
bit different from what I imagined. Here you see tanks and people
on street corners carry Uzi submachine guns. That's not the way it
looks in the picture on the back of the Bible.''
   Swaggart's tour is called ``Journey With A Purpose.'' A
television crew will tape his sermons and the footage will be shown
on his daily television show.
   The Garden Tomb is one of two sites where tradition says Jesus
was buried. The other is inside the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in
the Old City.
</TEXT>
