<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DC-10Brakes     07-29 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC-10 Brakes,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Orders Inspection of Brakes on Long-Range DC-10s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Friday
ordered a special inspection of landing gear brakes on long-range
McDonnell Douglas DC-10 aircraft and directed that the brakes be
replaced if they exceed prescribed wear limits.
   The order came in response to a May 21 accident involving an
American Airlines DC-10 last May in which eight of the plane's 10
brakes failed when the pilot aborted his takeoff, causing the plane
to skid 1,000 feet beyond the runway at the Dallas-Fort Worth
airport.
   The three crewmembers in the cockpit and five of the 240
passengers were injured and the plane was heavily damaged.
   The FAA directive applies only to McDonnell Douglas DC-10 Series
30 and Series 40 planes, the somewhat heavier long-range version of
the aircraft, said FAA spokesman Dick Stafford.
   According to McDonnell Douglas, there are 66 of the long-range
DC-10s in service in the United States and 229 worldwide. Among the
airlines that fly the long-range plane are Northwest Airlines,
United Airlines, American Airlines and the freight carrier Federal
Express.
   Under the FAA order, the inspections must be made by Aug. 20 and
by that date all brakes that do not meet prescribed wear limits
must be replaced, said Stafford.
   The order does not apply to lighter, shorter-range DC-10 Series
10 aircraft of which there are about 120 being flown by U.S. air
carriers, generally in domestic service, according to FAA and
McDonnell Douglas officials.
   Earlier this month, the National Transportation Safety Board as
a result of its findings in the Dallas-Fort Worth accident,
expressed concern about the FAA's brake wear requirements.
   The safety board urged a broad review of the requirements for
all types of jetliners. The FAA told the NTSB it was in the early
stages of reviewing its brake wear requirements.
   In the May 21 accident involving the American Airlines jet, the
pilot aborted his takeoff while traveling 204 mph down the runway
because he thought _ erroneously it later turned out _ that his
flaps or slats may have been in the wrong position.
   The plane slowed to 149 mph in the first six seconds, but ``the
deceleration decayed rapidly'' and the jet went off the end of the
runway still traveling 117 mph, according to the NTSB. The jet lost
its nose gear and plowed through the dirt for 1,000 feet before
coming to a halt.
   Investigators found that eight of the 10 landing gear brakes
``were near the maximum wear limits'' before the aborted takeoff
and failed within 8 to 9 seconds after being applied, the safety
board said July 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
