<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SovietJews     07-29 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Jews,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Jewish Leader Urges Moscow To Adopt New Emigration Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent American Jewish leader, after a
meeting Friday with Secretary of State George P. Shultz, urged the
Soviet Union to broaden its recently proclaimed policy of allowing
Jews who emigrate to choose their new homeland.
   Morris B. Abram, chairman of the National Conference on Soviet
Jewry, said Moscow should allow more Jews to apply for exit permits
to any country of their choice, rather than just Israel. A Kremlin
official said Thursday that ``It's up to them where they go.''
   Most Soviet Jews permitted to emigrate are given exit permits
for Israel, but about 90 percent go to the United States once they
reach Vienna, the transit point to Tel Aviv.
   Concerned about the loss of immigrants, the Israeli Cabinet has
ordered a change in procedures. Soviet Jews granted exit permits
would receive their Israeli visas in Romania and go on to Israel.
From there it would be difficult to get to the United States
because they would no longer have refugee status.
   Abram said the Israeli government ``has a right to make that
decision'' and that it would be ``a travesty'' to permit immigrants
from the Soviet Union to retain refugee status once they reached
Israel.
   ``It would be a declaration that a Jew, welcomed as he is in
Israel, is a refugee in his homeland,'' Abram said. ``That would be
a terrible construction of the meaning and purpose of the Jewish
state.''
   Soviet Jews who go to Israel are considered immigrants under
U.S. law. As a result, it is much more difficult for them to gain
admission to the United States than as refugees in Vienna.
   The situation has caused some strains between American Jews and
Israel as well as disputes within the American Jewish community.
   The solution, Abram said, lies in the Soviet government's
assertion that it does not care where emigrants chose to live. He
cited a statement on Thursday by Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir
Petrovsky in Moscow that ``we just allow all these people to leave
the country. It's up to them where they go.''
   Abram said ``as long as that is the position of the Soviet
government it is quite possible for freedom of choice to be
exercised in the Soviet Union.''
   In the past year, the Soviet Union has increased Jewish
emigration to the West to a rate of more than 1,000 a month,
compared to 1,000 a year in the early 1980s.
   According to statistics compiled by The National Conference on
Soviet Jewry, 60 to 90 Jews a month are permitted to leave directly
for the United States. Abram said 6,000 non-Jews were allowed to go
last year.
   ``So the idea that it is Soviet policy to prevent people from
leaving directly on American visas doesn't seem to be the case,''
Abram said. ``In this case, it seems to be that what they say is
what they have been doing. Let's hope they continue.''
   Abram said Shultz supports the principle of freedom of choice.
Otherwise, he and State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman
declined to elaborate on Shultz's position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedflyQuarantine     07-29 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medfly Quarantine,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quarantine Announced To Fight Medfly In San Fernando Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State agriculture officials banned the
movement of some fruits and vegetables in a suburban area and made
plans Friday to release millions of sterile flies to combat the
destructive Mediterranean fruit fly.
   No new Mediterranean fruit flies were found Friday in the
quarantine area, 62 square miles of the San Fernando Valley, a
collection of bedroom communities 10 miles northwest of downtown
Los Angeles.
   ``That's a very good sign that aerial spraying and ground
spraying are working,'' said Gera Curry, a spokeswoman for the
state Department of Food and Agriculture.
   The Medfly infestation was discovered in the San Fernando Valley
city of Northridge more than a week ago. Four Medflies have been
found thus far.
   The Medfly, one of the most destructive crop-destroying insects,
is common in Hawaii and probably was carried into Southern
California on fruit brought by tourists.
   Last Monday, 16 square miles of the San Fernando Valley was
sprayed with pesticides by helicopter, and ground crews also have
been spraying.
   The produce quarantine, which began Thursday, bans removal or
movement of home-grown fruit and garden vegetables in the
quarantine area.
   The quarantine also prohibits the sale of produce from street
and pushcart vendors. In addition, it bans residents from taking
fruits and vegetables into their workplaces for distribution.
   ``By moving fruit out of that quarantine area, you may be moving
Medfly,'' Ms. Curry said. ``The whole point of this is to make sure
anything that moves is safe.''
   Grocery stores and fruit and vegetable stands whose suppliers
treat the food with pesticide will be allowed to continue selling
produce.
   Meanwhile, officials said they plan to release 4 million sterile
flies next week. The release of sterile flies will drastically
reduce the chances of the female Medflies laying eggs, state and
county officials explained.
   The quarantine is expected to last until early November, but
agriculture officials said it could end earlier if the infestation
is eradicated.
   There was a five-month, 110-square-mile quarantine in eastern
Los Angeles in July 1987, because of a slightly larger medfly
infestation. The state's most serious infestation cost $97.6
million in eradication efforts that continued from 1980 to 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WaterRights     07-29 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Rights,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Angry at Wilderness Water Rights Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, in a decision
angering environmentalists, said wilderness areas have no automatic
claim to water rights, Interior Secretary Donald Hodel said Friday.
   ``This is a major victory for the western states, water users
and the principles of federalism,'' Hodel, flanked by a happy group
of Republican lawmakers from the West, told a Capitol Hill news
confernce.
   Hodel said that soon-departing Attorney Gen. Edwin Meese III
concurs with a legal opinion by Interior solicitor Ralph Tarr that
Congress must specifically award water to a wilderness area when it
creates the no-development enclave.
   ``This is a public resource giveaway of monumental
proportions,'' said Debbie Sease of the Sierra Club. ``Hodel and
Meese are sacrificing the lifeblood of our wilderness areas _ water
_ by saying, `Come and get it, we won't defend it.'''
   Hodel noted that U.S. District Court rulings disagree on a major
question in the arid West: Does the mere creation of a wilderness
area by Congress guarantee it will have enough water to ensure its
proper management.
   He said the administration was siding with a recent ruling in
New Mexico that said there are no water rights unless Congress
writes them into wilderness legislation.
   Congress has been skirting the controversial issue in wilderness
bills, leaving it up to to the Interior and Agriculture departments
and the courts to settle conflicting demands for scarce water.
   ``In most cases, these wilderness bills would not have passed if
Congress had to take water away from someone,'' Hodel said. ``In
order to get this water, you have to take it away from someone
else.''
   Under the administration policy, the rights of existing water
users, including federal forests, parks and wilderness areas and
Indian tribes, wold be maintained and protected, according to Hodel.
   He indicated that new areas lacking specific statutory water
guarantees will have to compete for water with other users before
various state water allotment authorities.
   Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, said that ``the people who live along
the banks of the Snake River are much better qualified to make
decisions about water use than the people who live along the banks
of the Potomac River.''
   ``This is an important decision for all of us in the West,''
added Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah. Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, said the
policy ``will help us resolve an issue that has confounded us.''
   Hodel's announcement was immediately attacked by environmental
groups and by Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo., who called the news
conference a political event because it reiterated a position the
administration has previously taken.
   ``The current administration feels threatened in the West
because of the all-out offensive by (Democratic presidential
nominee) Michael Dukakis,'' said Wirth, who sat in the audience at
the news conference.
   ``This is the first time I've seen a full-blown press conference
on a solicitor's opinion,'' Wirth said. ``This doesn't solve
anything except inflame things politically.''
   The policy runs counter to a U.S. District Court ruling in
Colorado in 1985 and to a 1979 opinion by an Interior Department
solicitor during the Carter administration, said Maggie Fox of the
Sierra Club.
   ``This marks a new low in Meese's and Hodel's flagrant disregard
for the law,'' she said.
   ``The spirit of James Watt is alive and well,'' said Wilderness
Society vice president Sydney Butler, referring to the
administration's first interior secretary.
   Christopher Meyer, a water lawyer for the National Wildlife
Federation, said that ``the decision reflects just about as much
careful thought as the administration's decision to sell arms to
Iran.''
   Hodel said the policy has ``the distinct possibility'' of
extending beyond the current administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
