<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     07-29 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani to Iraq: Iranian Army Stronger Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Iraq-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's commander-in-chief said Friday
that enemy forces had pushed 65 miles into Iran and threatened a
provincial capital but that Iran had routed the invaders and was
pushing them back toward the border.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, who is also speaker of Parliament, warned
Iraq that if it ``decides to continue the war, then they must know
that our strength today is by far greater than that of the time
prior to the acceptance of the resolution,'' he said. Iran accepted
a U.N. cease-fire resolution July 18.
   Speaking at a prayer service broadcast on Tehran radio,
Rafsanjani said Iraqi-backed Iranian rebels entered a hospital in
the western town of Eslamabad and ``rained bullets on some 30
patients,'' killing all of them.
   In the Iraqi capital of Baghdad, a spokesman for the rebel
fighters, the National Liberation Army of Iran, said they pulled
out of Eslamabad and Karand, 60 miles inside Iran, after holding
the cities for three days. The rebel group did not comment on the
Iranian charges of a massacre.
   A seven-member U.N. team, meanwhile, arrived in Baghdad on
Friday to discuss implementation of U.N. Resolution 598. The seven
officials, led by Norwegian Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset, arrived after
visiting Tehran and are expected to spend three days in Baghdad.
They refused to comment to reporters.
   At the United Nations, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
denied persistent reports that his peace talks with Iran and Iraq
are in trouble.
   ``Be patient,'' Perez de Cuellar said. ``And we will make
progress rather soon ... I am constantly in touch with the parties.
I keep working.''
   The process has stalled over Iraq's insistence on direct talks
and Iran's rejection of a face-to-face meeting before a cease-fire
is declared in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf conflict.
   Iran said it drove the Iraqi-backed rebel fighters out of
Eslamabad and Karand, killing or wounding 4,500 invaders in a
``heavy battle'' against ``forces of the Baghdad regime and their
hypocritical mercenaries.''
   Iran's armed forces were chasing the troops back toward Sar-e
Pol-e Zahab, 24 miles from the Iran-Iraq border, Iran claimed.
   Iranian press reports, monitored in Nicosia, said thousands of
invaders were wounded and more than 1,000 Iraqi tanks and personnel
carriers were either destroyed or seized intact.
   ``The operation destroyed the Islamic republic's cancer, which
... could have caused problems for Iranians,'' Rafsanjani told the
prayer congregation in Tehran in an apparent reference to the
rebels.
   In the sermon, he acknowledged the invaders had pushed 65 miles
into Iran, coming within 22 miles of the provincial capital of
Bakhtaran.
   ``This was a revolt that had to be destroyed, and if the Iraqi
regime wants to continue its aggressions, it will receive the same
response,'' Rafsanjani said.
   Tehran radio interrupted its normal programs to play martial
music and announce the victory over the National Liberation Army.
   The rebel group, in a communique released in Baghdad, said its
fighters ``returned to their bases'' Friday after three days of
fighting in which 40,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards were killed
or wounded.
   No independent observers were allowed near the fighting and
claims from both sides could not be verified.
   The rebels, estimated at 15,000, operate a series of bases along
the border. The National Liberation Army, the fighting arm of the
resistance group known as Mujahedeen Khalq, set up its headquarters
in Iraq after being expelled from France in 1986.
</TEXT>
