<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party 1stLd-Writethru a0637 07-29 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Leadership Approves Reform Plans, Gorbachev Urges Lean Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Gorbachev remarks on pruning
party and accomplishments of nationwide conference; EDITS to
conform and TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin leadership on Friday adopted broad
goals for making government more responsive, and Mikhail S.
Gorbachev urged pruning the Communist Party to exclude all but the
best and brightest, Tass said.
   The Soviet leader asked the Communist Party Central Committee to
have the parliament meet in November to make constitutional changes
allowing contested elections next March, Tass said. But it was
unclear from the report whether the committee adopted all of
Gorbachev's proposals.
   Gorbachev's proposal calls for multi-candidate elections to a
new 2,250-member Congress of Peoples' Deputies, which in turn would
choose a full-time parliament of at least 400 members and a
president with broad powers.
   Tass, the official news agency, issued a brief dispatch on the
eight-hour meeting that included only vague descriptions of decrees
and decisions adopted by the Central Committee, which has about 300
members.
   Its report on Gorbachev's opening address said he touched on
many issues, including youth problems and nationalities,
specifically the debate over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh. The
Caucasus enclave is part of Azerbaijan but its predominantly
Armenian population wants it annexed to Soviet Armenia.
   The 57-year-old Soviet leader also said he wants the 20-million
membership of the Communist Party reduced ``significantly'' to
include only the vanguard of Soviet society.
   At present, less than 10 percent of Soviet adults gain
admittance to the all-powerful party.
   Gorbachev also said a nationwide conference held a month ago
confirmed the Communist Party's role as ``the real driving force''
of reform. He said the meeting's major accomplishment was
recognizing the party's predominance.
   Membership rolls are to be reviewed before the end of the year.
That process could be used to dump the idle and corrupt or to
strengthen Gorbachev's base by revoking the memberships of his
conservative opponents.
   Gorbachev also acknowledged Friday that the nationwide
conference also ``demonstrated that conservative sentiments,
longing for the past, attempts to sow doubts, to portray
perestroika not as a historic endeavor but almost as a social
destabilization have by far not yet been overcome in society.''
   ``Perestroika'' is the term for Gorbachev's program of economic
and social reform.
   Gorbachev has faced resistance from some party members who think
he is moving too fast to change how Soviet society and its economy
have operated for decades.
   The Central Committee approved resolutions on ``reports and
voting in party organizations'' and on ``the general directions of
reconstruction of the party apparatus,'' Tass said.
   A special commission was formed, with Gorbachev as chairman,
``for the preparation of proposals for implementing the decisions
of the 19th All-Union Party Conference,'' it reported.
   That forum, which ended July 1, authorized a major revamping of
individual rights and the structure of government. Among its
recommendations were limiting elected party and government
officials to two five-year terms and multiple candidates for
elective office.
   Tass said the Central Committee meeting was over and details of
its actions would be published in the press.
   A spokesman at the Central Committee's information department
would not say whether changes had been made to the 13-member ruling
Politburo.
   ``You will have to wait for the official announcements,'' he
said, and asked that his name not be used.
   Western and Soviet sources had predicted at least one
longstanding member would resign during the meeting and perhaps set
a precedent for orderly retirement from the Politburo, whose
members traditionally have served for life or been voted out in
disgrace.
   Among those reported in line for retirement are President Andrei
A. Gromyko, 79, and Mikhail S. Solomentsev, 74. There have been
persistent rumors that Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, the Ukrainian
party chief, would be ousted or retired and Viktor M. Chebrikov,
head of the KGB secret police, replaced.
   The Politburo decided July 4 that the Central Committee would
meet to implement ``reforms of the political system, the
democratization of party, state and social life.''
   Gorbachev has also called for a society ruled by laws, which he
said would avoid a return of Stalinist repression or the corruption
and stagnation that characterized Leonid I. Brezhnev's leadership.
   Resolutions adopted by the party conference provided an outline
for change, which the Central Committee must translate into
specific programs and a timetable.
   They range from ending bureaucratic meddling in agriculture to
making all non-classified government information available to the
citizenry.
</TEXT>
