<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Khomeini 1stLd-Writethru a0629 07-29 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Khomeini, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis See Victory in Thwarting Komeini's Drive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 12 graf pvs, ``The strongest...'' to ADD
background on Sunnis and Shiites. Pickup 13th graf pvs, ``The
Iran-Iraq...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi officials say their greatest
achievement in the Persian Gulf war was preventing Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini from exporting Iran's Islamic revolution
throughout the Arab world.
   Diplomats in Baghdad say the war also helped unite Iraq and make
it a more efficient nation which will be able to better use its
vast oil resources in the future, despite the tremendous debt and
losses suffered in the 8-year-old war.
   The Iraqis clearly view the humiliation of the Iranian leader as
the main benefit of the war, which killed an estimated 1 million
Iranians and Iraqis.
   ``The most important outcome was not the technical victories we
scored against the Iranian army, but rather the entire defeat of
the ideological foundation on which the Iranian regime is based,''
President Saddam Hussein said in a recent speech.
   ``Khomeinism was not only evil and dangerous to Iraq and the
Arab world but to humanity at large,'' Hussein said in the speech,
which followed Iraqi victories that led to Iran's acceptance of a
cease-fire resolution on July 18.
   A senior Iraqi official called recent developments ``a
watershed'' because Khomeini ``accepted defeat'' and ``the notion
of coexistence with a secular regime, of cooperation on political
boundaries.''
   ``By accepting this in a legal and political sense, it will be
the end of a model'' Khomeini hoped to spread throughout the
region, the official said.
   ``Nobody would imagine that Khomeini would humiliate himself''
by accepting the cease-fire he had long opposed, said the official,
who demanded anonymity. ``We're very happy because he's not going
to be the prophet anymore.''
   Khomeini came to power in 1979 vowing to export his revolution
throught the Islamic world. His call was taken up by Islamic
radicals throughout the Arab world, generating protests and
guerrilla action in Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Lebanon, Egypt,
Bahrain, Tunisia and other countries.
   The bloodiest protests occurred in Saudi Arabia, where
Khomeini-inspired fundamentalists briefly seized Islam's holiest
shrine, the Grand Mosque in Mecca, in 1979, and where Iranian
demonstrations led to a bloodbath during the Islamic pilgrimage to
Mecca in 1987.
   Iran responded to the 1987 clashes by demanding the downfall of
Saudi Arabia's own Islamic fundamentalist government, which is
based on mainstream Sunni Islam.
   The strongest factions are in Lebanon, where Iranian-backed
militias have called for creating an Islamic republic.
   Shiite Moslems, the overwhelming majority in Iran, revere the
martyrdom of the Prophet Mohammed's grandson Hussein in 680, in an
Islamic factional war from which the Sunni and Shiite branches of
the faith developed.
   The Iran-Iraq war itself was preceded by Iranian threats against
Iraq's secular socialist government.
   During the war, Iran hosted a dissident Iraqi
government-in-exile headed by fundamentalist clerics, and it vowed
to pursue the conflict until Hussein and his associates were
toppled.
   Iraqi officials claim they were never worried about a
Khomeini-style revolution in their country. But they took strong
action against pro-Khomeini forces inside their country, which,
like Iran, has a Shiite Moslem majority.
   Shortly before the war broke out in 1980, the Iraqis deported
35,000 ethnic Iranians and executed Ayatollah Baqr al-Sadr, who had
vowed allegiance to Khomeini.It also crushed the pro-Khomeini Dawa
Party.
   Once the war started, Iraq's Shiites remained loyal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
