<DOCNO> AP880729-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-WestBank     07-29 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-West Bank,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Will Keep Some Ties With West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan said Friday that its new policy of
distancing itself from affairs in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip to give the PLO a larger role does not mean cutting
its ties to the people there.
   Information Minister Hani Khasawneh noted that Jordan will
continue paying the salaries of teachers and other administrative
officials in the occupied lands and that Palestinians from there
could keep their Jordanian passports.
   Khasawneh stressed that Jordan's decision to give the
Palestinians ``a free hand to deal'' with their 40-year-old issue
``does not mean that we are cutting all links with Palestinians.''
   The Palestinians' right to ``citizenship and a passport ...
could not be changed unless it is the will of its holder,'' the
minister added.
   Jordan said Thursday it was ending a five-year, $1.3 billion
development program for education and other services in the
occupied territories started in 1986. Khasawneh also said that all
joint Jordanian-Palestinian institutions, such as the Jordanian
Parliament, were under review.
   Wahid Jabari, the representative from Hebron on the West Bank
and one of 30 Palestinian members of the 60-member lower house of
Parliament, said ties between Jordan and the occupied lands could
never be completely severed.
   ``Arab summits, international conferences or wishes of some
parties cannot abolish the sacred unity between the two banks,''
Jabari said.
   ``I do not support the Jordanian step to withdraw its
responsibility toward the Palestinian people whatever the reasons
were.''
   Jabari dismissed reports that the 8-month-old uprising against
Israeli military occupation had also fueled feelings against
Jordan's King Hussein.
   ``People there have deep respect and admiration for King Hussein
and his policies,'' he said.
   The territories have been occupied by the Israeli military since
the 1967 Middle East war, when Israel seized the West Bank from
Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt. Two-thirds of Jordan's 3.5
million population is of Palestinian origin, but carry Jordanian
passports.
   A senior Jordanian official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Jordan's decision to give the Palestine Liberation
Organization more responsibility in the occupied lands, ``although
clear, does not mean that we are giving up our commitments to
Palestinans and their issue.''
</TEXT>
