<DOCNO> AP880729-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NamelessProtesters     07-29 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nameless Protesters,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 13 More Abortion Foes Who Refuse To Give Names</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen more anti-abortion demonstrators were
arrested Friday and refused to give their names, raising to more
than 100 the number of abortion foes jailed in a waiting game of
anonymity with authorities.
   A group called Operation Rescue organized the protest outside
the Atlanta SurgiCenter, a clinic where abortions, among other
medical services, are performed.
   The group led a similar protest at the clinic during the
Democratic National Convention on July 19, when 134 were arrested.
   About 96 of the first batch have refused to give their names and
remain in jail, identifying themselves as numbered ``Baby Jane
Does'' and ``Baby John Does'' _ in solidarity, they say, with
aborted fetuses.
   All pleaded innocent to the only charge against them, criminal
trespass, in three days of Municipal Court appearances that ended
Friday.
   Those arrested Friday were charged with giving a false name,
criminal trespass, unlawful assembly and disorderly conduct and are
to appear in court Monday.
   One demonstrator entered the clinic and tried to talk people in
the waiting room out of having abortions, but was ushered out by
employees.
   Operation Rescue spokesman Lowell Patterson said about 75
percent of those jailed vowed to conceal their identities and
remain jailed until their appearances in State Court, if that date
is within the next month or so.
   He said some others would identify themselves in the next few
days and sign $500 recognizance bonds if business or personal
matters required them to leave.
   Court officials say they cannot free unidentified people on bond
because there is no way of keeping track of them or assuring that
they return for scheduled court appearances.
   ``We will continue not to provide our identities to break the
grip which the abortion industry holds over the criminal justice
system in Atlanta,'' said Randall Terry, director of Operation
Rescue.
</TEXT>
