<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MoneyLaundering     07-29 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Laundering,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Fines Texas Currency Dealer $3.01 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department on Friday said it had
fined a Texas currency dealer $3.01 million in the first civil
penalty imposed in the department's efforts to crack down on money
laundering along the border with Mexico.
   The fine, for violations of the Bank Secrecy Act, was levied on
Oscar's Money Exchange of Hidalgo, Texas, and its owner, Oscar
Ortiz Alvarez, and another man, Antonio Franco.
   Franco's organization was accused of laundering $5.56 million
through Oscar's Money Exchange. Federal agents in June 1987 seized
$2.55 million. The remaining $3.01 million was transported to
Mexico by Alvarez and others without filing the necessary forms
with the U.S. Customs Service, the department said.
   The Bank Secrecy Act requires anyone transporting cash of
$10,000 or more outside the country to notify the Customs Service.
   Alvarez, arrested in McAllen, Texas, on Thursday, was charged in
the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas with
money laundering.
   The department said Franco is serving 35 years in a federal
prison after being convicted of participating in a drug smuggling
and distribution ring.
</TEXT>
