<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CandidateCar     07-29 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidate Car,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Loses Auto Workers' Support For Admitting He Owns
Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM MITZELFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state House candidate who drove his
imported car to a United Auto Workers meeting has only himself to
blame for losing the endorsements of Michigan's two major labor
groups, a union spokesman says.
   David Rutledge, of Ypsilanti, complained earlier this week that
House Speaker Gary Owen coerced leaders of the Michigan State
AFL-CIO to support his hand-picked successor, Kirk Profit, over
Rutledge in a primary election despite a decision by the group's
local members to remain neutral.
   But Tim Hughes, a spokesman for the AFL-CIO, said Rutledge's
admission to a UAW local screening committee that he owns a Subaru
and his wife drives a Mercedes killed any chance he had of winning
labor support.
   ``That's the first thing they do is look out the window and see
what you drive,'' Hughes said, chuckling.
   ``Somebody who thinks that little of workers in their district
that they're driving a foreign car is not going to get their
endorsement,'' Hughes said, insisting that Owen's preference never
came into play.
   ``If God himself endorsed (Rutledge), and he drove up in a
Subaru, he's not getting our endorsement,'' Hughes added.
   Rutledge said he's not surprised the union is using his choice
of cars against him, but he has borrowed an American-made car for
the rest of the campaign.
   ``If that's the only thing that Owen and company can find in
terms of a negative about David Rutledge, I accept that.''
   He said that if driving is an issue, perhaps voters should
consider that his opponent, Profit, has been arrested for drunken
driving. ``At least I can say I've never been caught drunk driving
in either one of my cars,'' he said.
   Profit and Rutledge will face off in next Tuesday's Democratic
primary for the right to take on the Republican winner in November.
   Political action committees for the Michigan UAW and AFL-CIO
have each contributed $2,500 to Profit's campaign.
   Owen's decision not to seek a ninth term in the House prompted
his two former staffers to compete for his seat.
   Profit, 35, served four years as assistant majority director of
House Democrats. He is a former undersheriff in Wayne County.
   Rutledge, 43, was recruited by Owen two years ago as deputy
director of the House Democratic Research Staff.
</TEXT>
