<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Uprising     07-29 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Uprising,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>To Review Cases of People Imprisoned During Anti-communist
Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cases of about 400 people
imprisoned during the 1956 anti-Communist uprising that was crushed
by Soviet tanks will be reviewed by the end of August, a Justice
Ministry official said Friday.
   The reviews could lead to amnesty and permission to travel
abroad for some of the 400.
   But Jenoe Laszlo, head of the ministry's legislation drafting
department, also was quoted by the newspaper Magyar Nemzet as
saying those who were convicted of high treason or espionage for
their acts between Oct. 23, 1956, and May 1, 1957 would be excluded
from the planned amnesty.
   Laszlo said amnesty would not be considered for those convicted
of committing common crimes such as homicide, robbery and ``acts
causing danger to the public'' during that period, the newspaper
reported.
   The revolt began in October 1956 with demonstrations demanding a
new government and that Soviet troops leave Hungary. On Nov. 4,
1956, about 4.2 million Soviet troopers and 2,500 tanks struck at
Budapest.
   Karoly Grosz, premier and Communist Party leader, said last week
during a U.S. visit that his government was preparing a measure to
remove travel restrictions for those sentenced for having played a
role in the uprising. He said the proposal could affect 400 people.
   Police can deny exit visas to people who have a criminal record.
   Hungarians generally have greater freedom of travel under
regulations approved Jan. 1. They allow passport holders to travel
to the West as often as they can afford within the country's
currency restrictions.
   Seven dissidents went on a hunger strike last week, however, to
protest what they said were arbitrary decisions by police over who
receives a passport. Most of the hunger strikers have been refused
permission to travel abroad for allegedly violating Hungarian
regulations on previous trips.
   Jenoe Fonay, one of the hunger strikers, was involved in the
1956 revolt and could be affected by the new ruling.
   Grosz said that among the cases to be reconsidered would be
those of people who had been refused amnesty earlier because of
political affiliation with the leaders of the 1956 uprising.
   But Grosz has steadfastly ruled out rehabilitation of the
leaders of the revolt, including Imre Nagy who was the Communist
Party leader at the time. His trial and execution were announced in
1958.
   Laszlo said those who were sentenced to five-year prison terms
or less following the uprising were given amnesties after their
release in the late 1950s or early 1960s.
   Those who served more than five years will have to apply for the
invalidation of their criminal record, he said.
   About 20,000 people jailed during and after the revolt were
released in a general amnesty in 1962.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
