<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blasts Administration Over Pentagon Procurement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 3 grafs at end with Wisconsin appearance</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis accused the Reagan
administration Friday of permitting the Pentagon's procurement
scandal and said if he is elected ``we're not going to surrender
our national security to greed and corruption.''
   ``We're not going to use our defense dollars to line the pockets
of Washington consultants,'' the Democtratic presidential nominee
said.
   Dukakis, visiting the state where he suffered the worst
embarrassment of his primary campaign, toured a General Motors
truck assembly plant to underscore his pledge to work for ``full
employment'' and his call for private and government investment in
modernizing industry and creating new jobs.
   He also met with Jesse Jackson supporters who had helped Jackson
win the state last spring. He got outspoken backing from one key
figure.
   At the GM plant, where Chevrolet and GMC light trucks are
manufactured, Dukakis walked along the assembly line to shake hands
with workers. He climbed behind the wheel of a new red, four-wheel
drive truck and drove it off the assembly line, carrying with him
United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber and Michigan's two
senators, Carl Levin and Don Riegle.
   As he had done in other cities a day earlier, Dukakis met
privately with leaders of Jackson's former campaign _ an
organization that produced a two-to-one Jackson victory over
Dukakis in Michigan's hybrid caucus system.
   ``I want them; I need them; I want them to be a part of not only
a great campaign but what I hope will be a great administration,''
Dukakis said.
   He met twice with Joel Furguson, Jackson's former Michigan state
chairman, who voiced support for the Dukakis-Lloyd Bentsen ticket.
``Our entire organization is ready to plug in and go,'' Ferguson
said.
   The candidate also met with the state's top Democrats, including
Detroit Mayor Coleman Young, one of the few black elected leaders
who backed Dukakis over Jackson in the primaries.
   Dukakis, speaking to 500 people outside another GM plant, where
Buicks are assembled, cited the report on Pentagon procurement
practices conducted for the administration by a commission headed
by David Packard. He said the report indicated the Reagan
administration had helped create a climate where ``honest and
efficient military acquisition is impossible.''
   ``In a Dukakis administration, we're not going to surrender our
national security to greed and corruption,'' Dukakis said.
   In the plant, Dukakis was greeted warmly by workers and
presented a maroon jacket with the UAW name and ``Duke for
President'' embroidered on the back.
   ``We want good jobs and these are the kinds of jobs we want for
the people of this country, to make our industrial base and
manufacturing industries competitive again,'' he said.
   The rally was in the same town where another GM auto assembly
was closed within the past year, leaving more than 3,000 people out
of work. Both Jackson and another primary rival, Rep. Richard
Gephardt, had traveled to that closed Flint plant for speeches last
spring.
   Asked what hope he could offer the laid-off workers, Dukakis
cited his plan to spend half a billion dollars investing in
economic development in distressed regions of the country.
   Dukakis repeated his criticism of the administration's handling
of Pentagon contracts later in Sturtevant, Wis., where he toured a
plant that makes metal casings for auto transmissions and other
machinery.
   Dukakis repeated his criticism of the administration's handling
of Pentagon contracts later in Sturtevant, Wisc., where he toured a
plant that makes metal casings for auto transmissions and other
machinery,
   Dukakis spoke to about 300 people in the parking lot of the
Wisconsin plant, where he said that bringing labor and management
together will be a ``major challenge to me if I'm president.''
   About 25 anti-abortion and other demonstrators chanted protest
slogans for much of his speech.
