<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MollyDodd-Lifetime     07-29 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Molly Dodd-Lifetime,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC's `The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd' Gets New Life on
Lifetime Cable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' the
critically praised series dropped by NBC for low ratings, is moving
next year to the Lifetime Cablevision Network, Lifetime announced
Friday.
   ``Molly Dodd'' was nominated Thursday for three Emmy Awards,
including Blair Brown for best lead actress in a comedy.
   Pat Fili, Lifetime's senior vice president of programming,
called ``Molly Dodd'' ``the perfect show for us.'' Lifetime is
geared toward female viewers. ``Molly Dodd'' is a bittersweet
comedy about a divorced woman in her late 30s living in New York.
   ``We expect this show will flourish in its move from network to
its new home on cable where the talent will have more creative
freedom and less restrictions,'' said Fili.
   In January, Lifetime will begin airing the 26 episodes already
produced and has contracted for 13 new episodes that will begin
running in the spring.
   The acquisition marks the first time since the USA Network
continued production of ``Airwolf'' two years ago that cable has
continued production on a show canceled by a network.
   Lifetime's purchase of ``Molly'' is significant in view of the
decline in network ratings and higher cable viewership.
   Jay Tarses, the creator and executive producer of the show, said
he was thrilled that the show would stay in production.
   ``Lifetime is doing something that could be very revolutionary,
could signal a new age in television for the creative community,''
said Tarses. ``It's another place to go, and there should be other
places to go, because this is a show that a lot of people wanted to
watch and the network said there just weren't enough people.''
   Tarses had been critical of NBC Entertainment President Brandon
Tartikoff's taste in programming after NBC moved the show around
the schedule and complained about its low ratings. But Tarses
avoided criticizing Tartikoff anew.
   ``I think he's one of the most intelligent men in the United
States,'' Tarses said, getting a big laugh from TV critics
attending the news conference.
   ``I said some things when all this was going on at NBC because I
was very upset about what had happened, but it all had to do with
the emotion of the moment,'' he said.
   Tarses also produced ``The `Slap' Maxwell Story'' on ABC. It was
dropped after a season. An earlier Tarses co-production, ``Buffalo
Bill,'' became a cult hit in reruns on cable. It too received
critical praise on the network, but was canceled due to low ratings.
   Tarses said he had to be convinced that a move to cable was
worthwhile, but is now sold on the idea.
   ``This could be the answer for people like me,'' he said.
``Maybe cable is exactly where we should be. `Frank's Place' (on
CBS) got nine Emmy nominations, but last week it was 72 (in the
Nielsen rankings).
   ``I don't want `Molly' to die, and this looks like genuine life
to me.''
   Tarses said the show would be produced in New York instead of
Los Angeles and that production would resume in January. The show
is unaffected by the writers' strike because the production company
has an independent contract with the Writers Guild.
   Tarses said Brown was shooting a movie in London and he had not
talked to her but ``I think she feels the same way I do'' about
moving the show to cable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
