<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Israel     07-29 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Israel,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Israeli Envoys in Moscow in 20 Years Pray with Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With mixed feelings of warmth and caution, Moscow
Jews welcomed the first Israeli diplomats to visit the Soviet Union
in 21 years to Sabbath prayers at sundown Friday.
   ``Shalom!'' shouted the burly, bearded delegation head, Meron
Gordon, as he and the five other Israelis met a crowd of 60 Jews
and reporters outside Moscow's Choral Synagogue.
   The Soviet Jews replied with shouts of shalom, a Hebrew word
that means both hello and peace.
   The diplomats, four of them Soviet-born, flew to Moscow Thursday
for a two-month visit. They are to inspect the former Israeli
Embassy in Moscow and review the Dutch Embassy's processing of
requests by Soviet Jews for Israeli visas.
   It is the first such mission to the Soviet Union since 1967,
when the Kremlin broke relations with the Jewish state to protest
Israel's occupation of Arab territories in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Inside the synagogue, Gordon, 41, who emigrated from the Soviet
Union in 1957, chatted in Hebrew with the Soviet Union's chief
rabbi, Adolf Shayevich.
   ``This is really special for us,'' Gordon told journalists.
``Every synagogue for us is the crucial point, the crossroads where
the Jewish community meets.''
   He and the other Israelis, wearing the traditional skullcap, the
yarmulke, took seats for Sabbath prayers.
   Many of the Soviet Jews said they learned of the planned visit
to the synagogue from radio newscasts on Voice of America and from
Israel.
   Several Soviet Jews outside the synagogue on central Moscow's
Arkhipova Street told reporters Friday night that they want to
emigrate.
   A 28-year-old man who identified himself only as Arya said he
had ``warm feelings'' toward the Israeli visitors, but was
concerned they had come in part to enforce a new Israeli policy
limiting the options of Jews who want to leave.
   The Israeli Cabinet ordered a change in procedure in June that
would force most emigrating Soviet Jews to go to Israel. Under
current rules, most emigres can choose where they want to resettle,
and most go to the United States.
   Arya said he just received Soviet permission to emigrate with
his wife and 2-year-old daughter, and might prefer some other
country than Israel in which to settle.
   Boris Chernobylsky, a prominent refusenik, or Soviet Jew refused
permission to emigrate, told a reporter he doubted the Israeli
diplomats would push for freer emigration.
   ``They are afraid of Soviet authorities and want to please
them,'' he said.
   Shayevich, who some Jews say is under the tutelage of the
government, told reporters he believes most Soviet Jews who want to
leave have already emigrated. He said the Soviet government has a
legitimate right to force people to stay if they had access to
classified material.
   From January to June, 6,017 Soviet Jews emigrated. Last year,
the Soviet Union allowed 8,011 Jews to leave.
   The rabbi said he hoped the Israeli mission would lead
eventually to restoration of diplomatic relations with the Soviet
Union.
   The Kremlin says it won't restore ties until Israel withdraws
from the occupied lands and agrees to an international Mideast
peace conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
