<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GrainReserves     07-29 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grain Reserves,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Given Extra 30 Days On Grain Support Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who have grain price support loans
coming due on July 31 will have an option to extend them to Aug.
31, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Officials said the action was taken as a result of a preliminary
injunction issued July 21 by U.S. District Court Judge Harry H.
MacLaughlin in St. Paul, Minn. However, they left the door open for
a possible appeal of the court's order.
   The court order barred the secretary of agriculture from
implementing notices issued by the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service to county offices concerning
the extension of loans and whether or not certain commodities would
be eligible for storage in the agency's farmer-owned reserve
program.
   Earle Bedenbaugh, acting executive vice president of the
department's Commodity Credit Corp., said all terms and conditions
of the individual contracts will remain the same.
   Producers who have reserve contracts, special storage loan
contracts and 1985 and 1986 extended loan contracts will continue
to earn storage payments through Aug. 31, he said. The payments for
the additional month's storage will be made when farmers settle
their loans.
   Meanwhile, Bedenbaugh said USDA and the Justice Department are
``examining possible courses of action which could be taken in this
litigation.''
   He said the one-month extension of all loans was ``to alleviate
any confusion among producers and in the commodity markets'' that
might have been caused by the court's injunction.
</TEXT>
