<DOCNO> AP880729-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0688 07-29 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Bush Slow to Recognize Day-Care Need</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bentsen in Texas, comments on Senate race,
rumored new Treasury secretary; tops with 5 grafs, picking up in
4th graf pvs, One mother, and adds 4 grafs at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen said Friday that Republican George Bush had been slow
to recognize the need for more child care, but he also said the
vice president's proposal on the subject was ``a step in the right
direction.''
   That was a kinder verdict than Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis gave during a news conference while campaigning in
Wisconsin. Dukakis said of Bush's proposal, ``I don't know of
anyone who is seriously concerned about child care who thinks that
makes sense.''
   Bentsen flew back to his native Texas to complete a three-day
campaign swing, his first solo tour since receiving his nomination
last week at the Democratic National Convention. With a rally and
news conference in Amarillo, he was campaigning hard on the home
turf of his Senate-race opponent, Rep. Beau Boulter.
   He told reporters he was going ``full bore'' on both of his
candidacies and intended to spend all the money he raised for his
Senate race on that contest, despite Republican complaints that it
was unfair. Texas law allows Bentsen to run for both offices at
once.
   Earlier Friday, Bentsen visited a state-subsidized day care
center at the UCLA campus, posing with pre-schoolers and listening
to parents' and employees' questions about why there was not more
federal day care help.
   One mother getting her degree in education told him that her
``whole eight years of education is more or less down the drain''
until her child is old enough to go to school, since she won't be
able to afford day care once she leaves the campus program.
   ``We're beginning to make some headway. We're really beginning
to see some attention given to this issue,'' Bentsen said, citing
his involvement last year in creating a commission to study
children's issues in Congress.
   Bentsen told reporters afterward that the Reagan administration
had fought him last year when he earmarked $50 million for federal
day care subsidies to local government. He said Bush's $2.2 billion
proposal amounted to a ``conversion.''
   ``I think the Bush proposal is a step in the right direction and
I'm delighted to see them get aboard on this issue,'' said Bentsen,
who as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee reviews any changes
in tax law. ``They have not been very supportive of these kinds of
efforts over the past eight years.''
   Asked if he supported the Bush plan's tax credits to mothers who
stay home with their children, Bentsen declined to comment, saying
he wasn't familiar with the details. He pointed out that Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., had drafted a competing plan with
subsidies and standards for day care centers.
   Dukakis has said he supports the Senate Democrats' legislation
in principle.
   The UCLA center, available for students and employees of the
university, is heavily subsidized with parents paying part or none
of the cost depending on their income. The center has an annual
budget of $650,000 and there are 77 youngsters enrolled, said
administrator David Menninger.
   The most a parent pays is $440 a month, which is less than
two-thirds the cost for care at the center which is just off Sunset
Blvd.
   Bentsen predicted Congress would eventually approve a blend of
the different child care proposals, including some tax credits and
some subsidies.
   Sen. and Mrs. Bentsen, who have three children and five
grandchildren, spent about 15 minutes with the children, some of
whom were frightened by the media commotion. Others seemed to enjoy
the scene.
   The 67-year-old Texas Democrat, dressed in a suit suitable for
the Senate chamber, bounced a boy on his knee, telling him
``Ride-em, Cowboy.'' He also got close-up looks at a wide variety
of plastic dinosaurs.
   On another subject, Bentsen, who is chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, praised Nicholas Brady who has been widely
reported as the next Treasury secretary if and when James Baker III
leaves that job to take over as Bush's campaign chairman.
   Bentsen said he expected there would be little opposition to
Brady, whose nomination would have to be cleared by his committee.
   Though Baker is still in his job and no nomination of Brady has
been announced, Bentsen spoke as if the changes had been put in
motion.
   ``I think that's a good choice,'' he said. ``Nick served in the
United States Senate. He was appointed to that job and served there
a few months, made a lot of friends. I'm very pleased to see the
choice. He's a man who has broad experience in the area and I think
will bring a lot to the job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
