<1ST_LINE>r w AM-President'sPlane     07-29 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-President's Plane,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Running Behind on Delivery of New Presidential Jet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has been notified that
the Boeing Co. is running behind schedule for delivery of the new
Air Force One, the jet that carries the president.
   Air Force Capt. Michael Laughlin said Friday that the
manufacturer ``had set a goal a long time ago of trying to get
delivery'' by Nov. 30.
   ``But it's a one-of-a-kind'' sort of plane, the spokesman said
in a telephone interview.
   He said Boeing told Pentagon officials it was having ``technical
difficulties with the installation of wiring bundles and the
availability of parts associated with'' the interior wiring.
   Loughlin said that Boeing is going to announce soon ``a new
delivery date,'' and administration officials hope the wide-bodied
Boeing 747 jet will be ready in time for some use by President
Reagan.
   At the White House, James C. McKinney, director of the military
office, said presidential aides hope Boeing can have the plane
ready at least by Jan. 20, 1989, inauguration day.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, would then get to use the new
aircraft to fly to their home in California.
   Asked if it appeared the aircraft would not be ready by
mid-January, McKinney said, ``Not so far, but everybody's got their
fingers crossed.''
   Meanwhile, the Air Force is building a new hangar kitchen to
replace the one at Andrews Air Force base in suburban Maryland that
has been used so far to prepare in-flight meals for passengers of
the presidential jet.
   Because the larger Boeing 747 will allow the seating of 93
people on the custom-made jet, compared to 69 seats on the existing
Boeing 707, the Air Force must have a hangar kitchen capable of
turning out as many as 4,000 meals at a time for Air Force One and
another Boeing 747 that flies as its backup.
   The custom-made presidential jet has a private compartment for
the chief executive as well as a flying office and separate
compartments for aides, guests, Secret Service agents and traveling
reporters.
   Laughlin acknowledged that it would be unlikely that Air Force
One and its traveling companion, the backup Boeing 747, would ever
need as many as 4,000 meals.
   But he said that capability is based on a ``worst-case
requirement,'' and that it represents the amount of food-serving
capacity that would be necessary if 93 passengers aboard each
aircraft made a seven-day trip and had three meals per day.
   Laughlin said the construction of an enlarged kitchen at the
Andrews Air Force Base hangar was necessitated by the need to keep
a larger volume of meals ready for loading onto the planes.
   ``You can make the pre-packaged meals in about the same space,
but it's storing them that's the problem,'' he said.
</TEXT>
