<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OilRig     07-29 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Fire Extinguished at Demolished Oil Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oil troubleshooter Paul ``Red''
Adair put out the last blaze Friday at the Piper Alpha petroleum
platform, which was demolished three weeks ago by an explosion and
fire that killed 167 men.
   A spokeswoman for Occidental Petroleum, the operator and main
owner of the platform, said Adair's crew poured concrete down the
last of the oil wells at the site, 120 miles east of Scotland in
the North Atlantic.
   She added that ``there is much work to be done yet'' on the
burned-out platform, which exploded in a fireball the night of July
6. It was the world's worst oil rig disaster, and Occidental said
it suspected a gas leak was responsible.
   Adair, 73, was called in to extinguish fires that continued
burning at many of the platform's 36 wellheads. He and his crew
pumped sea water into the wells and sealed them with concrete plugs.
   The Occidental spokesman said Adair will return to Aberdeen this
weekend if his men make enough progress with their remaining tasks.
   Lloyd's insurance exchange has said the accident is expected to
cost insurers a record of more than $1 billion.
   Work continued on stabilizing the platform. One of the legs has
been partly filled with cement and a steel cross-frame is to be
built.
</TEXT>
