<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Flights     07-29 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Flights,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany reduces number of low-level military flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry said Friday it is
reducing the low-altitude military training flights over West
Germany by 2,000 hours a year.
   Public protests about low-altitude flights have increased
because of several accidents involving NATO jets on training
missions.
   Rupert Scholz, the defense ministser, told reporters he had
rescinded an order for the training of jet fighter pilots as bomber
pilots, ``eliminating without replacement 1,000 hours of low-level
flights.''
   Another 1,000 hours of low-altitude training flights are to be
moved to a training area at Decimomannu on the Mediterranean island
of Sardinia, Scholz said.
   Since March 31, five U.S. Air Force F-16 jet fighters have
crashed on training flights over West German territory, including
three June 29.
   Fighter jets of the British, French and West German air forces
also have crashed in the past four months.
   Scholz announced July 5, after a West German F-4 Phantom
crashed, that he was making reduction of low-level training flights
a priority.
   According to the Defense Ministry, about 45,000 hours of flight
training are carried out by NATO military units annually over West
Germany.
   Military officials have said the flights are necessary to keep
pilots at top readiness.
   Scholz said he hopes to achieve further reductions in domestic
flights by West German air force fighters.
   Training of West German pilots at Goose Bay, Labrador, will be
increased by about 1,000 hours to 5,000 hours a year in 1990 or
1991, Scholz said. He also said he has been in contact with other
NATO officials to urge them to take all possible measures to reduce
the number of low-altitude flights.
</TEXT>
