<HEAD>Fitzwater Says Dukakis for ``Weaker Defense''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis aide's response, inserting 2 grafs after
5th graf pvs, ``He basically</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Friday that Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis ``is
for a weaker defense.''
   Fitzwater made the comment after a visiting West German
conservative leader, Franz Joseph Strauss, said at the White House,
``Every American president will provide the same policy regardless
of who wins'' the presidential election.
   Strauss, speaking with reporters after a meeting with President
Reagan, said, ``The guidelines of American policy will remain
unchanged.''
   However, presidential spokesman Fitzwater said, ``We have great
differences with the Democratic nominee in terms of defense posture.
   ``He basically is for a weaker defense and cutting defense, and
we are for a strong defense. He is for reducing commitments all
around the world, it would seem. So I would simply ask that anyone
take a pretty close look at Mr. Dukakis' foreign policy and defense
policies and they can judge for themselves.''
   The Dukakis campaign was quick to respond. ``Marlin Fitzwater
must be consulting the White House astrologer on Dukakis' position
on defense,'' said senior campaign adviser Kirk O'Donnell.
   ``Dukakis is for a strong defense and a strong America and he is
for strengthening alliances like NATO,'' O'Donnell said.
   Strauss, the minister-president (governor) of Bavaria and head
of the Bavarian branch of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's governing party,
talked to reporters in English.
   Vice President George Bush, the expected Republican presidential
nominee, walked up to reporters questioning Strauss and posed for
pictures with the visiting leader.
   Asked what difference it would make to West Germany whether he
or Dukakis became the next president, he stressed his familiarity
with the North Atlantic Alliance, saying, ``I understand the
alliance, I have been part of strengthening the alliance, I have
been working for the alliance.''
   Asked specifically to comment on Strauss' view that the election
would mean little difference to U.S. policy, Bush said Strauss ``is
a good man and he's my friend. He can say anything he wants here. I
don't want to put him in a difficult position.''
</TEXT>
