<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfArmsShipments     07-29 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Arms Shipments,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Book Says Frankfurt Airport Hub For Gulf Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frankfurt airport has become the
hub for arms shipments to the Persian Gulf region, according to a
book that goes on sale Monday.
   Juergen Roth, a West German journalist and television writer,
says in ``The Illegal German Weapons Business and Its International
Entanglement'' that the national airline Lufthansa carried military
supplies to Iran as late as June.
   Arms and ammunition are brought to Frankfurt by foreign
transport planes every two months, transferred to Iran Air and Iraq
Air cargo jets and flown to the gulf, he said. Iran and Iraq have
been at war since September 1980.
   Georg Schreiber, spokesman for the Frankfurt airport customs
office, said Friday no illegal arms were passing through the
airport.
   ``We control strategic goods coming in and passing through.
There has never been a case of such illegal wares being
transferred,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Roth accused West German security officials of ``silently
tolerating'' illegal arms transfers.
   He said an Israeli cargo jet landed at the airport last Dec. 29
and customs police provided security while it was unloaded. The
cargo included ``electronic spare parts and air-to-air rockets for
U.S.-built Iranian air force F-14 and F-15 jet fighters,'' Roth
said.
   According to the author, the plane also carried supplies for
Iranian Hawk air defense artillery batteries and about 80 TOW
rockets, and the cargo was transferred to an Iran Air jet.
   Citing investigations by Swedish customs officials, and
statements from a West German weapons dealer identified as Paul
Beermann, the writer said the weapons were being shipped by a
syndicate of several European companies.
   He said many of the arms moved under false manifests, sometimes
as industrial chemicals and hardware.
   Companies involved are located in West Germany, Britain,
Switzerland, France, The Netherlands, Italy, Norway, Belgium and
Sweden, Roth said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
