<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Escapees-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru a0613 07-29 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Escapees-Kidnap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Two Escaped Burglars Kidnap Minister</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with identification of minister, capture
of suspect.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who was abducted by two state
prison escapees and forced to drive them away in a church van was
released unharmed Friday and one of the convicts was captured,
police said.
   Michael Truitt, youth and education minister at Cresthill
Baptist Church, was released when the inmates abandoned the van
about 100 miles away, said Chatham County Police Chief Al St.
Lawrence.
   The two inmates who abducted the minister escaped with a third
man Thursday from a work detail at the prison near the Savannah
International Airport.
   Captured Friday was Steve McDuffy, 31, of Baldwin, who was
serving a 20-year sentence for burglary. McDuffy was arrested
without incident shortly before 4 p.m. while trying to make a
telephone call a couple of miles from where the van had been
abandoned, police said.
   Dennis L. Williams, who was serving two life sentences for
killing his two infant sons, was found hiding in a boathouse on
Thursday. He told police he was left behind by the other two
convicts when they waded into the marsh because he could not swim,
detectives said.
   Officers identified the man still at large as Kendal Eugene
Yawn, 25, of Alamo, who also is serving a 20-year sentence for
burglary.
   Truitt, 29, drove the van to the church Friday morning to meet
children who were to attend a day camp, St. Lawrence said. The
escapees had broken into a restroom at the church sometime during
the night, he said.
   None of the children had arrived when the abduction occurred and
the trip was canceled.
</TEXT>
