<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Jordan 1stLd-Writethru a0678 07-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Jordan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US To Maintain Aid To Palestinians Despite Jordan's Abandonment Of
Fund</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Recasts lead to stress US private aid while future of fund is
in doubt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will keep providing aid to
Palestinian Arabs through private relief groups while it seeks an
explanation from Jordan for abandoning a special development
program on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   ``These projects enhance the well-being and economic development
of the Palestinian people,'' State Department spokesman Charles E.
Redman said Friday.
   U.S. contributions this year are expected to total $7 million.
   Jordan announced on Thursday it was canceling the development
program in a move to give more responsibility over the 1.5 million
Palestinians in the Israeli-held territories to the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   A Jordanian statement in Amman said the kingdom was taking the
step in ``response to PLO demands.''
   The program, which exists largely on paper, is a $1.3 billion
plan for which the United States contributed $5.5 million in 1986,
$14 million in 1987 and $5.7 million this year.
   Italy has contributed about $20 million and Britain a lesser
amount.
   The plan had the enthusiastic support of Secretary of State
George P. Shultz as a means of improving the ``quality of life'' on
the West Bank and in Gaza, and also had the endorsement of Israel.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it
was not clear whether the fund would be canceled, turned over to
the PLO or operated in some other way.
   The State Department avoided any criticism of Jordan's decision.
   ``I don't have any reaction other than to say that we're
consulting with the government of Jordan regarding the announcement
and how it intends to implement the decision,'' Redman said.
   He said Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy would
take up the issue with Jordanian leaders when he is in Amman next
month. Murphy also will visit Egypt, Israel and Syria and has urged
Palestinians to meet with him.
   While King Hussein's decision was widely interpreted as at least
a partial withdrawal from the West Bank, the State Department said
it was too early to make any analysis.
   ``I just don't have any way to further evaluate the impact of
the Jordanian decision, and that's why we're going to talk to them
about how this decision is going to be implemented,'' Redman said.
   Asked if the United States would keep making contributions if
the fund were run by the PLO, the U.S. official said: ``Obviously
not.''
   Shultz is counting on Hussein to support a U.S. plan for peace
talks with Israel that would exclude the PLO but include
Palestinians in a Jordanian delegation.
   Hussein and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir have not
endorsed the plan, but Shultz is expected to make a fifth
peace-seeking trip to the region in the fall to solicit their
support.
   ``We don't interpret this announcement that we're talking about
as any lessening of Jordan's intention to remain actively involved
in the peace process,'' Redman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
