<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Slayings     07-29 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Slayings,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor, Two Union Officials, Six Peasants and Policeman Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police communique released Friday
reported the killings of six peasants, a mayor, two union officials
and a policeman but did not say who might be responsible for the
deaths.
   It said all 10 victims were slain Thursday.
   The peasants were killed at a ranch near the town of Puerto
Libertador, 230 miles north of Bogota, according to the report.
   Right-wing death squads have been accused of killing dozens of
peasants in northern Colombia in the last six months. Some
officials have blamed leftist guerrillas.
   The communique also said gunmen fatally shot Ramiro Garcia,
mayor of the town of Convencion, 250 miles northeast of Bogota. It
did not give details. Garcia, of the Conservative party, was
elected mayor March 13.
   The report said two officials of the petroleum workers union
were killed in the oil refinery town of Barrancabermeja, 160 miles
north of Bogota, by a gunman on a motorcycle.
   A policeman in the southeastern town of Aguas Claras also was
fatally shot by a man on a bicycle, the communique said without
elaborating.
</TEXT>
