<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Referendum     07-29 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Referendum,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chilean Opposition Asks Military To Stop Politicking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition alliance said Friday it has
asked the military to stop officers from campaigning because it
compromises the forthcoming presidential referendum.
   Patricio Aylwin told a news conference the coalition delivered a
letter to the military junta Tuesday protesting such activity.
   Aylwin is president of the centrist Christian Democratic Party,
one of 16 political groups that formed the alliance to promote a
``no'' vote in the referendum.
   The government plans a yes-or-no ballot in October on a single
candidate, who will be nominated at a meeting Aug. 30 of the army,
navy, air force and national police commanders. President Augusto
Pinochet, 72-year-old army commander who seized power in 1973 coup,
is expected to be chosen.
   Several high-ranking officers who favor Pinochet's nomination
have been campaigning at public rallies and in military gatherings.
Aylwin said that ``compromises the legitimacy of the (electoral)
process.''
   Chile's Constitution charges the armed forces with ensuring the
impartiality of elections.
   The coalition's letter, copies of which were given to reporters
Friday, said ``a significant number of officers, almost all of them
from the army, have begun to openly carry out an ostensible
political-electoral activity in favor of a `yes' vote.''
   It said the officers also were calling on troops in barracks
speeches to support the candidacy of Pinochet, ``whom they descibe
as the `supreme leader' or the `chieftan of the armed forces, with
a rhetoric similar to ... that of fascist and other dictatorial
regimes.''
   The referendum will be the first presidential ballot since a
Marxist, Salvador Allende, won the 1970 electoin. Gen. Pinochet
overthrew him in September 1973 and Allende died in the coup.
   If a majority votes for the candidate, he will begin an
eight-year term in March 1989. If he is rejected, a Pinochet is to
remain in power until a free election in 1990.
</TEXT>
