<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Media     07-29 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Media,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Closes Own State-Run Radio Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government suspended a state-run
news program Friday, a newspaper reported, in a strange twist in
the leftist Sandinistas' crackdown on the Nicaraguan press.
   The Radio Sandino news show ``En Directo'' was suspended for 48
hours for violating communications law, according to an Interior
Ministry communique published Friday in the government newspaper El
Nuevo Diario.
   The private news show ``Fabuloso Siete'' said the suspension was
ordered because of ``strong criticism'' by the government program
of one of the deputy directors of the opposition newspaper La
Prensa.
   A Radio Sandino newswoman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the suspension stemmed from a commentary made Thursday by one
of the broadcasters of ``En Directo.''
   The suspension of a state-run program may represent an effort to
project an image of fairness in the government's series of
broadcast and newspaper closures. It was the first action against a
state-run news organization.
   The crackdown began after government opponents held a big
demonstration July 10 outside Managua. Police battled protesters
and arrested about 40 people.
   The next day, the government complained of media coverage and
ordered La Prensa, Nicaragua's only opposition newspaper, and the
Roman Catholic station Radio Catolica closed. La Prensa reopened
Wednesday after its 15-day suspension, but the Catholic station was
closed indefinitely.
   A private news show, ``El Despertar,'' was also shut down
indefinitely. Another private show, ``El Noticiero,'' broadcast on
Radio Mundial, returned to the air this week after a 48-hour
suspension.
   Also Friday, El Nuevo Diario reported that a group of family
members blocked a road Thursday leading to Masachapa, about 30
miles southwest of Managua, to protest recruitment of youths into
military service.
   The newspaper said the demonstration ``was manipulated by
certain individuals.''
   La Prensa showed a photograph in its Thursday night edition of
special police forces shoving women.
   The two-year mandatory military service has been bitterly
opposed by many Nicaraguans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
