<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Justice-DrugTesting     07-29 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Drug Testing,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Injunction Against Drug-Testing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge issued a permanent injunction
Friday against the Justice Department's drug-testing program, under
which the agency would test 1,800 employees who are in sensitive
law enforcement posts.
   U.S. District Judge George Revercomb initially issued a
preliminary injunction, saying mandatory random drug testing cannot
be justified because the department does not consider drug use to
be widespread at the agency.
   ``It is impossible to argue that mandatory random urinalysis
drug testing serves the purpose of deterring illegal drug use by
trusted and apparently law-abiding employees,'' Revercomb said in a
14-page opinion granting the preliminary injunction.
   The judge said the 42 Justice Department employees who sued in
an attempt to block the program show ``a strong likelihood of
success'' on their claim that compulsory random urinalysis drug
testing is an unreasonable search and seizure that violates the
Fourth Amendment
   The government had asserted a critical interest in the security
of sensitive and classified law enforcement information and in the
integrity and public image of the department.
   Yet ``given the absence of a drug problem at the Department, it
is difficult to see how security of sensitive information, or the
integrity and public image of the Department would be much served''
by drug testing, said the judge.
   Revercomb noted that employees also might embezzle, obstruct
justice or accept bribes, but that ``no one could seriously argue
that, absent any grounds to suspect misconduct,'' the Justice
Department would be justified in tapping the employee's telephone,
censoring his mail or searching his house.
   ``Something more than unfounded fears must justify an intrusive
search,'' Revercomb said. ``Even though a relaxed `reasonableness'
standard applies to a search by the government as an employer, such
a search must be for a non-investigatory and work-related purpose.
... Referring to previous cases, Revercomb noted that
individualized suspicion is ``usually a prerequisite to a
constitutional search or seizure.''
   Under the Justice Department plan announced late last month, the
agency would have started testing in as soon as 60 days. Seven
percent of a group of 1,800 employees in positions deemed sensitive
would be tested annually.
   After issuing the preliminary injunction, the Justice Department
sought, and was granted, a permanent injunction. The government
will ask the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals next week for a stay of
the permanent injunction so that the department can proceed with
the program, said Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown.
   It can be more difficult to obtain a stay of a preliminary
injunction because the legal question presented in that instance is
whether a district judge abused his discretion, which is quite
broad. The review of a permanent injunction would examine the
merits of the constitutional arguments in the case, a prospect
favored by the Justice Department.
   Assistant Attorney General John Bolton had argued Thursday to
Revercomb that ``the whole world is watching,'' including leaders
of the Medellin cocaine cartel and Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   Stephen Sachs, the former Maryland attorney general, who is
representing 42 Justice Department employees who filed sued to stop
the program, said the agency ``clearly does not understand the
difference between ends and means.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
