<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Disease 1stLd-Writethru   07-29 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Disease, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0619,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Epidemic Claims Nine More Lives in Indian Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with lieutenant governor submitting
resignation after meeting on epidemic, details; PICKUP 3rd graf
pvs, Meanwhile, in ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least nine people died of cholera or
gastroenteritis in New Delhi on Friday, raising July's death toll
from the two diseases to 191, a city health official said.
   The United News of India reported that Lt. Gov. Harkishan Lal
Kapur, the top administrator of New Delhi, submitted his
resignation after a meeting Friday with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
on the water-borne diseases.
   No reason was given for Kapur's resignation and there was no
word whether it was accepted.
   The city health official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said 1,027 new cases of the diseases were reported Friday in the
city.
   Meanwhile, in the northern Indian state of Uttar Pradesh, 157
people have died in the gastroenteritis and cholera epidemic that
has broken out in at least 30 of the state's 57 districts,
newspapers said Friday.
   The deaths raised the number of victims nationwide to 618 since
monsoon rains started in late June. Officials blame the epidemic on
the contamination of the water supply by rainfall flowing through
sewage and uncollected garbage.
</TEXT>
