<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Singapore     07-29 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore Proposes Elected President, Keeping Parliamentary System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official government report proposed Friday
that Singapore have an elected president who would act as custodian
and not as chief executive, and that the parliamentary system be
kept intact.
   The first deputy prime minister, Goh Chok Tong, said in
presenting the suggested government reforms to Parliament:
   ``The president will not be an executive president. He will only
have a custodial role in two areas _ safeguarding our financial
reserves and the integrity of our public service.''
   Goh said the president should not have power to initiate
policies or make executive decisions.
   The president currently has no special powers but is ceremonial
head of the state. He must assent to any bill passed by Parliament
before it becomes law.
   The recommendations, drawn up by senior ministers, said the
parliamentary system of government should not be altered. The prime
minister and his Cabinet should govern the nation.
   On critical issues, they would still make the decisions but
would have to seek the president's concurrence. If the president
did not go along, the government could take the issue to the people.
   Parliament now elects the president for a four-year term. Under
the changes, the people would directly elect the president for a
six-year term.
   Sinnathamby Rajaratnam, senior minister in the office of
longtime Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, indicated on July 22 that Lee
could be chosen president.
   ``As far as I know, they (ministers) have decided Goh should
become the next prime minister the moment Prime Minister Lee steps
down,'' Rajaratnam was quoted as telling reporters.
   Lee will be 65 years old in September.
</TEXT>
