<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MIABurial     07-29 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIA Burial,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airman Listed as MIA for 22 Years is Buried in Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APALACHICOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of an Vietnam War Air
Force man listed as missing in action for 22 years were returned
Friday to his native soil in this Florida Panhandle fishing village.
   A funeral and burial ceremony with full military honors were
held for Herbert Eugene Smith, 30, killed July 29, 1966, when his
plane was shot down during a top secret mission over Laos. He was a
flight engineer.
   His remains and those of five other crew members were among
those of 17 U.S. servicemen returned March 2. Smith was a chief
master sergeant in the Air Force.
   Smith's wife, Barbara, 47, of Satellite Beach, said she believed
he might still be missing until forensic experts in Hawaii and
Colorado confirmed the remains were those of her husband.
   ``I was shocked,'' she said in a telephone interview published
Friday in the Pensacola News Journal. ``It was like ... for 22
years, even though he wasn't alive, he wasn't dead. He was still a
part of me. He was a part of my life. Then I was told it was
definite ... it was no longer a mission in my life to find out what
happened to him.''
   Before leaving Travis Air Force Base, Calif., Smith called his
wife on June 30, 1966, their 10th wedding anniversary. A month
later his plane disappeared.
   The Air Force initially told her the plane disappeared over
Thailand where the aircraft was based and there was hope her
husband survived. She also was told not to discuss the matter
because it might hinder his rescue.
   But years later she learned from the Central Intelligence Agency
that her husband was on a top secret mission over Laos. That news
angered her.
   ``I feel like I was lied to lots of time,'' she said. ``I feel
like they withheld information.''
   Mrs. Smith, who had gone to Laos in search of her husband in
1973, cried throughout the service.
   A seven-member honor guard from Tyndall Air Force Base near
Panama City fired three rifle volleys and two buglers played taps.
The U.S. flag that draped the casket was presented to the widow.
   Smith's children, now ages 23 to 31, were struggling with
burying a man few of them remember, Mrs. Smith said.
   Mrs. Smith, who earned a high school diploma and eventually a
master's degree in social work after her husband disappeared, works
as re-adjustment counselor for the Vietnam Veterans Outreach Center
in Orlando.
</TEXT>
