<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FinancialCorp     07-29 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Financial Corp,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadline Extended For Completing Deal With Bass Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal thrift institution regulators said
Friday they have extended the deadline for completing a deal with
the Robert M. Bass Group to take over one of the nation's largest
savings and loan associations.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said it expected to wrap up
negotiations with the Fort Worth, Texas-based Bass group for
acquisition of American Savings and Loan Association of Stockton,
Calif., by Sept. 1.
   The bank board had announced on April 21 that it had granted
exclusive negotiating rights to Bass until July 5, but later
extended that to Aug. 1.
   According to the agency's statement, ``then as now ... the
extension was granted because of the substantial progress made in
the negotiations to that date.''
   The ailing American Savings, owned by the Irvine, Calif.,-based
Financial Corp. of America, the second largest thrift holding
company in the nation, has been a candidate for a government rescue
for nearly a year.
   When the deal is finally completed, it is likely to set a record
as the largest rescue of a savings institution.
   According to a source familiar with the negotiations, the cost
to the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which insures
deposits in S&Ls up to $100,000, would be roughly $1.3 billion to
$2 billion.
   But, the source said, little or none of the assistance would be
in cash. Most of it would come in the form of promissory notes from
FSLIC or in guarantees against the risk of certain kinds of future
losses.
   One of the factors apparently snagging the deal is the Bass
Group's concern that the FSLIC assistance would be subject to
California's 11 percent corporate income tax.
   The California legislature has scheduled a hearing Aug. 8 on a
bill that would make it clear the tax does not apply.
   ``These have been complex negotiations, and the staff has worked
out most of the economic terms,'' said M. Danny Wall, chairman of
the bank board. ``However, there are other details to work out and
documents to complete, and we as a board need time to carefully
review the final recommendation from our staff.''
</TEXT>
