<HEAD>Actress Faces New Battle With Cancer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jill Ireland, who lost her
right breast to cancer four years ago, said Friday the illness has
returned but she will fight it with radiation therapy and willpower.
   Miss Ireland, 52, said she learned this week she has a localized
malignancy in her lymph nodes, but it is not spreading. She will
undergo five weeks of radiation treatment.
   ``I was absolutely terrified again'' and her husband, tough guy
actor Charles Bronson, was ``shocked and fearful'' when told the
diagnosis, she said during a news conference.
   The cancer was discovered when Miss Ireland sought treatment for
what she thought was a strained shoulder. Instead, it turned out to
be swollen lymph glands pressing on nerves above her right collar
bone, she said.
   Miss Ireland said she will also use a technique called
visualization to battle the illness.
   ``I visualize my cancer as fish eggs, and three times a day I
will visualize my piranha fish destroying, literally gnashing their
teeth and destroying my cancer,'' she said. ``That's a very good
technique because it stops you feeling like a victim.''
   Miss Ireland wrote a best-selling book called ``Life Wish''
about her 1984 bout with cancer and announced her new book, ``Life
Lines,'' will appear in March.
   She declined to reveal the contents, calling it ``somewhat
explosive.''
   She also is scheduled to be host of a syndicated television talk
show this winter, she said.
