<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-March     07-29 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-March,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Forces Ensure March's Non-Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military deployed thousands
of troops to guard against violence in a march Friday that marked
the 1975 killing by security forces of 14 student demonstrators.
   About 600 students walked peacefully from the University of El
Salvador campus to the downtown site where the 14 were killed on
July 30, 1975.
   The marchers, many of them masked and carrying wooden staves or
iron bars, placed banners and a wreath of evergreen branches and
yellow roses at the site and sang a revolutionary song before
returning to campus.
   Gen. Carlos Vides Casanova, the defense minister, told a news
conference military intelligence had expected about 70 armed
guerrillas among the marchers. He said leftist rebels battling the
U.S.-backed government are infiltrating labor, student and peasant
unions.
   At a separate news conference, a new alliance of peasants,
students and leftist workers called the Bread, Land, Work and
Liberty Movement accused the armed forces of killing one of its
leaders, Rigoberto Orellana.
   The government had called the alliance a guerrilla front.
   Orellana died Thursday after he was hit by a car in downtown San
Salvador. Jorge Villegas, Jaime Estevez and Santiago Flores, also
leaders of the group, said the car had followed him for days and
that he was run over intentionally.
   Armed forces officials were not available for comment on the
allegation.
   After a July 21 rally by students and workers that turned
violent, authorities were apprehensive about Friday's march.
   Police broke up the July 21 march with tear gas and gunfire. At
least nine vehicles were burned in that demonstration.
   Col. Galileo Torres, head of the armed forces press office, said
thousands of troops were mobilized Friday, including all National
Police and Treasury Police units in the capital. He said the 1st
Army Brigade and air force paratroopers were put on alert.
   Police with assault rifles were posted throughout the capital
near dawn. Loaded troop trucks patrolled downtown and two
helicopters hovered over the marchers.
   ``We don't cry for the martyrs of July 30th, we imitate them
with combative struggle,'' the marchers chanted. ``Yankee invader,
El Salvador will be your tomb.''
   The only incident occurred when soldiers tried to prevent U.S.
journalist Chris Norton, doing work for the Christian Science
Monitor, from photographing a water cannon.
   They tried to handcuff him, then threw him to the ground before
other journalists came to his aid and identified him. The soldiers
then let Norton go.
</TEXT>
