<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BoliviaCocaine     07-29 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia Cocaine,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captured Cocaine Kingpin Attributes Drug Problem To America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted cocaine kingpin Roberto Suarez
Gomez told reporters Friday the U.S. government is responsible for
the cocaine problem and that he allowed himself to be captured
because he opposes drug trafficking.
   Eight Bolivian journalists were allowed to meet with Suarez
Gomez in the San Pedro Prison in La Paz.
   He was arrested 10 days ago at his ranch 350 miles east of La
Paz.
   ``I hold the Reagan administration totally responsible for the
great advance of this (drug) affliction against humanity because it
had the obligation to delineate an efficient policy to confront the
problem,'' Suarez Gomez told the reporters.
   They quoted him as saying,``Without taking credit away from the
police, I facilitated my capture precisely because I could not
continue to carry the guilt of traffickers on my shoulders. That is
why I decided to come and face the situation that awaited me and
clear up my situation.''
   He added: ``I am not the king of cocaine, but rather the king of
the fight against cocaine. I have always fought to keep the price
of cocaine high to save my people and humanity from the brutal
effects of trafficking.''
   Suarez Gomez, 57, was greeted with shouts of ``Long live the
king!'' by inmates when he arrived at the La Paz prison Tuesday
from another jail.
   He is serving a 15-year prison sentence imposed this year after
he was convicted, in absentia, of dealing with illegal drugs.
   Suarez Gomez was indicted in Florida in 1980. He was accused of
conspiring to ship 854 pounds of cocaine into the United States.
   U.S. Drug Enforcement Admininistration spokesman Jack Hook has
said Suarez Gomez dealt in tons of cocaine.
   ``He could be considered one of the pioneers involved in
manufacturing and trafficking cocaine to the United States,'' Hook
said of Suarez Gomez.
   The prisoner also told the reporters that the cocaine trade has
a strong influence in the world of politics, but he did not give
any names of politicians who might have connections with drug
traffickers.
   Bolivia, an impoverished country with a population of 6.7
million, produces at least a third of the cocaine that reaches U.S.
and European markets, according to the DEA. It is estimated that
about 350,000 Bolivians depend for their livelihood on cultivating
coca leaves, processing them to be turned into cocaine or
trafficking.
</TEXT>
