<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Veterans 2ndLd-Writethru a0765 07-29 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Veterans, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0765,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Turn Goods Over To Sandinistas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 CORRECT that convoy sponsored by coalition of
six activist groups sted one, delivered several tons of food. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, Customs officials ....</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto MGA3</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy of 44 U.S. activists
delivered several tons of food, medicine and clothing to the
leftist Sandinista government Friday and President Daniel Ortega
praised them at a public ceremony.
   ``These people are representatives of the American people who
don't want war, they want peace,'' Ortega said to about 200 people
who gathered in Luis Alfonso Velazquez Park.
   Wounded Nicaraguan soldiers watched the ceremony and children
mobilized by the Sandinista Party chanted: ``Let's go to war, carry
the bullets!''
   The Veterans Peace Convoy, sponsored by a Washington-based
coalition of six activist groups, journeyed across Mexico and
Central America for two weeks after a dispute with the U.S. Customs
Service.
   Customs officials said the group, which includes many veterans,
would violate a 1985 economic embargo if they donated their
vehicles, as they plan to do. Humanitarian aid is allowed under the
embargo.
   ``While Reagan sends arms to the (rebel) Contras to murder our
children, he tried also to obstruct this caravan,'' Ortega said.
``He said they carried goods that threatened the security of the
United States.''
   Ortega had a child bring him a box of the goods and took out a
baby bottle. ``Look at the weapons they brought,'' he said, holding
it up. ``This is what Reagan did not want to arrive.''
   He screwed the top on the bottle. ``The weapon is ready to
fire,'' he announced. ``All it needs is milk.''
   Convoy member Raul Valdez spoke out against U.S. funding for the
rebels, known as Contras, who have been trying to overthrow
Nicaragua's leftist government for nearly seven years.
   ``This money that is sent to cause death here is being taken
away from our children,'' he said. ``Our taxes shouldn't be used to
kill Nicaraguans. It's unjust, immoral.''
   The activists were given military T-shirts and Sandinista army
hats. The ceremony ended with the Sandinista anthem, which
proclaims: ``We fight against the Yankees, enemies of humanity.''
   A convoy spokesman said the supplies would go to three
Sandinista organizations representing children, workers and women.
He also said 18 of the 20 vehicles would be left in Nicaragua with
party organizations, including labor unions.
   The operations of the Sandinista Party and the government are
closely intertwined in Nicaragua.
   When the veterans crossed the U.S. border, they were told they
faced fines of up to $50,000 each and 10 years in prison if they
did not bring the vehicles back within 30 days.
   A U.S. Treasury Department official in Washington, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Friday that no decision had been made
on whether to file charges against convoy members. He said the case
was under active review by the department's Office of Foreign
Assets Control.
   In June, U.S. Customs officials stopped the original convoy of
38 vehicles from crossing into Mexico. About 100 convoy
participants drove to Washington to demonstrate against the
decision, circling around the White House and in front of the State
Department for three days.
   Eight members of the group were arrested July 9 when they
refused to leave the road leading to a toll booth at a Rio Grande
bridge crossing at Laredo, Texas. The convoy finally crossed the
border July 14.
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada said thousands of people
greeted the convoy when it crossed the Honduran border Wednesday
into Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
