<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Church     07-29 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Church,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglicans Seek Compromise on Issue of Woman Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A compromise shaped up from private
discussions at the Lambeth Conference Friday on the issue of
consecrating the first women bishop in the Anglican church.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, head of the Anglican
communion, has said that although all Anglican churches probably
would accept women priests, a woman bishop could split the
communion. The U.S. Episcopal church and New Zealand church are
considering consecrating women bishops.
   The 525 bishops representing 70 million Anglicans in 164
countries will debate the issue Monday at the Lambeth Conference.
   A compromise resolution drafted Friday by John Neill, bishop of
Tuam in Ireland, urges the conference to respect differences of
opinion.
   It says the conference recognizes ``the serious hurt which would
result from the questioning of the validity of the episcopal acts
of a woman bishop, and likewise the hurt experienced by those whose
conscience would be offended by the ordination of a woman to the
episcopate.
   ``The church needs to exercise sensitivity, patience and
pastoral care toward all concerned.
   ``While addressing the issue we have tried to stress the deep
hurt that will be involved both ways among those who are offended
by it and by those who do not feel it goes far enough.''
   Archbishop Donald Robinson of Sydney, Australia, introduced a
resolution saying women should not be consecrated as bishops ``for
the avoidance of further impairment of communion both within and
between the churches.''
   Monday's debate will come at the start of the last week of the
three-week conference.
   This is the first Lambeth Conference to be held in 10 years.
Each of the 27 Anglican churches worldwide is self-governing but
they look to the Church of England for guidance and Runcie is the
world Anglican leader.
   The last Lambeth Conference in 1978 evaded the issue of women
priests by saying all the member churches should respect each
other's decisions. The question of a woman bishop did not arise at
that time.
   According to conference statistics, some 1,200 women have been
admitted to the priesthood by a minority of the Anglican churches,
most of them in the United States, Canada and New Zealand.
   Opponents say the concept of woman priests does not exist in
Bible teaching. They also say that bishops are considered the
successors of Christ's Apostles, who were men, and if a woman
bishop is consecrated some churches might leave the communion on
grounds she could not be in communion with the other bishops.
</TEXT>
