<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PipeBombs     07-29 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pipe Bombs,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in Salem, Another Found at South Bend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pipe bomb exploded early Friday in a
mailbox at Salem, just hours after a similar bomb was discovered in
the county courthouse at South Bend, about 200 miles to the north,
authorities said.
   No one was injured in the Salem explosion, and damage was minor,
police said. The bomb found in the St. Joseph County courthouse was
removed safely and detonated by police explosives experts.
   In Indianapolis, police said eight sticks of dynamite were found
Thursday in a city park, but were not wired to explode, police
said. ``I have no idea if there is a connection, or if it is a
copycat thing,'' said Indianapolis Deputy Police Chief Robert Ward.
   Since early July, a variety of explosive devices have been
planted in four Indiana communities. No arrests have been made, and
investigators have established no connection among the incidents.
   The bomb that detonated about 12:45 a.m. at Salem High School
was the second to explode in the state in a week. An exploding bomb
destroyed a door at a Loogootee school the night of July 22,
causing about $500 damage but injuring no one.
   In the first Salem incident on July 5, 13 dynamite time bombs
were discovered scattered around the city, prompting the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to send an investigative
team from Washington.
   ATF agent James M. Vaughn said in Louisville, Ky., that he does
not believe the two Salem incidents are related. Investigators also
discount the possibility of a link with the explosion at Loogootee,
about 50 miles west of Salem, said Vaughn.
   In South Bend, the investigation is being handled by city and
county authorities. On Wednesday a section of pipe wired to a
battery and timing device, but containing no explosives, was found
on a city street. ``We are not discounting the theory that the
incidents are connected,'' said sheriff's Cpl. Charles Feirrell.
   The courthouse bomb was found around 8 p.m. by a cleaning worker
in a basement restroom, said Sheriff Joseph Nagy. Police evacuated
six employees who had remained after office hours and routed
traffic away from the courthouse. The bomb was removed by a
remote-operated pulley and exploded at a gravel pit outside the
city, police said.
   The dynamite used in the original Salem bombs was traced to a
theft of dynamite last month from a crushed stone quarry in
English, about 30 miles southwest of Salem, investigators say.
   Investigators said the bombs were improperly wired. Three of the
bombs ignited, but did not explode, and produced only smoke and
small fires. The Indiana Arson Crime Association and ATF each have
offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to an arrest and
conviction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
