<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Apartheid     07-29 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Apartheid,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Closes Visa Loophole For Tennis Stars, Golfers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian government closed a loophole Friday
that allowed South African tennis stars, golfers and other athletes
to compete in Canada despite a Commonwealth ban on sporting links
with South Africa.
   Foreign Minister Joe Clark said in the future, individuals
traveling on South African passports and seeking entry into Canada
to participate in a sports event will be denied visas.
   The change means that South African tennis players Gary Muller
and Christo van Rensburg, scheduled to compete in next week's
Canadian Open tennis tournament in Toronto, will be denied visas.
   The minister told Parliament earlier this week that he intended
to close the loophole in a 1977 agreement that encourages
Commonwealth countries to combat apartheid by discouraging contact
or competition with athletes from South Africa.
   Ambassador Johannes Hendrik de Klerk of South Africa reacted to
that announcement by saying sports in his country had been fully
integrated for years.
   ``Isolating individual South African sportsmen and women can
make no positive contribution towards change in South Africa,'' de
Klerk said.
   Opposition members of Parliament pointed out that the agreement
was effective against sports teams from South Africa, but
individuals were entering the country on business visas.
   Clark said his action ``is fully in keeping with the major role
the Canadian government has played in the international struggle
against apartheid.''
   Next week, the Commonwealth committee of foreign ministers on
Southern Africa will meet in Toronto to review the fight against
apartheid, although no new sanctions are expected. Clark is
chairman of the eight-member committee.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which
South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
