<DOCNO> AP880729-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OceanLight     07-29 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ocean Light,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Light Source At Bottom Of Pacific</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA BLANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is light at the bottom of the deep dark
seas, scientists say they have discovered off the Washington coast.
   A group of scientists headed by University of Washington
oceanographers said they photographed the ocean-bottom light at
hydrothermal vents 180 miles off the Washington coast.
   The vents, openings along the ridges where the plates of the
Earth's surface meet, spew out 650-degree water that has picked up
minerals in the seabed.
   The light confirms a hypothesis that Cindy Lee Van Dover, 34, a
graduate student in oceanography in a joint Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution and Massachusetts Institute of Technology
program, has been working on for two years.
   The discovery also ends the long-held scientific belief that
there is no light at the ocean bottoms, said John Delaney, 46, UW
professor of oceanography and lead scientist for the dive.
   Ms. Van Dover, after whom the light has been named the ``Van
Dover Glow,'' began her research in the summer of 1986 on live
shrimp that crowded together around Atlantic Ocean hot springs
feeding on bacteria. The creatures lack normal shrimp eyes.
   Ms. Van Dover said she noticed large organs beneath their shells
that had no lenses, but otherwise looked like eyes. Further study
proved the organs were light-sensitive, although they could not
form images.
   ``If hot springs glow, then the shrimp would be able to use the
organs to lead them to the glow, and hence, to food,'' Ms. Van
Dover hypothesized.
   Tuesday, during the research submersible Alvin's final
2,200-meter dive, which is nearly 1.4 miles below sea level, the
scientists said they finally proved the hypothesis.
   Submarine pilot Dudley Foster held the vessel steady enough
against strong currents for a camera to take 20-second exposures of
the hot springs.
   When processed, the images showed light coming from two
different hot springs, the scientists said.
   The university announced the findings before the scientists
could publish them in any journal where they would be subject to
peer review.
   Ms. Van Dover said scientists do not yet know what produces the
light, but it could be because the minerals in the water heat up so
much they glow or it could be due to a chemical reaction.
   The light could offer some new possibilities to theories of
evolution of living creatures, Ms. Van Dover said.
   ``The thought that there could be photosynthesis (using light to
produce food) down there is an entirely new idea,'' she said.
``There has been a lot of thought on the origin of life and how
deep-sea life may have played in it.''
   The Alvin is scheduled to make another dive in four weeks, and
Delaney said either he or Ms. Van Dover will be aboard. The two are
considering experiments for that trip including identifying the
color of the light, its wavelength and measuring how far it
penetrates through the water, Delaney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers     07-29 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Seeking Fingerprints; Cite New Evidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers refused Friday to give her
fingerprints to police, who said they have new evidence in the
investigation of how she handled donations for her dying son's
liver transplants.
   Dade County prosecutors have been looking into Mrs. DeSillers'
handling of more than $689,000 donated for her 7-year-old son
Ronnie, who died in April 1987 awaiting his fourth liver transplant.
   Fort Lauderdale Police Chief Joseph Gerwens said new
developments from the investigation prompted his department to
issue a search warrant for the finger and palm prints of Mrs.
DeSillers and several others.
   He refused to elaborate on the information, saying only that no
arrests have been made.
   Mrs. DeSillers' Miami attorney, Roy Black, filed a motion in
Dade Circuit Court Friday, saying issuance of a search warrant for
the woman's fingerprints is ``an invasion of her body.''
   Judge Ralph Person scheduled an emergency hearing on the matter
Monday.
   Repeated telephone calls to Mrs. DeSillers' home by The
Associated Press resulted in a busy signal. Fred Kerstein, who is
handling the Dade County investigation, refused to comment.
   Ronnie, born with defective liver ducts, first attracted
national attention after a February 1987 robbery at St. Anthony's
Roman Catholic School in Fort Lauderdale, in which $4,000 collected
by schoolmates was taken.
   News of the incident prompted a nationwide outpouring of
donations for Ronnie's medical care, including a $1,000 gift from
President Reagan.
   Gerwens refused to say whether the fingerprints are related to
the parochial school robbery.
   Mrs. DeSillers has refused to pay $262,000 in medical bills to
Children's Hospital in Pittsburgh, saying her son received improper
care.
   A court-appointed caretaker of the donated funds said Mrs.
DeSillers improperly used $200,000 of the money on luxury items
ranging from jewelry to a BMW sports car.
   On Thursday, a Dade Circuit judge ruled that she is not entitled
to the remaining $240,000 of the donated money and that it should
instead pay medical bills, debts and help other needy ill children.
</TEXT>
