<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAtlantic-Apartheid     07-29 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAtlantic-Apartheid,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Atlantic Nations Condemn Apartheid, Shun Waste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented meeting of 22
South Atlantic nations ended Friday with a call for sanctions
against South Africa and an end to transferring nuclear and toxic
waste to the region.
   The participants also called on Argentina and Great Britain to
reach a definitive peace settlement in their dispute over the
Falkland Islands, off the Argentine coast.
   Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and 19 African nations signed the
declaration at the end of the five-day meeting, the first of its
kind for the region.
   The 22 countries met at Brazil's invitation to create a ``zone
of peace and cooperation'' in the South Atlantic. The concept
involves keeping the region free of military bases and nuclear arms
in accordance with a 1986 U.N. resolution.
   The countries voted to ``condemn the abhorrent policy of the
racist regime of apartheid in South Africa, the continued illegal
occupation and colonial domination of Namibia, South African acts
of aggression against Angola and other neighboring states.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   The 22 nations recognized SWAPO, the South West Africa People's
Organization, as the ``sole and legitimate'' representative of
Namibia, also known as South-West Africa.
   The group endorsed ``the imposition of comprehensive and
mandatory sanctions against the South African regime.''
   The statement also urged joint efforts to block transfer of
toxic waste to the South Atlantic. Countries in West Africa have
recently shown mounting concern over the dumping of garbage there
from Western nations, including the United States.
   The participants called on Argentina and Great Britain to
continue talks on the future of the Falkland Islands, which
Argentina calls the Malvinas. Argentina claims it owns the
British-held islands and waged an unsuccessful war in 1982 to take
them over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
