<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-LawyerKilled     07-29 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Lawyer Killed,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel's Attorney Found Shot To Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer who won acquittal two weeks ago for a
suspected guerrilla leader was found shot to death on an oceanside
highway near Lima, the Interior Ministry said Friday.
   It said Manuel Febres Flores, 45, was killed Thursday morning
and his body was recovered hours later, with no identification.
Police said he was beaten and was shot seven times.
   Febres Flores, a member of a laywers' group accused by the
government of having ties to the leftist Shining Path guerrillas,
successfully defended Osman Morote against terrorism charges and
won his acquittal.
   The president of the Association of Democratic Lawyers, Alfredo
Crespo, blamed a ``repressive instrument of the government'' for
the killing.
   A group calling itself the Rodrigo Franco Democratic Front,
after an official slain by the Maoist-oriented Shining Path last
year, called Lima newspapers and claimed responsibility for the
death, reporters said.
   Government officials denied any knowledge of the group and the
Interior Ministry vowed to track down Febres Flores' killers.
   The government considers Morote the Shining Path's No. 2 leader
and military strategist. Morote was cleared for lack of evidence
but remains in jail facing other terrorism charges.
   In his state of the nation address Thursday, President Alan
Garcia, head of the left-of-center Aprista Party, condemned
Morote's acquittal and demanded tougher anti-terrorism laws.
   Crespo told The Associated Press that members of the lawyers'
association have been receiving death threats for six months. The
association frequently defends people accused as guerrillas and is
considered a Shining Path front by the government.
   The Shining Path insurgency began eight years ago. The
government says it has claimed 15,000 lives and caused $10 billion
in damage. The Shining Path, which has no known ties to any
guerrilla organization in Latin America or elsewhere, seeks to
overthrow the government and create a communist state.
</TEXT>
