<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Grosz     07-29 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Grosz,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader Rules Out Multiparty System</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary-Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian leader Karoly Grosz, ending a 30-hour
visit to Canada after a U.S. tour, said Friday that reforms in his
country will not include loosening Communist Party control.
   Grosz, premier and head of the Communist Party, said Western
capital is necessary to help finance economic progress in his
country but Hungary is not prepared for a political system with
more than one party.
   ``This is not timely today in Hungary,'' he told a news
conference. ``I've seen countries in the world having a multiparty
system and still having no democracy.''
   Two weeks ago, the Hungarian Communist Party's Central Committee
approved economic and political reforms that include the creation
of a ``socialist market economy'' and legalizing the framework for
a pluralist party system.
   Grosz said the reforms will not undermine the goals of communism.
   ``We want a socialist system that works better,'' he said. ``If
a theory is carried out in a mistaken way, this doesn't necessarily
mean the system is not working.''
   Grosz, who has acknowledged the failure of austerity measures he
pursued after becoming premier in June 1987, said joint business
ventures between Hungarian industries and foreign corporations are
a key to overcoming the nation's economic stagnation.
   ``But I wouldn't like the Hungarian government to engage in
doing business, that's up to businessmen,'' he said.
   After a 55-minute meeting with Prime Minister Brian Mulroney,
Grosz said the Canadian leader ``agreed 100 percent with all the
ideas I put forward.'' There was no comment from Mulroney.
   Grosz also met hydroelectric, atomic energy and
telecommunications company executives to discuss possible joint
ventures.
   He refused to meet with Hungarian-Canadian human rights
activists angry at Romania's resettlement plans that include the
elimination of about 7,000 villages populated mainly by ethnic
Hungarians.
   Grosz said Hungary has sent a protest letter to the Romanian
government and added: ``As for the refugees (coming from Romania),
we accept all those who ask for the right to stay with us in
Hungary.''
</TEXT>
