<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras-Compensation     07-29 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Compensation,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Government To Compensate Family Of `Disappearance' Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Inter-American Court of Human
Rights on Friday found the Honduran government guilty in the 1981
disappearance of a student in police custody and ordered it to pay
damages to the man's family.
   A government spokesman said Honduras will comply with the order,
the first verdict handed down by the court.
   The decision in the case of Angel Manfredo Velasquez, 35, a
university student leader, came after an eight-month trial.
   The court is an agency of the Organization of American States
based in San Jose, the capital of neighboring Costa Rica. Its seven
international jurists are handling other cases of Central American
citizens who disappeared while in custody or suffered other human
rights abuses.
   Honduras' independent Human Rights Commission claims 150 people
have disappeared in Honduras during the past eight years, and
another 800 have been slain for political motives.
   Velasquez, a leftist, was a student at the National University's
College of Economics when police arrested him Sept. 8, 1981, during
the rightist military government of Gen. Policapo Paz Garcia. He
has not been heard from since.
   Student and labor activists protested his disappearance at the
time and several armed groups briefly invaded radio stations,
newspapers, news agencies and other media to press demands for an
investigation.
   Lisando Quesada, a spokesman for President Jose Azcona Hoyo,
told reporters: ``Velasquez's family will be (compensated) by the
state because Honduras faithfully complies with obligations under
international agreements.''
   Quesada refused to say how much the compensation will be.
   Ramon Custodio, president of the Human Rights Commission, said
he was satisfied with the court's decision and hoped it will mark a
new stage in respect for human rights in the region.
   ``Let us hope this case constitutes a starting point for wider
investigations on abuses of human life in Latin America,'' he said.
   Honduras had denied the charges against it, but two key
witnesses in the case were shot to death in the Central American
nation in January in what human rights advocates claim was an
effort by death squads to silence their critics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
