<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0671 07-29 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0936</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Optimistic For Fire Containment By Saturday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with most of evacuees in Rapid
City returning home, quotes from homeowner and planned reopening of
Yellowstone Park entrance. Picks up, 13th graf pvs, `Fires fed...'.
SUBS grafs 19-25 bgng `Members of...' to UPDATE with fund for
firefighters started, revised figures on outbuildings and vehicles,
and Idaho families going home. Picks up 23rd graf pvs,
``Firefighters in ...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher humidity Friday gave firefighters
the upper hand against a 3,000-acre forest fire that had destroyed
15 homes on the western edge of the city, but it remained the
top-priority fire in the nation.
   ``We're very confident today,'' said Steve Gallegos, fire
incident commander. He said the fire was 90 percent contained by
afternoon.
   Only a wisp of smoke was visible during the afternoon, drifting
with light wind.
   ``If the weather holds we're pretty confident that no other
structures will be lost,'' fire information officer Rich Homann
said.
   Homann said much of Friday was spent strengthening fire
containment lines.
   Firefighters said they hoped to contain the arson blaze by early
Saturday and control it by Sunday. That was the first time since
the fire started Tuesday that firefighters had given an estimate of
when they might get a handle on the blaze in the forested Black
Hills.
   ``It's looking a lot more positive than it has,'' said fire
information officer Mike Ball.
   Hundreds of people had evacuated their homes from several
subdivisions in and around the forest, and all but 125 people were
allowed to return home by Friday evening.
   Gene Ickler, who left his home on Wednesday, said he didn't know
what to expect when he returned Friday. The fire burned to within a
few feet of his house, but it was not damaged.
   ``You feel like doing a cartwheel to see your home standing,''
he said. ``The emotions really run.''
   Fire crews in Yellowstone National Park, where about 93,000
acres of forest has burned, took the calculated risk Friday of
setting their own fires in dead timber and brush to rob major fires
of fuel paths to building complexes.
   Park officials said the south entrance to the park will reopen
Sunday because the danger of fire reaching buildings around the Old
Faithful geyser had been significantly reduced.
   Fires fed by drought-dried fields and forests also blackened
regions of Alaska, Montana, Idaho, California, Washington and
Wisconsin. But all of Utah's fires had been tamed by Friday,
officials said.
   Humidity of 40 percent to 50 percent was expected to slow the
Rapid City fire, Ball said.
   ``Last night firefighters were able to work on that line that
they've been trying to complete in the southeast along Highway
44,'' Ball said Friday. Crews working by hand finished burning all
the fuel between the edge of the fire and the fire line.
   Flames jumped the highway at one point but only about 20 acres
burned on the other side before the fire was extinguished, said
Mary Sue Waxler, spokeswoman for the U.S. Forest Service.
   The blaze licking into housing developments in hills along the
western edge of this city of 50,000 people was the top priority
fire in the nation, Homann said.
   ``That basically means that when resources are requested for
this fire we will receive first priority,'' he said.
   Members of volunteer fire departments from around the state
saved 100 houses Thursday with an estimated value of $3.7 million,
Ball said. Those departments had brought 65 fire trucks to the area
to pump water onto threatened houses. A local businessman and his
father have started a fund for the firefighters, saying they should
be rewarded for their work.
   ``Firefighters are really risking their lives to protect
structures as well as they can,'' Homann said. ``One house had the
aluminum window sills melted out of it, and firemen were still able
to save the house.''
   In addition, National Guard helicopters carried hundreds of
loads of water to dump on buildings in the path of the fire.
   Considering that the fire spread over 600 more acres of housing
areas Thursday, firefighters did well to lose only eight houses
that day, said Waxler.
   The fire also had destroyed 40 outbuildings and more than 40
vehicles.
   Elsewhere, 10 families driven from their cabins in two
developments in a mountainous area northeast of Boise, Idaho,
because of the 4,600-acre Willis Gulch fire were allowed to return
home Friday night.
   More crews joined firefighters on the lines Friday, raising the
number of firefighters to more than 970.
   Firefighters in Yellowstone revised the number of acres burned
from 95,000 down to about 93,000 after aerial infrared mapping in
the 2.2 million acre park, which is the size of Delaware and Rhode
Island combined.
   On the 10,100-acre Shoshone fire, which forced the closure of
the park's Grant Village and threatened buildings in the complex,
officials got part way through a planned 300-acre burnout designed
to put a quarter-mile buffer around the village.
   Heli-torches _ flame throwers on helicopters _ were used to set
burnouts on the northeast flank of the 8,800-acre North Fork fire,
which threatened the large hotel and services complex surrounding
the Old Faithful geyser.
   ``We're happy with the burnout so far,'' said fire spokesman
Brian Fox. ``Once we get the northeast head of the fire dealt with,
it can go north, away from Old Faithful.''
</TEXT>
