<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlayboyClubCloses 1stLd-Writethru a0774 07-29 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Playboy Club Closes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last U.S. Playboy Club Closing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from patrons and
bunnies. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `On Saturday...'. SUBS 14th graf,
`Officials at...', to delete now-redundant reference to bunnies.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high heels, bunny tails and
figure-shaping costumes that transformed cocktail-serving into a
sexual fantasy will be just a memory Saturday, when America's last
Playboy Club closes.
   The Playboy Club in a Lansing hotel was filled to its 250-patron
capacity on Friday night for one last party, and 60 people ended up
standing outside.
   ``I want to grab a cottontail,'' said 42-year-old Bill McDonald.
   ``This is the first and last time I'll be here, so it's worth a
wait,'' said Lynda Nagle, who had never been to the Lansing club
but had fond memories of visits to the Playboy Club in Detroit more
than a dozen years ago.
   ``The food was great, the atmosphere was great. It was a place
to go to meet executive-type husband material,'' she said.
   Inside, Milos Tavorsky, a quiet man of ``around 60,'' sat alone
at the end of the bar, watching the camera crews and shaking his
head.
   Tavorsky said he'd been a three-times-a-week patron for the past
four years and couldn't remember a time when it was as crowded.
   ``A week ago there weren't 20 people hre,'' he said. ``This is
something.''
   Outside in a hallway, bunny Michelle _ even on the last night
they obeyed the rules about revealing their last names _ was taking
a snapshot of the waiting crowd while bunny Rochelle posed for with
a beaming man who tipped her $10 and whispered his hotel room
number.
   Rochelle just rolled her eyes.
   ``We get a lot of this,'' she said.
   Rochelle, a bunny for two years, said the last week had been
tough on America's last nine bunnies, though tips were good.
``There's few girls, so it's been difficult to take care of the
quantity of people,'' she said.
   On Saturday, the Playboy trappings _ oversized posters of
magazine covers and other memorabilia _ were to be auctioned for
charity.
   The custom-fit bunny costumes, however, will not be on the
auction block, said Playboy spokeswoman Terri Tomcsin in Chicago.
   ``Those go back to Playboy Enterprises,'' she said.
   Hugh Hefner opened the first Playboy Club in Chicago in 1960 and
the clubs had their heyday in the 1970s, when there were 22 around
the world.
   The company-owned clubs were closed in 1986, and the three
remaining franchise contracts _ with hotels in Des Moines, Iowa;
Omaha, Neb.; and Lansing _ were not renewed this year, Tomcsin said.
   Thriving clubs remain in Japan and the Philippines, and Tomcsin
said the company plans more overseas operations.
   Tomcsin said she has been surprised by the media attention the
Lansing closing received.
   ``We just had a big deal with the last of the company-owned
clubs,'' she said. ``That was different. We had been around for 26
years. We were very established. The Lansing club opened in '82 _
you can't really compare.''
   Tomscin said the media attention shows the Playboy philosophy
had an impact on America. ``We were more than just a fad,'' she
said. ``We had become an important part of American culture.
   Writer Gloria Steinem, who once took a job as a bunny to write
an expose, offered a different perspective.
   ``I think that Playboy clubs were based on sexual repression of
men and economic, kind of, oppression of women and I'm glad to say
both things are ending,'' Steinem said in an interview with ABC
News.
   Officials at the Lansing Hilton said the closing announcement
boosted business at the club, which scrapped the key cards and let
in the general public in 1987.
   ``Business has increased four or five times,'' said Hilton
general manager Rick Barrett. ``I think a lot of people realize
it's the end of a bit of Americana.'
</TEXT>
