<DOCNO> AP880729-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Democrats     07-29 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Democrats,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newly Merged Party Names Ex-Commando as Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly merged Social and Liberal Democratic
Party on Thursday elected a former Royal Marine commando, Paddy
Ashdown, as its first leader.
   Ashdown, 47, a member of Parliament since 1983, faced a tough
fight to restore the flagging fortunes of Britain's centrist,
third-ranking political movement. Its ratings have slumped in
acrimony over the merger, which was made final last March.
   Ashdown defeated Alan Beith, by 41,401 votes to 16,202, in a 72
percent turnout by the party membership after a lackluster
campaign. Both men formerly belonged to the Liberal Party.
   Ashdown said after his election that the new party had three
years _ until to the next election _ to supplant the opposition
Labor Party as the only prospect of providing a viable alternative
to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives.
   ``I don't underestimate the scale of the task,'' Ashdown said in
a television interview. ``But if I didn't believe we could do that
I wouldn't be doing this job.''
   The Liberals precipitated the merger after their electoral
alliance with the Social Democratic Party failed at the last
election in June 1987 to break the power grip of the Conservatives
and Labor..
   Social Democratic leader David Owen, a former foreign secretary,
refused to merge and has maintained a breakaway faction as a
separate party, thus splitting the already minority centrist vote.
   Liberal Party leader David Steel, who did not run for the
leadership of the new party, blamed the alliance's disappointing
showing in 1987 partly on having two leaders.
   The alliance took 22.5 percent of the vote, down from one-fourth
at the previous general election in 1983.
   The centrists' ratings in the latest poll, by Harris last week,
were down to 7 percent for the Social and Liberal Democratic Party
and 3 percent for Owen's faction.
   Ashdown, who represents Yeovil in southwest England, served in
the Royal Navy's elite, undercover Special Boat Service in the Far
East and later as a Royal Marine captain in the Middle East and
Northern Ireland, before turning diplomat.
</TEXT>
