<HEAD>Two Gunman Take $300,000 From Armored Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen wearing hardhats, masks and
sunglasses pistol-whipped a guard and stole more than $300,000 from
an armored car outside a bank, authorities said.
   The robbers fled, and an automobile matching witnesses'
description of their getaway car was found in a residential area
six blocks from the Wells Fargo bank branch office, said FBI
spokesman Tom Griffin. No arrests were made.
   Griffin said more than one shot was fired during the robbery,
but he did not elaborate.
   A guard in the Loomis Armored Inc. armored truck was struck in
the forehead with a gun by one of the robbers. The guard was
hospitalized and reported in good condition.
   Kim Kellog, a spokeswoman for Wells Fargo at the company's
headquarters in San Francisco, said the robbery occurred as the
Loomis truck arrived to deliver currency and coins to the branch
office. She confirmed that ``more than $300,000'' was taken.
   Investigators said the suspects attacked one of the guards at
the rear of the car as he prepared to make a delivery.
   ``They immediately started hitting him on the head with a
handgun,'' said police spokesman Sgt. Bob Burns. ``We don't know if
the shot was fired accidentally or if he fired a shot to frighten
him.''
