<1ST_LINE>s a BC-PreachingKids Adv07-1stAdd   07-29 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Preaching Kids, Adv 07-1st Add,0638</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>MARION, N.C.: totally saved.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mrs. Strode, who said she met her husband in a Chambersburg
barroom when she was 15 and married him a year later, acknowledges
she resisted the Lord for years after her husband and children were
converted.
   ``I even left one time, for 18 months, because I couldn't take
the constant preaching anymore,'' she said.
   ``During that time I lived like a whore, with seven or eight
different men. I was trying to see what the world had to offer but
I realized it didn't have anything for me, and I came back to my
family. A few months after that I was saved.''
   The family moved from Pennsylvania to North Carolina in January
1987.
   ``Everything we had was piled up on top of a flatbed truck,''
she said. ``We looked like ol' Jed Clampett of the Beverly
Hillbillies when we hit town.''
   Strode and his wife are natives of the Chambersburg area, just
north of the Maryland line.
   ``Robin quit school in the 12th grade because she was pregnant
with our second child, but I'm a high school graduate,'' he said.
   He said he went to high school in Gettysburg, living in a
children's home after his mother's death when he was 14. He spent
two years in the Army in West Germany and served a four-year
machinist's apprenticeship, he said.
   ``I used to be a drunken fornicator, but I always worked and
made good money.''
   Strode says he came to Marion after hearing a taped sermon by
Danny Castle.
   ``Things weren't going so good in Pennsylvania for us and I
really liked Danny Castle's preaching,'' he said. ``But now I'm not
so sure that he's really, truly saved.''
   In Pennsylvania, Strode was twice arrested while preaching,
charged with disturbing the peace, and he in turn accused
Chambersburg officials in a suit of violating his First Amendment
rights. The charges and the suit were eventually dropped, with the
city agreeing to pay his lawyer's fees.
   Will there be more trouble when public school starts up again,
on Aug. 22?
   ``We may send the kids to school or we may try and teach them at
home, if we can get together the money for the books and so
forth,'' he said.
   Asked what their response will be should the Strode children
resume their preaching on school grounds this fall, McDowell County
school officials would say only that they intend to enforce school
regulations to the letter.
   Those rules say children must go directly into the school when
they arrive. The Strode boys refused to go inside immediately,
instead preaching outside until the bell rang.
   ``Frankly, I'm afraid they might suspend my kids, like they did
last spring, and then try to take them away from me,'' Strode says.
``I love my kids and that's something I could never allow to happen.
   ``Who knows? We're in the process of building a house. Maybe
we'll just sell it and move away. Somebody probably would buy it in
a minute, just to get rid of us.''
   If the Strodes do leave Marion, the mayor of Chambersburg,
Robert Morris, he hopes they don't return to his community.
   ``Strode's a terribly disrupitve influence,'' Morris said in a
telephone interview. ``He used to go up and down our main street,
screaming at the top of his voice, calling people whores and
whoremongers and so forth.
   ``It's much quieter here since the Strodes left the area and,
frankly, we hope they never return.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
