<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-29 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0527</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending increased in June at the
fastest pace in 10 months, the government said, fueling concern
over inflation and whether the economy will have room for
production of exports.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that personal consumption
spending shot up a seasonally adjusted 1.0 percent in June, the
steepest climb since a 1.3 percent gain last August.
   The report was a disappointment to many economists who are
looking for growth in consumer demand to slow in order to narrow
the nation's trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of imported goods, one of the main
inflationary yardsticks in the U.S. economy, rose 2.7 percent in
the April-June quarter, the largest increase in more than a year,
the government reported.
   The Labor Department said Thursday that the second-quarter rise
followed a 1.2 percent increase in the January-March period and was
the steepest since the 4.1 percent jump in the first three months
of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most comprehensive banking bill since the
Great Depression cleared a House committee after 16{ grueling hours
of debate, but it faces an uncertain future with little time left
in Congress' legislative year.
   The bill, approved Thursday by the House Banking Committee,
grants banks broad new securities powers but restricts their
ability to enter real estate and insurance and imposes new
obligations on them to serve the poor.
   The bill now is headed for the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, where the chairman, Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., is
known to be skeptical of letting banks into the securities business.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress overwhelmingly approved some $6 billion in aid for
drought-stricken farmers after scaling back provisions for special
assistance to milk producers and ethanol fuel makers.
   Also Thursday, the Reagan administration projected the federal
deficit for the upcoming budget year at $140.1 billion _ short of
the trigger for across-the-board spending cuts _ but warned that a
hefty drought-relief bill could cause the automatic reductions to
kick in.
   Most wheat and soybean futures slipped lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. reported that its second-quarter
earnings slid 24.5 percent from a year earlier, and analysts said
buyer incentive programs may have shrunken results more than the
company expected.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker said Thursday its earnings fell to
$320.4 million, or $1.45 a share, from $424.1 million, or $1.98 a
share, in the second quarter of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to resurrect MGM and United
Artists as separate movie studios collapsed, when financiers Kirk
Kerkorian and Burt Sugarman announced they couldn't agree on
details of the $400 million deal.
   Extensive talks failed to produce a definitive agreement, MGM-UA
Chairman Stephen Silbert said Thursday.
   The investors had reported just two weeks earlier an agreement
in principle for Sugarman and his allies to buy 25 percent of a
``new'' Metro-Goldywn-Mayer, which was to be spun off from
Kerkorian-controlled MGM-UA Communications Co.
</TEXT>
