<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rates on 12-Month Treasury Bills Hit Highest Level in Three Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 52-week Treasury bills rose
in the government's latest action to the highest level in nearly
three years.
   The Treasury Department sold $9.0 billion of the bills at an
average discount rate of 7.40 percent on Thursday, up from 7.04
percent at the last auction on June 30.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 24, 1985, when the
one-year bills sold for 7.51 percent. The new discount rate
understates the actual return to investors _ 7.95 percent _ with a
$10,000 bill selling for $9,251.80.
</TEXT>
