<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RevcoReorganization Bjt   07-29 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Revco Reorganization, Bjt,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Drugstore Chain Files For Chapter 11 Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revco D.S. Inc.'s inability to pay the
huge debt incurred in its 1986 leveraged buyout has forced the
giant drugstore chain into federal bankruptcy protection, and
illustrated the potential risks to companies and investors involved
in such transactions.
   Revco D.S. Inc., which operates 2,000 U.S. drugstores in the
Midwest, Southeast and Southwest, filed for protection from
creditors Thursday, just over a month after failing to make a $46
million interest payment to holders of bonds issued to finance the
$1.5 billion buyout, the largest ever to fail.
   Boake A. Sells, chairman and chief executive officer, told a
news conference that holders of $400 million in junk bonds
accelerated the payment schedule after Revco missed the interest
payment June 15.
   Junk bonds are high-yield, high-risk notes commonly issued to
fund leveraged buyouts and other types of corporate takeovers.
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly with
borrowed funds that are repaid with the company's cash flow or sale
of its assets.
   Revco's buyout foundered as increased competition and sluggish
cash flow crippled the company's ability to cover its obligations.
   Against a tide of new discount operations and supermarkets
adding pharmacies, Revco tried to slash prices and move beyond
drugs to big-ticket items like small appliances. Lately, as those
efforts faltered, it refocused on its core drugstore business.
   Revco, which has annual sales of $2.3 billion, fills more than
65 million prescriptions a year.
   ``Revco's leveraged buyout didn't work out, and hundreds more
have,'' Sells said. ``Junk bonds have been the best investment on
Wall Street...but if you'd only invested in one junk bond you'd be
pretty unhappy if it was Revco.''
   D.S. Partners of New York owns controlling interest in Revco,
Sells said. When the drugstore chain missed its June 15 interest
payment, bondholders established a steering committee that
contacted the company.
   Proposed talks over having Revco turn over stock to satisfy the
debt broke down before they even started, Sells said.
   Revco has been ``husbanding'' cash the past few days to meet its
payroll and to pay venders who sell to the company after Thursday's
Chapter 11 filing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Akron.
   Revco's two largest venders reacted well to news of the
bankruptcy filing, Sells said. He said the reorganization might
disrupt shipments from a vender or two, but he does not expect much
change in day-to-day operations.
   The company does not play to lay off any of its 28,000 employees
because of Chapter 11 and has received court permission to continue
payments of salary and benefits, Sells said.
   The Chapter 11 filing includes Revco; its parent company, ANAC
Holding Co., and most of its subsidiary operations. Insta-Care
Pharmacy Services is not included, the company said.
   The filing allows Revco to obtain new credit and invoices for
goods and services, and requires the company to submit to
bankruptcy court a reorganization plan restructuring the company's
debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Interco Bjt   07-29 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interco, Bjt,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Capital Bids $2.46 Billion For Interco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partnership bidding $2.46 billion to acquire
Interco Inc. may have to raise its offer to satisfy shareholders,
some industry analysts say.
   Interco said Thursday that its board would meet Aug. 8 to
consider the $64 a share bid made by City Capital Associates, a
Washington, D.C.-based limited partnership.
   Wall Street indicated it believed bids for the apparel and home
furnishings manufacturing and retailing company. Interco stock
soared $13.37{ a share to close at $67.75 in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Thursday.
   Interco's best known brand names include London Fog clothes,
Florsheim and Converse shoes and Broyhill and Ethan Allen furniture.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, City
Capital said it already owned 8.7 percent, or 3.14 million, of
Interco's 38.4 million outstanding shares.
   City Capital listed its principals as Steven M. Rales and
Mitchell P. Rales. They are respectively the chairman and president
of Danaher Corp., a Washington-based manufacturer of automotive and
industrial products and vinyl building materials.
   Ned Armstrong, a securities analyst in the Washington, D.C.,
office of Johnston, Lemon, expressed confidence in the Raleses
ability to attract financial backing for what looks to be a
highly-leveraged bid for Interco.
   City Capital said it did not have financing commitments for the
proposed buyout, but said it was confident of being able to arrange
them.
   The partnership said that if it succeeded in acquiring Interco,
it planned to sell the apparel business and was considering the
sale of parts of its general retail merchandising and footwear
manufacturing and retailing businesses.
   But City Capital left open the possibility that it might reach
``a different conclusion as to which of (Interco's) assets might be
retained or sold'' after a review of the company's assets,
operations and policies.
   In a letter to the Interco board, City Capital also said it
might increase its offer based on a further review of information
about the target company.
   Robert F. Buchanan, a retail industry analyst with the
investment firm A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said he
believed Interco was worth more than the City Capital offer.
   ``I think a fair value is somewhere around $67,'' he said.
   Buchanan, who said Interco's footwear and furniture segments
were its most valuable divisions, said the company likely would
want to remain independent.
   Laurence C. Day, an analyst with Newhard, Cook and Co. Inc.,
agreed, saying he would be surprised if Interco was receptive to
the offer, even if City Capital offered to keep Interco management
intact.
   Day said recent actions by Interco were defensive moves designed
to boost the price of its stock and make a takeover attempt more
expensive.
   The company announced earlier this month it was considering
selling its apparel manufacturing group as part of a restructuring
that began in 1985.
   ``I think it's a real question whether Interco is interested,''
Day said. ``I would doubt it.''
   In addition to its manufacturing operations, Interco operates
201 retail locations in 15 states, including home-improvement
centers, general merchandise discount stores, men's specialty
apparel shops and specialty department stores.
   Interco had sales of $3.34 billion last year, with the apparel
group contributing about 24 percent.
   Buchanan said Interco's performance ``hasn't done as well as it
could in recent years'' and its stock price had languished.
</TEXT>
