<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
modest trading today but traders predicted fear of central bank
intervention would limit the currency's upswing.
   Gold prices fell slightly.
   Foreign exchange dealers said end-of-the-month commercial
requirements and technical short-covering nudged the U.S. currency
up in early trading.
   The dealers said dollar demand stemmed largely from corporate
customers who needed to cover their commercial obligations before
the end of the month. Some market operators were covering
short-dollar positions, or buying dollars to fulfill agreements to
sell them, ahead of the weekend as well, they said.
   Italian traders, however, predicted the market would not see a
significant rise in the dollars this session because fear of
central bank intervention inspired some caution.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7170, compared
with $1.7225 Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8764 West German marks, up from 1.8645; 1.5615
Swiss francs, up from 1.5505; 6.3280 French francs, up from 6.2885;
2.1088 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0920; 1,386.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,370.50; 1.2100 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2086.
   In Tokyo, whose business day ends before Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.43 yen to close at 132.53. Later, in London, it was
quoted at 131.92 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $432.10 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $433. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $432.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $432.25, down from $432.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid price of $434.48, up
from Thursday's closing bid price of $433.78.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.82 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $6.79.
</TEXT>
