<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rallies, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dipped slightly in afternoon trading in
Tokyo today but closed higher at 132.53 yen, while stocks continued
to rise.
   The dollar, which opened trading at 132.60 yen, finished 0.43
yen higher than Thursday's close of 132.10 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 57.52-point
winner Thursday, gained another 115.54 points, or 0.42 percent, to
finish the day's trading at 27,911.63.
   After opening slightly above the 28,000 mark, the most widely
followed barometer on the exchange remained higher than 28,000
through most of the morning session, but edged down in afternoon
dealings.
   It was the first time the index exceeded 28,000 points since
July 15. The Nikkei has fluctuated at the mid- and low-27,000 level
over the past two weeks.
   The market was helped in part by an overnight gain in New York,
traders said.
   Financials such as banks closed higher, led by Sumitomo, Fuji
and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Banks.
   Also among gainers were heavy industrials such as
Ishikawajima-Harima, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and Mitsui
Engineering and Shipbuilding.
   Electricals fell back after early gains as some investors took
profits.
   ``It has been an established pattern that if market opens
higher, it declines because of profit-taking,'' said a broker at a
major securities firm who would not be quoted by name. ``But the
environment is good and the dollar seems stable for some time.''
   Foreign exchange dealers attributed the dollar's strength to
reduced concern about growing inflation in the United States. In
New York overnight, the U.S. currency rose 1.05 yen to close at
132.60 yen.
</TEXT>
