<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Deficit 1stLd-Writethru   07-29 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Says Budget Deficit Will be Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add time element.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration says the federal
deficit will be $5.6 billion higher than it predicted back in
February, with the government's red ink now estimated to total
$152.3 billion this fiscal year.
   While the new administration estimate announced Thursday is
higher, it is still below the more gloomy projections earlier this
year by many private economists, who were forecasting a deficit of
$160 billion or worse.
   Those economists have been busy revising their own figures, and
some now say the administration's new deficit forecast for the
fiscal year ending Sept. 30 may actually be too pessimistic.
   As the year began, the administration predicted the overall
economy as measured by the gross national product would expand at a
sluggish 2.4 percent rate. The new budget has boosted that GNP
estimate to 3 percent.
   The higher growth this year has helped push the unemployment
rate down to a 14-year-low of 5.3 percent. More people working
means more tax revenues for Uncle Sam.
   Tax revenues are expected to be $4.2 billion higher than the
administration's February projection, according to the new report.
   Michael Evans, head of a Washington forecasting firm, said he is
now predicting the 1988 deficit will total $145 billion based on
the gains in tax revenues which have already occurred.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said he is
forecasting a deficit this year of $151 billion, slightly lower
than the administration's estimate.
   The administration is calling for the deficit in the next fiscal
year to decline to $140.1 billion, an estimate that private
economists say is generally in line with their own forecasts.
   That deficit estimate is $5.9 billion below the $146 billion
level which would trigger automatic spending cuts as required by
the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   However, White House budget director James Miller warned that
the $5.9 billion cushion did not leave much room for error,
especially given a lengthy list of spending measures Congress is
considering in an election year.
   The measure with the highest price tag is a drought-relief
package for farmers, which Miller estimated would cost the
government between $4.3 billion and $6.6 billion.
   Miller said President Reagan supports drought relief but is
opposed to using ``the plight of the farmers as an opportunity to
make a Christmas tree out of that bill'' by loading it up with
other farm assistance that has little to do with drought relief.
   Miller also listed as potential budget-busters measures to step
up the battle against illegal drugs and provide more aid the hungry
and homeless.
   He said if all the proposals were enacted by Congress, it would
increase spending between $6.4 billion and $8.7 billion, enough
even at the low end of the estimate to trigger the automatic
spending cuts.
   ``We can't do all the things that Congress has on its list right
now,'' Miller told reporters at a White House briefing.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., agreed
that the administration's mid-session review points up the need for
lawmakers to make tough choices in coming weeks.
   ``All of the urgent needs of the nation cannot be funded at the
levels most of us would support in less difficult times,'' Gray
said.
   Evans said he doubted that Congress would risk triggering the
across-the-board spending cuts, especially since they would take
effect only weeks before the November election.
   ``I think Miller is trying to hold people's feet to the fire so
Congress doesn't go crazy with the drought bill, but it would snow
in July before Congress would allow across-the-board spending cuts
to go into effect,'' Evans said.
   Evans said that last year, when Congress faced similar budget
problems, it found a way to keep within the deficit targets by
pushing $5 billion in spending from September to October, the start
of a new fiscal year. He said if necessary, lawmakers would resort
to similar budgetary tricks this year to escape mandatory spending
cuts.
   The administration's mid-session budget review projected that
the budget deficit would decline steadily in coming years.
   It forecast a 1990 deficit, if Congress accepts its proposals on
further spending cuts, of $102.3 billion, declining to $85.4
billion in 1991, $64.9 billion in 1992 and $34.2 billion in 1993,
the year the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law calls for the
budget to be brought finally into balance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
