<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Parliament     07-29 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Parliament,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita Calls on Parliament to Reform Tax System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita told Japan's
legislators Friday that tax reform is the most important domestic
issue facing the nation, and urged them to approve the first major
overhaul of the tax system since it was set up by U.S. occupation
forces in 1950.
   In a speech before the Japanese parliament, the Diet, Takeshita
delivered a strong appeal for passage of a tax reform package he
has pinpointed as a top item on his political agenda.
   ``There is an urgent need to rectify (distortions of the present
tax system) to institute a new tax system that is fair, simple and
acceptable to the people,'' he said.
   Tax reform has been long awaited by the average Japanese
salary-earner who bears a heavy direct tax burden, compared to
self-employed individuals and other categories of taxpayers who are
eligible for substantial tax breaks.
   Takeshita said that if his package is approved taxpayers will
win an unprecedented amount in tax cuts totaling 5.6 trillion yen,
the equivalent of $43 billion, for fiscal 1988 ending next March.
   But a shadow already looms over the tax reform plan.
   Opposition parties refused to open Diet proceedings until the
prime minister's ruling Liberal Democratic Party agreed to
substantial tax cuts. They are also demanding the government scrap
plans to introduce an indirect consumption tax of 3 percent on
goods and services next April.
   Takeshita indicated he was prepared to compromise: ``It is
important that the tax burden be passed along smoothly and justly,
and the administration will work to create the right environment
for this.''
   Earlier Friday, the Cabinet approved six tax bills making up
Takeshita's reform package due for debate in the Diet in upcoming
weeks.
   The new plan calls for reducing the 12 brackets in the
progressive income tax system, with rates ranging from 10.5 percent
to 60 percent, to five brackets ranging from 10 to 50 percent.
Residential taxes would also be reduced and corporate taxes would
drop from 42 percent to 37.5 percent.
   Eight categories of goods and services have been earmarked as
non-taxable, including medical care, education costs and capital
gains from land transactions.
   The 70-day extraordinary Diet session opened Tuesday after a
one-week delay and after an agreement by the ruling party to
investigate two recent developments: the role of a government
submarine in a marine disaster last Saturday and the recent
disclosure of unethical stock deals that reaped massive profits for
government officials, including a Takeshita aide.
   Takeshita opened his speech with an apology over the collision
between a military submarine and a leisure vessel that claimed 30
civilian lives.
   He also alluded to the legal but shady stock purchases in which
selected individuals were offered shares of the Recruit-Cosmos Co.,
a real estate firm, prior to their release for over-the-counter
dealings.
   ``We must always be mindful of political ethics and
self-discipline in government service ... and it is imperative that
we continually fulfill our responsibilities without even a hint of
impropriety,'' Takeshita said.
   The scandal involves more than a dozen prominent political and
business leaders suspected of earning huge profits by obtaining the
unlisted shares and then selling them after they were released on
the market.
   To date, Takeshita, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone and
former Foreign Minister Shintaro Abe have admitted their aides at
the time earned profits.
   In Japan, however, it generally known that aides act on behalf
of the politicians they serve.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Trade     07-29 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Rises From Previous Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan posted a current account surplus of $6.43
billion in June, up 11 percent from the previous month but down 14
percent from the same month last year, the Finance Ministry
announced Friday.
   In May, Japan's current account surplus totaled $5.79 billion,
while in June 1987 it registered $7.5 billion.
   The current account is the broadest measure of a country's
commerce, measuring trade in goods and services as well as other
capital flows.
   Ministry officials said imports continued to rise sharply during
the month. But they said exports also increased, continuing the
double-digit rise that began last November despite the higher value
of the Japanese yen.
   The officials said demand remained strong for Japanese products
in other countries, including the United States.
   ``The U.S. economy has been doing very well and that is one of
the major reasons for this increase, despite the yen's
appreciation,'' one official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   A higher yen makes Japanese products more expensive and
therefore less competitive overseas.
   The officials said demand remained especially high for Japanese
items such as automobiles, steel, semiconductors and business
machines.
   Japanese imports have been growing because of strong domestic
demand resulting from Japan's current economic expansion and
because of the higher yen, which tends to reduce the cost of
foreign products.
   Growth of imports of non-ferrous metals, lumber and steel was
particularly strong during the month, the officials said.
   Record numbers of Japanese tourists traveling overseas, taking
advantage of the yen's appreciation, helped reduce the current
account surplus, the officials said.
   The portion of the current account measuring flows of money
related to tourism, shipping, insurance, banking and commodity
services showed a record deficit of $737 million during the month,
they said. In May, the figure was $612 million, and in June 1987 it
was $251 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
