<DOCNO> AP880729-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-AutoExports     07-29 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Auto Exports,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's First-Half Automobile Exports Down 5.1 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's exports of four-wheeled automobiles fell
5.1 percent during the first six months of this year from the same
period of 1987, the Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association said
Friday.
   The association attributed the decline to the Japanese yen's
appreciation, which makes Japanese products less competitive abroad.
   Japanese car exports have been declining for two years. The last
time auto exports grew from year-earlier levels was in the first
half of 1986, when a 5.2-percent increase was reported.
   Expanding production in the United States by Japanese car makers
was another factor for the sustained fall in exports, the JAMA
report said.
   Exports of four-wheeled autos totaled 3.1 million in the first
half, the association said.
   Auto exports to the United States slid 17.5 percent to 1.3
million vehicles, accounting for 40.8 percent of the total
shipments to overseas markets.
   A total of 721,459 vehicles were exported to the European
Economic Community, down 3.2 percent from a year earlier.
   Those to Southeast and Northeast Asian countries, including
China, dipped 0.4 percent to 219,954 vehicles.
</TEXT>
