<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-BankEarns     07-29 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Bank Earns,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lloyds Returns to Profitability</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyds Bank PLC on Friday joined other major
British banks in announcing a return to profitability during the
first half of 1988 following its losses of a year ago.
   Lloyds said it had a net profit in the six months ended June 30
of 288 million pounds, the equivalent of $495 million, or 35 pence
a share, compared with a net loss of 516 million pounds in the same
period of 1987.
   The loss in the 1987 period, like those chalked up by other
major banks, was caused by Lloyds' additions to its reserves
against possible bad Third World loans.
   Revenue, which includes net interest income, foreign exchange,
commission, fees and other earnings, rose 11 percent to 1.46
billion pounds from 1.31 billion pounds.
   Interest income rose to 930 million pounds from 867 million
pounds.
   Lloyds' merchant bank recorded a profit of 5 million pounds,
compared with a loss of 32 million pounds a year ago.
</TEXT>
