<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pearson-Amerada     07-29 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pearson-Amerada,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pearson Sells Oil Subsidiary To Amerada Hess</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pearson PLC, the British conglomerate which
publishes the Financial Times, said Friday it sold its British oil
subsidiary, Whitehall Petroleum Ltd., to Amerada Hess Ltd. for $162
million in cash.
   Lord Blakenham, chairman and chief executive of Pearson, said
Whitehall's oil interests had potential but Pearson would have to
make a substantial capital investment in the subsidiary and wait
for years before it would make a significant contribution to the
conglomerate's profit.
   Sam Laidlaw, Amerada Hess Ltd.'s managing director, said the
acquisition ``is in line with our intention to further expand and
develop our North Sea interests.''
   Whitehall's principal assets are interests in Ivanhoe, Rob Roy
and the Waverley fields in the North Sea operated by Amerada Hess
Ltd. In addition, Whitehall has a portfolio of prospective acreage
with interests in 28 offshore licenses and 15 onshore licenses.
   Whitehall had operating profits of 2.5 million pounds, the
equivalent of $4.3 million, in 1987.
   Amerada Hess Ltd. is the British subsidiary of Amerada Hess
Corp. of the United States.
   The deal is subject to British regulatory approval, the
companies said.
   Publisher Rupert Murdoch acquired a stake of more than 20
percent in Pearson earlier this year, a move which Pearson called
unwelcome.
  
</TEXT>
