<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Insurance     07-29 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Insurance,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aetna Reports 32 Percent Drop In Operating Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aetna Life & Casualty reported Friday its
second-quarter earnings dropped 45 percent, due in part to a $45.1
million charge in connection with its coverage of A.H. Robins Co.
   Aetna said its second quarter earnings totaled $136 million, or
$1.19 per share, down from $248 million, or $2.12 per share, in the
same quarter of 1987.
   The results reflect the after-tax charge resulting from the
reorganization of Robins. The charge is in addition to reserves
previously established by Aetna for insurance obligations for
claims by users of Robins' Dalkon Shield intrauterine devices.
   Aetna's second-quarter earnings also were depressed by a $17
million capital loss and lower tax benefits in the prior year.
   Revenue rose to $6.33 billion from $5.54 billion in the second
three months of 1987.
   Aetna Chairman James T. Lynn called the results in line with the
company's expectations.
   Net income for the first six months of the year was $268
million, or $2.33 per common share, compared with $469 million, or
$4.03 per common share, for the first half of 1987.
   First-half revenue increased to $12.3 billion from $10.66
billion.
   As of June 30, 1988, Aetna's total assets were $75.7 billion, 6
percent greater than a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880729-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     07-29 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0416</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved sharply higher in
moderate trading today as gains in the bond market buoyed investor
enthusiasm for equities.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 33.60 to 2,115.93
at midafternoon.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 12 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 984 issues up, 413
down and 484 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 133.36 million shares as of 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   The Dow opened higher and advanced in a measured manner,
piercing the 2,100 level at midday. ``We'll see if this market can
hang on,'' said Peter Vandenberg, a trader at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Analysts said the gains reflected fresh strength in the bond
market. In addition, investors continued to react favorably to
comments by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who indicated
Thursday that the Fed hasn't changed monetary policy recently.
   ``Those comments encouraged people to believe interest rates are
not going to go up any further and maybe even go down,'' said
Charles Jensen, chief technical analyst at MKI Securities Corp.
   With the spotlight off interest rates, Jensen said investors
were able to turn their attention to the flood of positive
corporate earnings reports that have been pouring in over the past
few weeks.
   ``We've had very good earnings, but most of the stocks did not
participate last week'' because of fear that higher interest rates
would dilute corporate profits down the road, Jensen said.
   Much of the day's activity centered on blue-chip issues.
Strategies to capture quarterly dividends also accounted for a fair
share of overall volume.
   Technology issues, often a leading force in the stock market,
were showing strength.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, IBM was up 1| at 125];
Union Carbide, which withdrew a planned offering of 15 million
common shares, was up 1~ at 23], and Eastman Kodak was up ~ at 45{
amid rumors the company may sell its household products division
for as much as $2 billion.
   Public Service of New Mexico, which was unchanged at 15, was the
most active issue with 22 million shares changing hands as traders
moved to capture the utility's quarterly dividend.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.97 to 152.37. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index stood at 305.09, up 1.46.
</TEXT>
