<HEAD>London Stocks Finish Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices closed higher on London's Stock Exchange in
a lazy session Friday, spurred upward by a strong start on Wall
Street.
   Dealers said interest in the overall market continued to sag, as
only speculative activity in certain stocks drove the market higher.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 12.3
points, or 0.7 percent higher, at 1,853.6. Volume was a moderate
479.2 million shares, compared with 496.9 million shares Thursday.
   Dealers said the market was encouraged by Wall Street's strong
start. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 15.11 points at
2,097.44 as the London session drew to a close.
   Oil issues were higher across the board. Dealers said
independent oils were boosted on the news that Pearson PLC sold its
British oil exploration and production subsidiary, Whitehall
Petroleum Ltd., to Amerada Hess Ltd. for 94 million pounds, or $161
million in cash.
