<HEAD>Crop Futures Soar Their Limits; Corn Leads Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and sobyean futures scored their first
major advance in more than two weeks Friday, closing sharply higher
in a rebound sparked by a basketful of bullish factors.
   ``Mr. Excitement jumped in here today,'' said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst with G.H. Miller & Co. in Chicago.
   Most corn and soybean futures soared their respective daily
limits of 10 cents and 30 cents a bushel while the limitless August
soybean contract gained more than 34 cents.
   After more than a week of generally falling prices across the
board, an overnight increase in cash corn prices spurred some
hedge-type buying of corn futures by commercial grain dealers and
processors, analysts said.
   The depressed soybean market also attracted bargain hunters
while wheat gained on news of a 400,000-metric-ton sale of U.S.
wheat to China and on the Agriculture Department's decision not to
reduce for next year the portion of the acreage wheat growers must
set aside to qualify for federal price supports.
   A rumor later in the day that the Soviet Union was in the market
for corn prompted further buying of corn futures.
   A soybean production estimate of 1.56 billion bushels by
meatpacker Conagra Corp., compared to the Agriculture Department's
latest estimate of 1.65 billion bushels, added further support to
the soybeans, analysts said.
   And private weather forecasts reducing the prospects for rain
this weekend in the drought-stricken Farm Belt lent strength across
the board.
   At the close, wheat was 10 cents to 17 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.68 a bushel; corn was 6
cents to 10 cents higher with September at $2.75 a bushel; oats
were 7 cents to the limit 15 cents higher with September at $2.71{
a bushel; soybeans were 9{ cents to 34{ cents higher with August at
$7.76 a bushel.

</TEXT>
