<HEAD>Deal to Swap Cable Systems Collapses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. said a deal to trade its
cable television operations in Arizona for cable properties owned
by Tele-Communications Inc. and United Artists Communications has
collapsed.
   The decision to call off the deal, which was announced in March,
``was a mutual agreement between all three parties,'' Times Mirror,
owner of the Los Angeles Times, Newsday, and the Baltimore Sun
papers, said Thursday.
   The swap, valued by analysts at about $740 million, involved
Times Mirror's cable franchises in Phoenix, Bullhead City, Casa
Grande, Lake Havasu and Nogales, Arizona. In return, the company
was to get Tele-Communications' cable syustems in Reno and Carson
City, Nev., South Lake Tahoe, Calif., and Zanesville, Ohio; and
United Artists properties in Brookhaven, N.Y., Decatur, Ill., and
Taunton and North Attleboro, Mass.
   A separate agreement for Times Mirror to buy
Tele-Communications' cable system in Rock Island, Ill., also fell
through, the company said.
