<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Up in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices made slight gains Friday in light
trading dominated mostly by technical factors.
   Traders said activity was slowed in advance of the weekend and
in anticipation of a possible meeting next week of OPEC's pricing
committee.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude, the benchmark U.S.
grade, gained 16 cents to settle at $16.31 a barrel.
   Among refined products, the August contract for wholesale
unleaded gasoline attracted the most activity on its last day of
trading. The contract lost .21 cent to settle at 51.74 cents per
gallon, while prices for later months advanced slightly.
   The August contract for heating oil, which also expired, gained
.32 cent to 44.66 cents per gallon.
   ``You have a market that's tired of being news generated ... and
is trading flat,'' explained Greg Dreis of Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   Traders began heading to the sidelines of the volatile market
Thursday, showing reluctance to make big commitments in advance of
the Aug. 3 meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries' pricing committee.
   The Lausanne, Switzerland session is expected to deal with the
13-nation cartel's continuing overproduction problems, which have
helped depress prices.
</TEXT>
