<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv30-31   07-29 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 30-31,0758</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 30-31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Giant Japanese Bond Issue Helps Fill Triple-A Void</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese have invaded the U.S. financial
markets in a big way again.
   In Samurai style, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. issued
$500 million in 10-year notes _ one of the largest foreign bond
issues ever floated in this country, according to its underwriters.
   The July 19 issue was snapped up by U.S. institutional investors
hungry for old-fashioned, triple-A bonds, even if they aren't
American.
   With a dwindling number of triple-A U.S. corporate bonds now on
the market, analysts say there's plenty of room for ``Yankee
bonds'' issued by foreign governments and companies to raise
capital _ most of which also carry the top rating.
   ``Yankee bonds'' are issued in the United States by foreign
entities and regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   ``I don't see any kind of volume that can't be absorbed,'' said
Jim Nickelson, a senior vice president of Daiwa Securities Inc.
``There haven't been enough (triple-A) issues to really saturate
the market.''
   In recent years, a number of major U.S. banks that had enjoyed
triple-A ratings were stripped of them by the credit-rating
agencies after they took steep losses on loans to developing
countries. Some big oil companies were similarly downgraded after
the world oil price slide in 1985.
   Even more recently, the surge in corporate takeover activity in
this country has brought downgraded ratings for some blue-chip
companies that piled up their debt to pay for big acquisitions.
   ``Dwindling ranks, no question about that,'' said John Lonski,
senior economist for Moody's Investors Service, referring to the
number of triple-A U.S. companies. Moody's is one of the top rating
agencies, along with Standard & Poor's Corp.
   There are currently 13 U.S. companies with triple-A ratings from
both Moody's and Standard & Poor's, Lonski noted, down from 18 in
1981.
   The survivors include International Business Machines Corp.,
Exxon Corp., Amoco Corp., Procter & Gamble Co., Morgan Guaranty
Trust Co., Aetna Life & Casualty Co. and some of the regional
telephone companies.
   There's a peculiar irony here. Some U.S. industrial giants, like
General Motors Corp., lost their triple-A imprimaturs largely as a
result of competition from Japanese companies. Now, Japanese
conglomerates like Nippon Telegraph and Japan Air Lines are jumping
into the triple-A void with big bond issues in the United States.
   Like Nippon Telegraph, other foreign companies have been raising
capital in the United States with big bond issues. Earlier this
month, the West German Bank for Economic Progress sold $300 million
in 10-year notes in the U.S. market. And the governments of Sweden
and Finland recently issued what Daiwa's Nickelson calls ``real
barn-burners'' _ 40- and 50-year bonds that fetched high prices.
   Conservative U.S. investors ``love the Yankee bond market,''
said Larry Kreicher, an international economist and bond strategist
for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Many of the foreign bonds offer investors high-quality,
regulated securities which still sell for less than U.S. Treasury
issues, Kreicher explained. He noted that the ``Yankee'' market has
grown from $3.7 billion in 1985 to a projected $6.8 billion this
year.
   What makes the Nippon Telegraph issue noteworthy is the size of
the company as well as the magnitude of the sale. The Japanese
utility can be considered the biggest company in the world, with a
stock market value of around $300 billion.
   That's equivalent to the combined market values of these giants:
IBM, Exxon (both rated triple-A), General Electric Co., American
Telephone and Telegraph Co., Ford Motor Co., GM, Merck & Co. Inc.,
Philip Morris Companies Inc. and Du Pont, according to the
investment firm Goldman, Sachs & Co.
   The Nippon Telegraph sale was ``a museum-piece issue,'' said
Michael Lynch, a senior partner in the Global Finance Department of
Goldman, Sachs, the lead underwriter of the issue. ``It's such a
strong entity ... It's hard to extricate it from the Japanese
economy.''
   The giant utility had been part of the Japanese government until
April 1985, when the government sold 25 percent of its shares to
the public.
   Other state-owned Japanese companies that are on the drawing
boards to be privatized in the near future _ such as Japanese
National Railways and Japan Tobacco Co. _ also are strong
candidates for bond issues in the U.S. market.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 30-31</NOTE>
