<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds, Dollar, Farm Prices All Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks and bonds strengthened sharply Friday in rallies stemming
partly from the dollar's appreciation against foreign currencies,
counteracting fear of higher inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 46.40 points
to 2,128.73, the largest one-day advance since a 48.36-point gain
June 8. Broader market barometers also rose strongly.
   In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of the economy, the
Treasury's key 30-year issue rose more than $3 per $1,000 face
amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price, fell to 9.21
percent from 9.26 percent late Thursday.
   Market economists attributed part of the advances to a jump in
the dollar's value in foreign exchange trading, which increases
overseas demand for securities denominated in dollars and lessens
the prospect of sharply higher domestic inflation, a constant
source of concern to investors.
   The U.S. currency gained more than a West German pfennig to
1.87985 marks and nearly a half Japanese yen to 133.145 yen. The
gains came despite central-bank dollar selling to slow its
appreciating value.
   In other economic news Friday, the Agriculture Department said
the prices farmers received for raw products this month rose 3.6
percent from June, reflecting the drought's devastating effect on
crop and livestock production.
   The department's said higher prices for corn, soybeans and eggs
contributed most to the July increase. Lower prices for oranges,
cattle and hogs partly offset the rise in other commodities.
   Department projections earlier this month showed 1988 grain
production may be reduced by 24 percent from last year. Heat and
drought have dried pastures and forced producers to thin herds to
cut down on rising feed costs.
</TEXT>
