<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PhoneContract     07-29 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Contract,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GSA Pushes Back Deadline For New Federal Phone System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Services Administration said
Friday it has pushed back its deadline for awarding bids for an
all-new federal telephone system known as FTS 2000.
   In a brief statement, the GSA said award of the contracts,
scheduled for Sept. 30, has been delayed until the end of the year.
   Contracts on the FTS 2000 system, worth as much as $25 billion
over 10 years, were originally scheduled to have been awarded by
the end of 1987. However, that date slipped when the GSA, under
pressure from Congress, decided to split the contract, with 60
percent going to one vendor and 40 percent to another.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. has joined with the Boeing
Corp. to compete against a team consisting of US Sprint
Communications Corp. and Martin Marietta Corp.
   The GSA the latest delay was being made ``to make available
additional time for evaluating the large amount of technical and
financial bid data.''
   AT&T spokesman Herb Linnen said the company was ``very
disturbed'' by the delay.
   ``AT&T has expended significant resources to meet requests from
the GSA for information so that the agency could make good on its
commitment to meet the Sept. 30 deadline for awarding the
contract,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
