<DOCNO> AP880729-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BoeingOrders     07-29 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing Orders,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Announces Aircraft Orders Estimated At Up To $790 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. announced Thursday it had received
orders for 12 commercial jets, with a total value estimated at up
to $790 million, from a Canadian and an Australian airline.
   In addition, Rolls-Royce said Thursday that an Australian
leasing group, Ansett Worldwide Aviation Services, had converted
options on six Rolls-Royce powered Boeing 757 aircraft into firm
orders. But Boeing spokesman Tom Cole said the Seattle aerospace
company had not been able to confirm that deal yet with Ansett.
   If the Ansett order goes through, it would give Boeing its
fourth straight record year in dollar value for commercial jet
orders. Ansett had taken the options in October when it placed a
firm order for six 757s.
   Canadian Airlines International Ltd. on Thursday ordered three
747-400s and took options for three more, while Australian Airlines
ordered nine 737-400s with options for five more.
   Neither airline announced the values of their orders. But Cole
said a 747-400 sells for $115 million to $130 million, and the
smaller 737-400 for $29 million to $33 million. The orders also
include provisions for training and spare parts, which Cole said
usually boost the cost by 15 percent.
   At those prices, the Canadian Airlines' order would be worth
between $396.8 million and $448.5 million, and Australian's order
would be for $300.2 million to $341.6 million.
   So far this year, Boeing has had orders for 438 jet aircraft
worth about $19.75 billion. That compares with last year's 366 jets
worth $19.9 billion, a record for dollar value. The record for
number of jets ordered is 461 in 1978.
   Canadian Airlines is to receive its new jets from late 1990
through March 1991. It said in a news release that it will use the
new jets on Pacific routes, such as Toronto-Tokyo and
Vancouver-Hong Kong.
   The 747-400, which made its first flight last spring and is to
be delivered to its initial customer before the end of the year,
can carry up to 660 passengers, but will normally carry up to 412
to achieve an 8,200-mile range. Boeing has had 149 orders for
747-400s, and 873 orders for all versions of 747s.
   The 737-400, a stretch version of the twinjet, will seat 139 in
Australian's configuration and have a range of about 2,500 miles.
The airline is to receive the planes in 1990 and 1991.
   Australian Chairman A.E. Harris said it plans to use the planes
to start replacing its Boeing 727-200 aircraft, which it began
operating in 1970.
   Boeing has 125 orders for 737-400s. There have been more than
2,150 orders for all 737 models.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
