<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-29 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0544</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $660 million leveraged buyout of Koppers
Co.'s chemicals business has apparently hit a snag, putting a hitch
in Brian Beazer's plan to use the proceeds to help finance his $1.8
billion takeover of Koppers.
   The British industrialist, who prevailed June 1 in a bitter
takeover battle against Koppers' former management, did not deny
the rumors, which surfaced Thursday, nor would he reaffirm a
prediction he made Monday that the chemicals buyout would close
Aug. 8.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revco D.S. Inc., a giant drugstore chain,
has filed for bankruptcy protection, a month after missing a $46
million interest payment to bondholders, officials disclosed.
   Revco Chairman Boake A. Sells said Thursday the stage was set
for the reorganization filing when Revco failed to pay the interest
on $400 million in junk bonds June 15. Bondholders were demanding
payment of the principal as well as the interest.
   Revco issued the bonds to finance its $1.5 billion leveraged
buyout in late 1986. When it missed the interest payment, the Revco
buyout became the largest leveraged buyout to fail.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker has been fired
following an internal investigation into whether he traded stocks
with advance knowledge of Business Week magazine articles, the
securities firm said.
   The giant brokerage house said Thursday that William Dillon, 33,
a financial consultant in its New London, Conn., office, was
terminated after company lawyers uncovered records suggesting
stocks might have been bought and sold on tips from articles due to
be published in the mass-circulation magazine.
   The dismissal came a week after Business Week said it was
probing pre-publication trading linked to its ``Inside Wall
Street'' column.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major U.S. airlines said their after-tax profit rose
strongly in the latest quarter from a year earlier, boosted by
revenue gains generated by growth in passenger traffic.
   UAL Corp., the parent of United, the nation's largest airline,
on Thursday reported a 134 percent jump in second-quarter profit to
$124.2 million, or $5.77 a share.
   Delta, the third-largest U.S. carrier, posted a 76 percent boost
in profit in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year, to $103.28
million, or $2.11 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service began a 16-month,
$700,000 quest to lick the problem of stamps that don't stay stuck,
urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a ``seat belt
for a stamp.''
   Gordon C. Morison, a senior assistant postmaster general, made
it clear Thursday that the post office was serious about
development of a superior, water-activated adhesive.
   He said the Postal Service would spend nearly $90 million this
year for stamps, sales of which would generate about $8 billion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced Thursday as the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials rose 28.63 points to 2,082.33.
   The dollar rose against major currencies. Gold prices were mixed.
   Bond prices finished unchanged to slightly lower.
   Corn and sugar futures fell sharply while most wheat and soybean
futures slipped. Crude oil futures were little changed.
</TEXT>
