<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Prime     07-29 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Prime,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2nd-Qtr Profit Drops 54 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. said Thursday its
second-quarter earnings fell 54.1 percent despite a 73 percent
revenue rise.
   Prime said it earned $7.2 million, or 15 cents a share, in the
three months ended July 4 compared with a profit of $15.7 million,
or 32 cents a share, a year ago.
   The company reported revenues of $408.4 million for the quarter,
up from $236 million a year earlier.
   The latest results include a onetime charge of $5.1 million
after taxes for the previously-disclosed withdrawal of its
mini-supercomputer from the market.
   The 1987 figures do not include results of Computervision Inc.,
which merged with Prime in February.
   On Monday, Prime pulled its MXCL5 mini-supercomputer from the
marketplace, citing competitive pricing and a slumping market for
the action.
   In a statement, Prime President Joe M. Henson said the company
met its earnings and revenue expectations despite the charge on the
MXCL5.
   ``We're pleased that in the midst of a difficult industry
environment and our integration with Computervision, we were able
to meet our revenue and expense goals for the quarter,'' Henson
said.
   For the first six months of the year, Prime said it earned $21.7
million, or 45 cents a share, down from $27.6 million, or 56 cents
a share, a year ago.
   Six-month revenue rose to $772 million from $458 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
